1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Hello and welcome to my latest Chessable
repertoire - the White repertoire vs 1.e4 e5 based on the Italian game. Or,
rather, Dynamic Italian. What is this work about, what can you expect and why
did I create it? As you might know, I've already created a White repertoire
against the Sicilian available here on Chessable under the name 'The
Accelerated Rossolimo'. This course, together with that one, should get you
covered versus the two very main Black tries - 1.e4 c5 and 1.e4 e5! I have
been teaching privately for years, and when it comes to building the students'
repertoire after 1.e4 e5!, I have always been a little puzzled. Playing a line
like Scotch Four Knights is not a good idea as it is very unambitious. Sure,
it's easy, but it won't develop you as a player. Playing Ruy Lopez is
definitely very interesting and ambitious, but there is so much to learn. For
example, after 3.Bb5 Black already has a plethora of choices, such as 3...a6 
(the main move by far) , 3...Nf6, 3...g6, 3...d6, 3...f5 - all of those are
serious moves! Besides that, 3...d6, 3...Nge7, 3...Nd4, 3...Bc5 and others
need to be examined. And this was just a list of Black's options on move 3!
The same happens on move 4, 5, etc. So, unless you are a 2000+-rated player,
you either don't play the Ruy with the White pieces or play it while agreeing
to be totally ignorant and unaware of your surroundings, or you study all
those lines while giving up a few thousand puzzles that could be solved, a few
hundred games that could be studied carefully, etc. No good. The Italian,
instead, is a happy medium, the golden solution. Why so?  1. Black's options
are already quite limited on move 3 - there are only two good moves. There are
interesting sidelines he can throw at us, but we deal with those in the course
and I prove White should be rather happy to face them - there isn't too much
we need to learn and know by heart - instead, we typically get lovely
positions by following simple logical chess principles, such as playing
actively, fighting for the center, developing our pieces to good squares, etc.
2. White is the one to choose the pace of the game. What do I mean? Well, you
can always play Quiet Italian with d2-d3, c2-c3, Nbd2, etc. Or you can go for
one of the gambits!  3. This opening will, most importantly, improve you as a
player. Multiple interesting positions are to be reached, both tactically rich
ones as well as positionally complex ones. And, again, we are the ones
choosing what type of play we will get. Now, you might wonder why did I go for
the dynamic choices instead of the quiet ones, and why are my choices exactly
the ones presented? Why the Evans Gambit and not something else? Why 4.Ng5 and
not some other dynamic line? For one, it is important to understand there is
no theoretical advantage in 1.e4 e5!. It is a rock-solid move where Black is
always fine theoretically if he knows his stuff. So, whether we play a rare
sideline or the very mainline, Black should equalize if he is well-prepared.
But, we will make his path to equality as rocky as possible! The problem with
the quiet continuation 4.d3 is that Black has too many move orders available
to him. I love Quiet Italian positions for both sides, but I don't find them
easy to explain. To make matters worse, I find the Chessable format absolutely
unuseable for those positions. Why so? Well, Chessable is based on spaced
repetition, while in Quiet Italian, we'll have so many transpositions/
similar-looking positions that it's barely possible to take advantage of this
cool technology. Instead, when we go for the direct play - just as in this
course! - MoveTrainer will prove tremendously useful. Both Evans Gambit and 3..
.Nf6 4.Ng5 are extremely direct and straightforward. The positions do get
rather murky, but as you will be training the lines, your preparation will be
top-notch. And, there aren't any move orders Black can throw at us trying to
confuse or trick us. We won't get thrown out of book! The reason why I like
those lines chess-wise, though, not Chessable/MoveTrainer-wise, are also very
important. If you are a relatively inexperienced player, then the calm
positional play, where you are trying to slowly outmaneuver your opponent, can
be rather difficult. You may not yet understand the importance of the weak
squares/space advantage. But, by playing the lines given here, you'll be able
to get engaged in the much more dynamic concrete play, where it's all about
sacrificing, checkmating, playing for the quick development. Or, sometimes, it
might be about grabbing an extra pawn or two and trying to stabilize the
situation and slowly convert the advantage by trading down. Agree, both
scenarios lead to a very understandable play. This is a lot more useful for
your development at this point than the slow maneuvring battles. Instead, if
you are an experienced or even a titled player, the lines presented here will
serve as a great attempt at a theoretical advantage. I am sharing my own
knowledge and expertise combined with the ideas from the recent games and the
ideas given by the best engines out there - Stockfish, AsmFish, Lc0, and some
other ones. I have found tons of interesting ways to put Black under pressure
in the critical lines - of course, for you as for the more experienced players,
it won't be just about such general things as initiative and attack. It will
also be about a plethora of new plans/suggestions/move orders that challenge
Black's setups and recommendations given in books on 1.e4 e5 for Black. One
thing I love Chessable for is the fact that we have such various pool of
students here. It's not easy, though, to cater both to 1500-rated and
2300-rated players. I know that IMs and GMs study my courses diligently, but
they've also received a lot of feedback from the 1000-2000-rated players. So,
I hope that the variations given here will serve each group - in different
ways for players of different strengths, but equally usefully! Besides that,
for those of you who might find all the theory in the main lines to be
overwhelming, I've added a chapter 'Italian for beginners' where I broke down
the most important concepts and a few most basic plans that should get you up
and running. That is a bonus chapter, it has nothing to do with the rest of
the course, but instead, it's aimed at providing a very simple and
understandable weapon that you can take up and start using quickly. And, there
is a QuickStarter Guide to help the players willing to play the mainlines
immediately learn the most important variations! Good luck! This repertoire
had helped several private students of mine both in terms of winning some
specific important games and developing their chess, and I hope it would do
the same thing to you! As always, my first and foremost goal is not just to
provide you with a good opening weapon, but also to help you improve your
chess overall, so often we focus on the importance of development/fight for
the center/control of the weak squares and many other things. Hopefully, 10
model games will also help a lot and will give you a much better feel for the
arising positions and for how to handle the middlegame/endgame!  Yours, Yuriy
Krykun} *

