[White "Repertoire Clashes"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "5"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {To begin with, I would like to mention that the
name 'Repertoire Clashes', to the best of my knowledge, was used for the first
time in Daniel Barrish's courses on 1.d4, and I find that name rather cool - I
hope he doesn't mind I call this chapter this way. Now, it's time to speak
about the theoretical value of this work and about how it challenges other
authors' recommendations. It's not possible to create a good product that
brings something new and valuable unless the author consults the existing
sources and tries to improve on them. So, here are the sources I have
consulted, and here is what I have done to tackle the given recommendations. 
1. 'Unleash the Bull: 1...e5 - a full repertoire for Black' by Yuriy Krykun:
Don't worry, I am not that arrogant to put my own repertoire in the first
place ahead of books written by GMs! The reason why this goes as the very
first theoretical source, though, is because it's always difficult to
challenge your own suggestions. As an honest author, I gave the best
suggestion possible for Black in that course, so tackling it with the other
color was by no means easy. Overall, the evaluation holds true, of course:
Black is perfectly fine in the line 5.c3 Be7! 6.d4 Na5! that I have
recommended in that course. But, I did manage to expand my analysis a bit and
show how to challenge other Black moves in the critical position. In fact,
once we arrive at the most critical position where these two repertoires clash,
we can see most GMs 2600-2700 have misplayed it with Black! So, while the
students of my courses will know the right recommendation that equalizes for
Black, most players won't, which will lead them to a lot of trouble. In fact,
I was so interested in the line that I even had to update my Black course to
show additional ideas I have found for White. There is a lot of interesting
stuff!  2. 'Lifetime Repertoires: Jan Gustafsson's 1. e4 e5' by Jan Gustafsson:
Jan did a fantastic job of covering all the critical variations. Our
repertoires clash after 3...Nf6 4.Ng5, where in the critical line he briefly
mentions 8...Ng4, while his main recommendation is 8...Nd5. The line that I
gave is very rare and new and as a result, after his 10...f5!N idea, we are
immediately off to a completely unexplored position. I know that many players
will be following his analysis, so I have spent countless hours trying to
challenge his work - and I am very happy about the result! I am giving two
suggestions that try to tackle his repertoire. In one of them, White quickly
wins two pawns, but Black is better developed and is able to eventually get
them back and equalize. The first good piece of news is that White is not
risking anything at all. If Black is careful, he draws. If not, he is just
material down, and there is no attack we need to fear or something. Besides
that, another great piece of news is that Jan cut his analysis quite early.
This is understandable, as it's not possible to cover every rare line, but
this does give us reasons to be happy, as according to what I found, Black
needs to know a few more precise moves - they are not given in his course. But,
I also wanted to stay as ambitious as possible, not settling for a draw if
Black did his homework. So, I am giving another suggestion - it's not analyzed
at all in his course. Again, objectively things are equal, but the positions
are extremely complicated, and handling them won't be easy by any means - the
better-prepared players have massive odds. We have two great possibilities, as
a result: a risk-free one leading to a draw if Black knows his stuff, or a
very murky one leading to the nerve-wracking complications. It's up to you
what to choose!  3 'Two Knights Defense' by Andrey Terekhov: Another great
work, which covers the mainlines rather profoundly and suggests plenty of new
ideas. The repertoires again clash in that very critical position of the Two
Knights after 8...Nd5. The line Andrey gives is very decent, but again, he
cuts it short. He analyzes only 12 moves or so, saying Black has a very decent
compensation for the missing pawn at the end. I totally agree with the
conclusion, but I think he needs to find a few more very important moves, so
chances are my analysis will give us significant odds. Again, those authors
aren't superficial or lazy - their works are great! - it's just that the line
I am giving is rather rare and is getting popular only now, so it's not
practical on their end to dig too deep.  4. 'Bologan's Black Weapons in the
Open Games: How to Play for a Win if White Avoids the Ruy Lopez' by Victor
Bologan: Bologan is a good author, who covers both 3...Bc5 and 3...Nf6 in his
book, giving readers a nice choice. His suggestion vs 3...Bc5 is rather rare
but very decent! It is not easy for us to claim an advantage, but I think
White keeps a somewhat nicer position - and Black, again, needs to find a few
precise moves. Besides that, we also have a few ways of handling the position
there, so you do have some choice - I give plenty of choices in this course!
His suggestion versus 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 didn't satisfy me, though. He gives the
line 8...Ng4 and concludes his own analysis with the words alike 'Black is
somewhat worse in this endgame, but should hold'. Well, I didn't dream of
winning by force after 1.e4, so I am happy to be in a situation like this - an
endgame where we are playing for two results! It is strange for me to read
such words in his book, though, as it's obvious Black does have equality after
1.e4 e5! so if he couldn't find it in his line, he should have just settled
for a different line! We have two endgames available, in both White is a tiny
bit better and can press without much risk. A very enjoyable outcome.  5.
'Playing 1.e4 e5 - A Classical Repertoire by Nikolaos Ntirlis': This is one of
my favorite authors! He isn't a titled player, but he is a very good
correspondence player and his books contain a plethora of interesting ideas
and explanations. A lot to be learned! Fortunately, that's not precisely the
case when it comes to dealing with my recommendation. The reason is that the
move 10.Nc3 is rare and new like I said earlier, so it's not mentioned at all.
Actually, we can still arrive at a more popular position via a transposition,
so I did check his suggestions. But, again, they are rather brief, and I
believe nowadays it's pretty much common knowledge that the game Aronian-Ding
Liren, which is analyzed in detail both in the theoretical section as well as
in the section on Model Games, questions that variations and makes it rather
suspicious. Again, I am very happy with the result of this repertoire clash! 
6. 'The Open Games for Black' by Igor Lysyj and Roman Ovetchkin. This was,
surprisingly, a very hard nut to crack. The word surprising does not refer to
the authors' playing strength or analytical skills - they are very strong GMs
and good authors. The reason why I expected this to be a lot easier is that
the book was published in 2012, and 8 years is a huge amount of time, given
how fast the engines are getting better and the fact the Lc0 and Fat Fritz
made an appearance only very recently. But, their analysis in that Evans line
with 5...Ba5 6.d4 d6 7.Qb3 Qe7 is truly top-notch. The good news is that both
they and I agree that the final positions are very interesting, we think that
Evans definitely deserves a lot more attention than it has been having. And,
in the rather long but pretty forcing and important theoretical line, I have
managed to find a very promising novelty 16.Re1!, which puts Black under a
certain amount of pressure and forces him to solve serious practical problems.
According to the engine, this is 0.00, which refers to 'A dead draw, you dumb
human being'. But, joking and self-criticizing aside, the final position is
very interesting and rich in possibilities. Black keeps two extra pawns, but
White's pieces are extremely active and his attack can get very strong. I
definitely think chances are on White's side in a practical game. And, again,
it's not very likely Black will find all those precise moves that lead him to
that position. Another happy outcome while tackling a great book written by a
2700-rated GM. There are a few other sources I have consulted, but they are
either less significant or give lines similar to the ones discussed above, so
I've decided to cut this list short here in order not to make this incredibly
lengthy!  Cheers, Yuriy} *

