1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {This is a pretty new thing to me, which I suggest
you all don't rely on 100%, but use it as a helpful piece of advice. I have
put tons of love and effort into this course and firmly believe it can prove
equally beneficial to both 1500-rated and 2500-rated players. This is a bold
claim, isn't it? But, of course, players from very different rating pools,
with different strengths and different opposition need to use this course in
different ways to take maximum advantage out of it. So, after pondering for a
while, I've decided to come up with suggestions on how players of different
levels should study this repertoire. Feel free to improvise and ignore my
advice, though! Obviously, the most logical way to read a book is to start on
page 1 and finish on the last page. Fair enough? Sure. But, what if you are
reading an encyclopedia? I guess you'd rather force your way to the page/topic
you need while ignoring the rest for a while? As I said, I've tried to make
sure the material in this book will be adequate and user-friendly for
relatively inexperienced players, but also, I wanted to cater to numerous IMs
and GMs who have been studying my courses and that I have had feedback from.
If you are a beginner, you can take maximum advantage of this course by
studying the chapter 'Italian for beginners'. A fairly logical suggestion,
isn't it? Your main goal in the opening should be to get up and running and
avoid blundering pieces in the upcoming middlegame/endgame. Of course, knowing
some typical ideas really helps. If you are rated between, say, 1400-1800,
your main focus should be on the chapters devoted to Black's sidelines on move
3 man, those folks play 3...d6, 3...h6, 3...g6 and stuff a lot! - my students
will wholeheartedly confirm!, to the sidelines of the Evans (they will often
go to the wrong square with the bishop or commit typical mistakes and run into
some decisive attack) as well as sidelines of the 3...Nf6 4.Ng5, such as 4...
Bc5, 4...d5 5.exd5 Nxd5?, etc. Do look around the mainlines, but I would
rather use this course as a reference/train the lines you've been facing. Did
you see some serious move? Use your brain! You've finished the game, look at
the line and explanations. It could also be a good idea to look at more lines
in the reading mode but don't rote-learn too many. It's tedious and you won't
benefit immensely from so much learning. If you are a player between 1800-2200,
you are likely to still be facing the sidelines, but your level should suffice
to figure out what the good responses are. Of course, it's great to use the
course to a huge advantage while preparing against some OTB opponent who is
known for playing a specific line. But at this point, knowing more mainlines
will really help! In Evans, your opponents are likely to know good defenses.
They won't blunder 3...Nf6 4.Ng5 d5 5.exd5 Nxd5? anymore. It is still useful
to know how to react to that stuff, but gaining a better idea about the
mainlines - both idea-wise and theory-wise! is really helpful. That's the
level where you are already able to retain a lot of information/theoretical
lines in your mind and take advantage of the opponents' wrongdoings and
deviations. If you are 2200+, all the way up to 2700, you might nearly ignore
the sidelines, or browse through quickly. Do concentrate on mainlines. Do some
work on your own and check stuff with databases. I am totally confident in the
quality of my work, but I think once you get to a really high competitive
level, the best piece of advice regarding any books/analysis by anyone else
goes 'trust but verify'. But, here I should already stop talking, as at this
level you are likely to know well what works best for your chess and what
doesn't! I have done plenty of opening work and opening preparation assistance
to 2500-2650+ players in the past years and I am totally confident that these
lines, especially the 3...Nf6 4.Ng5! variations, primarily the main chapter,
are extremely strong and challenging theoretically. They are good enough to
put an opponent of any level under a lot of pressure, both analytically and
practically. But, I have always been voting and vouching for common sense in
chess, and the idea of rote-memorizing dozens and hundreds of lines without
distinguishing clearly which ones are rare and which ones are important, which
ones are complicated and which ones are not too difficult, always seemed
foreign and alien to me. So, I have written this guide to help the users by
sharing my perspective. I know this is just an opinion - if you want to, you
are very welcome to study the entire thing. I have put hundreds of hours in
the analysis and would be glad to have as many of you as possible study the
course. But, first and foremost, I wish you much practical success over the
board, which is something you cannot achieve without a healthy and practical
approach.  Cheers, Yuriy} *

