1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Now, we are going to analyze Black's sidelines on
move 3. Some of them, such as 3...Be7 and 3...g6, actually make a lot of sense,
even though those clearly aren't the best moves available out there. On the
other hand, some moves, such as 3...d6, 3...h6, and so on, clearly don't
deserve too much attention, but I did want to cover them anyway because my
private students of the club level face them a lot when opponents either don't
know the theory or want to avoid the theoretical battle. Logically, it's fair
enough to expect that if you are a club player, you'll encounter them a bunch,
too. We are not going to be discussing all the aforementioned moves in the
QuickStarter, but I did want to mention them all anyway. Of course, you can
find comprehensive coverage of all of them in the actual chapter devoted to
sidelines. The good news is that White is able to keep the advantage in all
those lines without knowing too much or without making the play sharp and
unpredictable. The bad news is...wait, why did I say that? Well, usually after
the words 'the good news' they follow with 'but' or 'here's the problem,
though'. Not this time - this time we just enjoy the easy advantage. Remember
the rule of thumb: in most cases, passive moves in this position are punished
by the active d2-d4! which yields White the space advantage, as we will see in
numerous variations.} Bc5 (3... d6 {This is another rather passive move.
However, as we will see, it's not a very easy one to refute! The fact that it
was played by Ivanchuk in the past and by Paravyan and Gledura recently,
should give you an idea that it's a fairly decent continuation, in fact. At
this point, I also like the dynamic continuation.} 4. d4 Bg4 5. h3 {Many
students of mine get naturally scared of this pin, which is understandable.
But, in fact, White is nearly winning here.} Bh5 {A very important move that
truly punishes Black's play, as the d4-pawn isn't hanging at all.} 6. d5 Nb8 7.
g4 {Black has to retreat in this way, which is rather passive. Now, White is
able to obtain large advantage thanks to his extra space rather effortlessly.}
Bg6 8. Nc3 {The bishop is extremely misplaced and passive on g6, White is much
better.}) (3... Be7 {I am going to mark this move as a fairly interesting one,
because while it's clearly inferior to the main guys 3...Bc5 and 3...Nf6, it
does have some interesting ideas behind it. For one, if White were to play 4.
d3 here, Black could go 4...Nf6!, getting back to the 4...Nf6 Italians while
avoiding the Two Knights with 4.Ng5. Pretty clever, isn't it ? Even Magnus
tried it in a rapid game in 2018, and it was occasionally essayed by Jobava,
Laznicka, Bacrot, and others. I can definitely relate to the ideas and reasons
why strong players might want to try such continuation: it avoids the sharp
lines like 4.Ng5 or 4.d4 where White is likely to just make a draw if he
wishes to and did his homework well, as well as the 3...Bc5 4.c3/d4 stuff,
where White can also try to simplify the game and make a draw. Obviously,
that's not what we're gonna be doing in this course - we are playing for a win
- but stronger players might try this against you to just get a game without
compromising their position too much. Of course, such luxury comes at a price,
though.} 4. d4 {Again, the same piece of advice. When in doubt while facing
the passive 3rd moves, go for this central advance!} d6 {This is definitely
the most popular move and the key point behind Black's choice on move 3. He is
trying to claim that 5.d5 leads to a position where White has somewhat more
space, but the bishop is misplaced on c4. And, very importantly, the positions
are very atypical of the Italian - that is definitely a good enough reason
against this move, already. In the endgame after 5.dxe5, though, Black also
pretends he's doing fine. That position is definitely solid, but I think White
is surely able to keep some very neat pressure.} 5. dxe5 dxe5 6. Qxd8+ {
Now, Black seemingly has several ways of recapturing, but once you look more
attentively, it becomes obvious only one recapture is possible.} Bxd8 7. Nc3 {
Now, let us discuss the arising position. What are White's goals and how can
he be better? For one, it's a very symmetrical position, isn't it. In such
situations, it is not possible to count on the advantage thanks to the extra
space or the better structure, as the word 'symmetrical' in the description of
the pawn structure strongly suggests. So, the main factor involved is the
activity and development, as well as the possibility to start creating threats.
Let's understand White's advantages and goals:  1 He is better developed.  2
He is easily able to castle long - this is very important as it will enable
him to join the game quickly with his a1-rook.  3 He is able to control both
key diagonals. Now, this part might require further explanation. I believe
that in many symmetrical structure, such as the French Exchange, or this
structure, where the d-pawns get exchanged, there are two key diagonals. In
this case, it's a2-g8 and g1-a7. The reason is that the bishops are placed
best exactly there as they are able to control several important squares. So,
White already controls a2-g8, as Black shouldn't be too willing to go ...Be6
as that will compomise his pawn structure. On the other hand, while we don't
control g1-a7 yet, we inevitably will, as we are about to go Be3, stopping ...
Bc5.  4 It is likely that due to the superior activity of our pieces, we will
be able to create dynamic threats, which will result either in the structural
changes which are supposed to be favorable for us, or in material gains. For
example, we can play Nd5, keeping the Black bishop stuck on d8. That will
force Black to either tolerate the very strong knight, or trade it, which will
either enable us to get the bishop pair if Black takes with the bishop, or,
possibly, take exd5 and put more pressure on the e5-pawn. Another very
important thing is that Black cannot castle long here, or, at least, this
won't be easy at all. Now, the issue is that castling short is dangerous
strategically as it will drive the king too far away from the center, while
staying in the center is dangerous, because even though this is a queenless
middlegame, there are a lot of pieces and the king might run into some checks/
pins/attack.  Finally, let's start discussing the Black moves. I believe it's
not as much about the moves, as it is about plans, so let's focus on Black's
very main contrinuation ...Nf6, while briefly mentioning minor tries.} Nf6 (
7... f6 {I am not a fan of this move which was played by Hebden and Galego,
both 2500+ players. The idea is to protect the e5-pawn and prepare the move ...
Na5! Now, because Black just weakened the a2-g8 diagonal, it makes sense to
keep the bishop there, so I like the very logical continuation} 8. a3 {Very
important! The bishop is now ready to retreat to a2 in the event of ...Na5.}
Nge7 9. Be3 Ng6 10. O-O-O Nf8 {Black is forced to spend a lot of time in order
to prepare ...Be6, obstructing the a2-g8 diagonal.} 11. Nd2 {This is a very
nice move. The ideas include protecting the c4-bishop as well as possibly
preparing f2-f4! Why is f2-f4 potentially strong if it might spoil our
structure? Well, we are much better developed, so we need to open the position
up!} a6 12. Nb3 {Is an even better move, preparing Nc5 and Nd5 and opening up
the d-file.} Be6 13. Nd5 Ne7 14. Nc5 {Black's position is terrible.}) 8. Be3 {
We continue the logical development. Now, Black has a few choices - not even
move-wise, but regarding the character of the arising position. Say, ...Be6
will give him the doubled pawns, while castling will drive his king away from
the center. Some other moves, instead, such as ...Be7, keep the tension for
now. So, we should discuss all those scenarios.} O-O {This is the most popular
move and the one I call a nearly losing mistake! Be careful and attentive as
this is your chance to punish those guys.} 9. Bc5 Re8 10. Ng5 {This is it.
Black has to go ...Be6 and get only a knight for that bishop as well as a
handful of weaknesses.} Be6 11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bb5 {Another excellent move,
which was found in most games. The idea is to take on c6, and this cannot be
stopped.} Be7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Bxe7 Rxe7 15. O-O-O {This is it. The position
here is not just somewhat better, it is completely resignable for Black. Why
so? He has too many pawn weaknesses. Way too many. For example, the plan of
Rd2/d3 followed by doubling rooks on the d-file, playing f2-f3, and then
re-routing our knight via a4 to c5, or via d1 and e3 to c4 should suffice, as
one of the Black pawns will inevitably fall. Just for your record, White
scored 12/12 from here.}) (3... h6 {This move clearly isn't best. It does
serve the purpose of taking the g5-square under control, though.} 4. d4 {
This is very typical. When allowed, we grab that center and challenge that
e5-pawn.} exd4 5. Nxd4 {At this point, many moves are possible, but we won't
go too deep. I would like to mention a few things, though: 1 If we compare
this with the Scotch Game, which arises after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.d4 exd4 4.
Nxd4, White is kind of a tempo up, as he has the additional move Bc4, while
Black has played ...h7-h6. I think the difference is clearly in our favor.
White now simply has more space and Black also needs to watch out for some
typical dynamic problems, for example} d6 {Maybe that is the most solid move,
as it stops the e4-e5 ideas. But Black won't be able to develop anyway.} 6. O-O
Nf6 {Now after the simple Nc3 or Re1 White's advantage is large and stable,
but it's even more tempting to opt for the forcing choice.} 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. e5
{Black's position is falling apart because taking on e5 is barely possible.}
dxe5 9. Bxf7+ Ke7 10. Bb3 {I am being rather harsh evaluation-wise, but indeed,
this is just lost. Black's coordination is terrible and he's got plenty of
weaknesses - it is a good time to cut the analysis short.}) (3... Nf6 4. Ng5 {
Welcome to the second part of this repertoire - the romantic Two Knights with
4.Ng5! This is definitely an extremely interesting line, which I chose for
several reasons. First of all, I firmly believe it's a very ambitious attempt
where White has good chances for the opening advantage. Obviously, 1.e4 e5! is
a rock-solid defense which I love from the Black side, too. But, while Black
should clearly be able to equalize in all the lines after 1.e4 e5, and often
in many ways, this move is something that would force him to know as much as
possible. This suggestion of mine clearly fits well with what I am
recommending against 3...Bc5. Also, a very important consideration I had in
mind while making this repertoire is that since this is a Chessable course -
exactly a Chessable course, and not some random DVD or something - we need to
make the maximum use of MoveTrainer technology. In the sharp line, this tool
will serve us best! This chapter is devoted to all the sidelines Black can try
and throw at us, starting from 4...Bc5 and 4...d5 5.exd5 Nxd5 to 5...b5, 5...
Nd4, etc. The main position of the 4.Ng5 line, which arises after 4...d5 5.
exd5 Na5 6.Bb5+ c6 7.dxc6 bxc6 will be covered in the following chapters.
Since this chapter is devoted to Black's sidelines, it is obvious that we will
be able to keep an advantage - often, even get a winning position after the
opening! - but some lines are rather tricky and require a rather careful
handling, so be attentive! Let's dive in.} d5 5. exd5 {Now, 5...Na5 is the
very main line and the only sound move. But, we also need to refute a handful
of other possibilities, such as 5...Nxd5, 5...b5, and 5...Nd4.} Na5 {Finally
we get to the main line! We will discuss Black's very main continuations in
the following chapters, but now we'll already start analyzing this move, or
more precisely, Black's minor tries in it. What's the idea of going to the
edge with the knight? Well, as we saw, Black cannot afford to take on d5 right
away. So, he hopes to drive the White bishop somewhere back and capture the
pawn later. But, the issue is that is allows for a nasty check.} (5... b5 {
This is known to be bad if White reacts carefully.} 6. Bf1 {The point is that
if Black takes with the queen, he won't attack both the bishop and the pawn
see what happens after 6.Bxb5 which would enable us to win the time with Nc3!,
attacking both the b5-pawn and his queen. Instead, if he were to take with the
knight, the queen won't be able to come to d5 anymore, and we again with the
b5-pawn under the much more favorable circumstances.} Nd4 {The most popular
move and Black's trickiest attempt. Now he's protecting the b5-pawn and is
about to grab the one on d5. Our g5-knight is also going to be rather
misplaced unless we make immediate use of it, or unless we challenge Black's
idea right now somehow.} 7. c3 {We attack the knight, because it cannot
retreat as the b5-pawn would be lost.} Nxd5 8. cxd4 Qxg5 9. Bxb5+ Kd8 {This
was all very forced, as both sides were just grabbing the opponent's
unprotected pieces. Interestingly, this line is being tried by IMs and GMs
once in a while. For example, Duda played it versus Wei Yi at the World Junior
Championship in 2014; Georgiev gave it a go versus Saris. But, nowadays the
computers got a lot better and it is rather easy to find out what the right
way for White is.} 10. O-O {Most GMs preferred 10.Qf3, but this is better as
we are making a vital move, to begin with, and don't decide yet where our
queen would go.} Bb7 11. Qf3 {We stop all the ...Nf4 sort of tricks which
could have hurt our king badly.} Rb8 {Black protects the bishop, again
enabling all the knight jumps. Here, in order to keep the advantage, we need
to find the brave} 12. dxe5 {The point is that we threaten to just go d2-d4,
building a tremendous center and kicking the Black queen away, while not being
afraid of any knight jumps.} Ne3 {Unless Black makes this move, he is just
lost.} 13. Qh3 {While this might seem really complicated - indeed, the
position isn't the cleanest one out there! - it was all seen in more than 70
games. Now the mate on d7 is threatened and the Black knight is hanging, so he
is forced to trade queens.} Qxg2+ 14. Qxg2 Nxg2 15. d4 Nh4 {The last trick -
now we don't want to blunder ...Nf3+!} 16. Bg5+ {We immediately trade that
knight!} Be7 17. Bxh4 Bxh4 18. b3 {Okay, the dust had settled and we are just
a pawn up for no compensation. Later, we will try to trade the bishops with
Bd3-e4, depriving Black of the bishop pair. This is just a position with an
extra pawn, which is the price we get for navigating through all those
complications successfully and carefully!}) (5... Nxd5 {This move is known to
be bad for a long time. Actually, 6.Nxf7 has been known to be the refutation
for hundreds of years and it even obtained the meaty name 'The Fried Liver
Attack'. But, I think another continuation is even better and it requires less
memorization. While 6.Nxf7 is by all means very attractive is strong, it's
even easier to kill Black with another move while also cutting down on some
work. Be very careful, because especially if you're a club player, this is the
mistake you'll face PLENTY!} 6. d4 {We are immediately opening up the center.
Another important thing is that we are protecting the g5-knight, thus creating
threats like Qf3, hitting the f7-pawn and the d5-knight.} Be7 {Black's second
popular move, which also runs in a typical sacrifice.} 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Qf3+ Ke6
{Other moves aren't critical at all - this way Black, at least, protects his
knight on d5.} 9. Nc3 {We attack that knight one more time.} Ncb4 10. O-O {
Now we just finish the development. Now the plan is to keep developing and
opening the position, while the instant threat is a2-a3, forcing the Black
knight away and winning the d5-knight.} c6 11. a3 {We force the knight away.
Now, two options are possible - either retreating back to a6, or courageously
taking the c2-pawn.} Nxc2 12. dxe5 {White couldn't care less about the a1-rook
as his goal is to open up the position and to win that d5-knight, which would
make us a huge step closer towards the main idea - mating the Black king!} Nxa1
13. Rd1 Nc2 14. Nxd5 {Now the Black king is getting slaughtered instantly, for
example} cxd5 15. Bxd5+ Kxe5 16. Qf4# {Mate! This is quite deserved when your
king keeps walking around in the middle of the board for many moves!}) 6. Bb5+
{Now, Black's absolutely main move is 6...c6, which we'll be discussing in the
next chapters. Here, we are going to analyze an interesting sideline that many
strong GMs have tried, so don't take that move too lightly!} c6 {Finally we
get to discuss the mainline of Two Knights with 4.Ng5, where Black sacrifices
a pawn, hoping to get significant compensation as we are spending a few moves
to grab it.} (6... Bd7 {If I were to list the players who gave this move a try,
we'd need a few pages. Just to mention a few most eminent ones: Naiditsch,
Postny, Beliavsky, Predojevic, Sokolov, Nunn, and many others. What is Black's
idea? The thing is that the mainline, 6...c6, implies a pawn sacrifice. Here
Black is saying that if the White bishop retreats, he'll easily and safely
capture the d5-pawn. Instead, if we take on d7, holding on to the pawn won't
be easy, either. But, his idea has one shortcoming, which is kind of sad as I
was very interested in this line from Black's perspective for a while, but on
the other hand, fair, as it's clear you cannot just avoid all that mainline
theory without giving something up.} 7. Qe2 {This is a very important move as
we protect the bishop while also attacking the e5-pawn. Now, Black faces a
choice. Most strong GMs continued 7...Be7, but the slightly more popular move
among the entire pool of players has been 7...Bd6, protecting the e5-pawn,
which is somewhat more natural. We also need to check the naive 7...Bxb5, even
though that's just terrible.} Be7 {This is a very cool idea which almost works
- Black just wants to develop and get the d5-pawn back. And, of course, his
e5-pawn isn't hanging at the moment. The idea of Black, or rather his
compensation, is clearly shown if we take on d7 and then on e5.} 8. Nf3 {
This is a rare idea which I consider White's most promising continuation, and
the easiest one! Now, Black has a choice - he can either capture the d5-pawn
immediately or castle first. The latter has been the most popular continuation,
and that's the move I am somewhat skeptical about as it feels like Black
should act faster to prove compensation.} Nxd5 {This is a bit more forcing as
Black might try to save a tempo on castling, or try to start with a slightly
different move.} 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nxe5 Qe6 {This is the idea - we are
prevented from castling because of the pin over the e-file, as then ...f7-f6 !
would win our knight.} 11. d3 {We would like to just play Nf3 now, in order to
offer the queen trade. For example, after} O-O 12. Nf3 {Black needs to either
accept the queen trade, which clearly isn't a challenging continuation for us
at all or avoid it, which gets us into positions very similar to the ones that
arise in the line with 8...0-0. He does have one funny attempt, though, which
is} Bb4+ 13. c3 Qa6 {We definitely don't want to blunder any ...Re8-related
stuff.} 14. O-O {The easiest.} Nb3 {This was the idea - the queen on a6
suddenly proves useful. Realistically though, you shouldn't expect such nifty
tricks in real OTB chess, as the only game that reached this position was a
correspondence one. But, I definitely wanted to show you the line which I
consider Black's best try.} 15. cxb4 Nxa1 16. Na3 {The knight on a1 is stuck
and will be lost soon.} Nxb4 17. Be3 Qxd3 18. Qxd3 Nxd3 19. Rxa1 Nxb2 {With 19
brilliant moves, Black managed to make it in the endgame where we have two
pieces for a rook and two pawns, but it's a significantly better position for
White as after} 20. Rb1 {He wins the b7-pawn. Now Black still has the tricks,
such as} Rfd8 {threatening the rook trade on d1.} 21. Nd2 Na4 22. Rxb7 Nc3 {
Now we can either have the a7-pawn or the c7-pawn, in either case, we keep
some steady advantage, but with precise play, Black should hold. Well, okay,
if your opponent finds more than 20 amazing moves, and you still get to press
him in the arising endgame, I think this can be called a rather thorough
opening preparation, can't it?} 23. Nac4 Nxa2 24. Bxa7 {White pieces are
clearly more useful as the Black rooks are dominated and have no open files,
while his knight on a2 is also very misplaced. The c7-pawn is also about to be
lost, which would lead us to a position where the engine should hold a
fortress on the same flank, but the human player is likely not to be able to
withstand the upcoming 100-move-long pressure. This has been one of the best
lines for Black you can find in this chapter!}) 7. dxc6 bxc6 8. Bd3 {This
slightly ugly-looking move is my recommendation in this position. But, it's
not a fruit of my imagination - in fact, this idea has been already enjoying a
great reputation for years, and while it's not the most popular move in the
entire pool of games, it is definitely the move top-players choose most
frequently whenever they reach this position. What is the point? Why does the
bishop go to this weird square, obstructing the d2-pawn and thus all the
queenside pieces, instead of the more natural square on e2? The reason lies in
the position of our g5-knight. Black can choose to kick it around and in many
lines, we want to retreat to e4, so we need our bishop to be protecting that
square. Now, the main move and the best move by Black, which has been given in
their 1.e4 e5! repertoires by such great analysts as Jan Gustafsson and
Nikolaos Ntrilis. That's the move I've played with Black on many occasions,
too, and I definitely think that's his best choice. But, there are several
other continuations available, such as 8...h6, 8...Ng4 (Bologan's choice in
his book) and 8...Bc5. Black has other moves as well - 8...Be7, 8...Bg4, etc,
but they clearly are inferior to those three. Actually, I am able to assume
that Black might be able to equalize with perfect play in some of the lines
given in this chapter, but I definitely think it'll be way more difficult than
after 8...Nd5.} Nd5 {Finally, we reach the very main position of the whole 4.
Ng5 complex, which arises after this precise reply 8...Nd5! I would like to
warn you in advance that most of the arising positions are extremely messy and
complicated and involve a great deal of risk for both players - but as known,
the higher the risk, the higher the potential reward. And we are going to be
very well-prepared for taking that risk! Black is immediately attacking the
g5-knight while also bringing his knight to the lovely central square - soon
he will try to play ...Nf4. In my opinion, White has three very promising
ideas here. One is to go 9.h4 - a move that Ntirlis in his excellent book
calls critical. I also think it is very interesting, but it leads to some
absolutely insane complications. Another ambitious line is 9.Nf3 Bd6 10.0-0,
which is the very main continuation. It is definitely the richest line in this
position, which leads to some very interesting battles, where Black is
typically a pawn down, but White gets that cramped pawn structure and Black
enjoys serious compensation. As I mention in several places, one thing I
particularly enjoy about Chessable is the diversity of the students of the
courses. I know IMs and GMs have been studying my courses diligently; so have
amateurs and people who only play online. Of course, if you are a less
experienced player, my recommendation (just one line) is going to be more than
enough. If you are a more experienced player, though, you might be curious to
look around and to see what other ideas are available. Since I have no clue
who you, dear reader, are, and what your ambitions are, I thought I'd mention
those two options - either to enable you to save the time on the search, so
that you can start to investigate additional critical options on your own, or
so that you just enjoy hearing a bit more information about this variation and
the history of its development. Finally, I have decided to stick to the third
option, which is an extremely fresh idea, used by Van Foreest in this year's
Tata Steel against no less than Mr.Carlsen. This variation, although it leads
to equality - just as all others, ultimately! - was good enough to set the
World Champion on the verge of a loss. Hopefully, the preparation of the
players you'll be facing won't be much better than the one of the World
Champion! Now, let me mention a few theoretical sources for Black that we are
dealing with here.  1 Jan Gustafsson's Lifetime Repertoires 1.e4 e5! on
Chessable; I have managed to find a new idea that he hasn't covered in his
course. I do think his recommendation is the most forcing and critical test of
my suggestion for White, but we will be able to pose problems - and yeah, fair
enough, if Black is playing perfectly, it is going to be a draw.  2 Ntirlis's
'Playing 1.e4 e5' book, published by Quality Chess; Here's what happened:
Ntirlis did some high-quality extensive analysis of all the mainlines, but my
move appeared in the tournament play only very recently and is very rare, so
it's not discussed in his book at all! To be fair, he is discussing one line
that we can get via our move order as well, but it got some very superficial
coverage and the most critical idea for White wasn't mentioned. Good news for
us, as he's an excellent analyst and many people follow what he recommends in
his book, they won't be prepared to meet this repertoire!  3 Andrey Terekhov's
excellent course on two knights here on Chessable; Before I proceed to discuss
what's going on with that repertoire, I'd like to say a few words about its
author. I've known Andrey since 2013, when, interestingly enough, I - an
unrated player back then! - faced him in an OTB tournament in Kiev, as we were
both living in Ukraine back then. I've had an excellent tournament and got my
first FIDE rating of 2050 or so, but he beat me in a rather one-sided way,
showing I had a lot to learn. The reason why I am discussing him is that I
found him a very interesting person and a model presentation for the non-chess
world, what a chess player should look like. Having become an FM, he has
managed to pursue a highly successful career at Microsoft while also being an
all-round intelligent person with various interests as well as a rather
talented author. So, for me to see that he had published a Chessable course
wasn't just something interesting chess-wise, as I knew immediately the
quality of the content would be impeccable, but also, I just felt good about
hearing his name again and checking out his recent writing. Now that you might
be a little bored with my background and all these stories, let's return to
the chess part. Having said many good words about Andrey Terekhov, I now feel
obliged to challenge his theoretical conclusions in order not to sound biased!
Andrey mentions Gustafsson's suggestion in his course while also giving one of
his own - 10.Nc3 0-0 11.Be2 f5. This is also a rather good move and we will
deal with it in this chapter, too.} (8... h6 {The second popular move which is
rather popular at a club/ tournament level, yet it is also being occasionally
used by likes of Caruana, Bacrot, Sokolov, and many other notable GMs. So, we
clearly need to check it seriously.} 9. Ne4 Nd5 {This is the idea behind
Black's last move - he is preparing to play ...Nf4. The whole point is that
had he started with 8...Nd5, which is the main move that we are about to
discuss in the following chapters, White would be able to retreat to f3 with
his knight, while after 8...h6 9.Nf3?? e4! White would just lose a piece.} 10.
O-O {Now, we need to discuss two moves - the main 10...Be7 and the sidelines
10...Nf4. It's also important that we want to castle as quickly as possible;
Levon Aronian chose 10.Nbc3 against Caruana, which was fine, but less precise
as after ...Nf4! the g2-pawn was hanging.} Be7 {At this point, we need to make
one very important move. Black might want to push ...f7-f5 at some point
sooner or later in order to grab space in the center/on the kingside. So, we
stop that idea.} 11. Ng3 O-O {Now Black is again ready to push ...f7-f5.} 12.
Bf5 {Another key move - we want to trade the bishops. Not only are we a pawn
up, but also Black has somewhat more space in such positions, so trading is
twice as beneficial for us. At this point, I think all the moves but one allow
for the trade and aren't interesting at all - we simply trade the bishops,
play d2-d3, Nc3 or Nd2, develop the queenside pieces (remember about the idea
Nb1-d2-b3!) and convert our extra pawn.} Ba6 {I can't say this is the best
move objectively, as maybe Black should already accept the fact he's a pawn
down and his position is bad. But, this is definitely the most principled
continuation, as Black avoids the undesirable trade and tries to create some
threats. It also led Black to success in a high-profile game between the late
Igor Kurnosov - what an insanely gifted player he was! - and Ernesto Inarkiev.}
13. d3 c5 {At this point, White reacted quite well, but it would have been
even better to simply offer the knight trade. 0-1 (57) Kurnosov,I (2657) -
Inarkiev,E (2680) Khanty-Mansiysk 2013} 14. Nc3 {Black's problem is that he
cannot really turn down this offer, as} Nf6 15. Nce4 {White is being quite
persistent. We trade those guys and can either play for simplifications or go
for the kingside attack with such ideas as Qg4/h5, possibly intending some
sacrifices like Bxh6. The engine already claims White is just winning, I'd
give the slightly more modest evaluation as the position is still complicated,
but it's definitely a hugely favorable situation for us!}) (8... Ng4 {
Bologan's suggestion and something that Grischuk played recently vs Vitiugov 
(July 2019, Grand Prix). Black immediately attacks our g5-knight. In this
chapter, this is definitely the best move available to Black.} 9. Ne4 f5 {
That's the idea behind Black's last move - he is just attacking our knight,
hoping it would retreat, which would enable him to get some very strong
initiative with ...e5-e4!} 10. Be2 h5 11. h3 {Black is forced into a tunnel
variation now.} fxe4 12. hxg4 Bc5 {The right move, putting more pressure on f2,
and the only move that has ever been played. Now, the game is developing in a
very forcing manner, but White has two promising continuations.} 13. b4 {
This is one of them and the one I am recommending, as it's the cleanest
solution, in my opinion. What's the point behind this pawn sacrifice?} Qd4 {
Black has to decline the sacrifice and grab our rook on a1 instead. Now Jan in
his 'Lifetime Repertoire' quotes the following extremely forcing line.} 14.
bxc5 O-O 15. O-O Qxa1 16. Nc3 {The queen on a1 is now paralyzed, it has no
moves.} e3 {Jan says that's the move that made him interested in the whole
thing with 8...Ng4.} 17. gxh5 exf2+ 18. Rxf2 Rxf2 19. Kxf2 Be6 {At this point,
Jan analyzes moves 20.Bf3, as was played between Stellwagen and L'Ami (2 games
in the database) and 20.Ba3 (420 games, including the correspondence ones, of
course), saying the latter should be a draw. I also think it should be a draw
if Black knows everything perfectly, but White is still pressing in the
arising position.} 20. Ba3 Qxd1 21. Bxd1 Rf8+ 22. Ke1 {For some reason, Jan
analyzes only 22.Kg3, which I believe is weaker. But, it's understandable he
doesn't want to go into some tremendous amount of detail as his main
recommendation is 8...Nd5, while this line is just something he mentions for
fun. Something I don't understand, though, is why Bologan analyzes only 22.Kg3,
as it's his main (and only!) recommendation versus 8.Bd3!, he should have
investigated the position more deeply! What can we say about this endgame?
White has two pawns for the exchange and a bishop pair as well. Black's pawn
structure is rather damaged and ruined - all of his pawns are weak! His knight
on a5 is also out of business. In a similar position (not this one) Jan
suggests the plan of Na5-b7-d8-f7, which makes perfect sense. Yet, this
definitely isn't fast enough and White should be able to obtain a clear
advantage.} Nb7 23. d3 Nd8 24. Bc1 {Now it's a good time to activate the
bishop as it wasn't doing anything on a3.} Nf7 25. Bf3 {Now the c6-pawn is a
problem. We are already very deep in the line, so I won't analyze several
continuations available to Black, let me just give you a few more moves.} Nh6 {
Black is improving his knight's position.} 26. Bxc6 Rc8 27. Be4 Rxc5 28. Kd2 {
White is clearly pressing in this endgame. His ideas include a2-a4, Ba3, Nd5,
possibly Bb2 if the rook is forced off the first rank. It's very important
that the Black rook cannot find a good use for itself as there aren't many
open files, and the existing open files don't offer any good entrance squares/
targets for that rook.}) 9. Nf3 Bd6 (9... Nf4 {Before we dive in the
complications after the main move 9...Bd6, let's first look at this sideline.
Now it's very important to be careful, as 10.0-0 Bd6 transposes to the
mainline 9...Bd6 10.0-0, while we prefer the move order 10.Nc3!} 10. Bf1 {
In my opinion, this is clearly the best move which comes close to refuting the
somewhat sloppy 9...Nf4. Now Black doesn't get to take on d3 and we are about
to play either d2-d3 with the idea of Bxf4, or even d2-d4!, opening up the
center, as the e5-pawn is the only defender of that unstable knight.} Bd6 11.
d4 {The obvious threat is dxe5 where White will not only attack the d6-bishop,
but the f4-knight, too.} exd4 12. Qxd4 {Now the f4-knight is forced out.} Ne6
13. Qd1 O-O 14. Bd3 {This is just a free extra pawn, we will just castle and
possibly play h2-h3 to stop any Bg4-related plans. Then follows Nc3, Be3, etc,
where we just start trading and approaching the winning endgame thanks to our
extra pawn.}) 10. Nc3 {As I said in the introduction, this is a very rare move.
At the moment of writing, the main 10.0-0 was seen for more than 500 times,
while this move was chosen in 25 games only. But, it was played in such a
high-level game as Van Foreest-Carlsen, so its popularity will definitely
increase a lot! What is the difference, why do we start with 10.Nc3 as opposed
to castling and playing Nc3 later? I would quote Andrey Terekhov's words from
his course on Two Knights: 'The main idea behind this move is to take control
of e4 square, and thus prepare Be2, followed by d3. This might look slow but
it is surprisingly potent setup.' I find this explanation rather precise and
concise - indeed, Be2! is now our positional threat, sort of. Now, Black has
three main moves that we need to discuss - the main 10...0-0 which was seen in
15 games and is suggested by Terekhov, the second most popular 10...Nf4 and
Gustafsson's novelty 10...f5!, which is the most precise way for Black to
handle the position, I think.} O-O {Andrey recommends this natural move, and
that's exactly what Magnus did versus Van Foreest.} (10... Nf4 {This is a very
interesting move, in fact! Jan and Andrey aren't even mentioning it, as 11.0-0
is very likely to transpose to the mainline. To the best of my understanding,
the reason why they are ignoring it is because after 10.0-0 they prefer 10...
0-0 instead of 10...Nf4, as that 10...Nf4 isn't considered most precise for
Black. It indeed is the most popular move according to the database, but it's
not what the top players have been doing as of late. But, many players are
unaware that 10.0-0 0-0! is currently the trend, so they are likely to make
this move - we need to be ready.} 11. O-O {The whole point of this move order
this position also often arises via 10.0-0 Nf4 11.Nc3! is that White used to
automatically insert the move Re1 in, but it would often prove useless as that
e5-pawn wasn't hanging, as a matter of fact! Now, our positional threat is to
go Be2 in order to stop the opponent from spoiling our structure. So, Black
needs to take.} Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O {At this point, we have two interesting
possibilities.} 13. b3 {Aronian's move. The goal is to meet ...c6-c5, which is
Black's typical idea as he wants to grab space and improve his knight's
position with ...Na5-c6, with Ba3, putting pressure on the c5-pawn right away.
Now, a few continuations are possible here.} c5 {Ding made this move and got a
rather bad position, which was the reason why all this talk appeared that the
line 10...Nf4 was rather not too fun for Black.} 14. Ba3 {White often places
the bishop on this position in order to target the c5-pawn. But the fresh news
about this game specifically was the fact that he managed to attain all that
without committing to a useless move Re1.} Nc6 15. Ne4 Nb4 16. Bxb4 cxb4 {
Now that the knight is traded, many opportunities for dynamic counterplay also
disappear from Black's agenda.} 17. Re1 Bb8 18. Ng3 {18.Nc5! was even better,
but this also works.} Qxd3 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Rxe5 Be6 21. Re3 Qd4 22. Ne2 Qd6
23. d4 {White managed to stabilize the position and keep the extra pawn. While
Black did manage to save his half a point, this has nothing to do with the
opening - White's opening was clearly a large success as he just got a healthy
extra pawn without allowing much of a counterplay. 1/2 (43) Aronian,L (2765) -
Ding,L (2805) Saint Louis 2019}) (10... f5 {As usual, Jan Gustafsson lives up
to his reputation of a great analyst and suggests a very powerful novelty in
his course - that was the toughest nut for me to crack. Just as after 10...0-0
- Terekhov's suggestion - I would be giving two alternatives here, which
should suit both those of you who are looking for some absolutely insane wild
game as well as those looking to check who well-prepared the opponents are and
just let them get half a point if they did their homework well. While
objectively it's not possible to prove White's advantage after this move, I am
very satisfied with our prospects practically as we are choosing between a
forced draw and a highly interesting complicated position which wasn't
discussed in Jan's course, which means even students of that course won't be
expecting it at all. The idea of Black's last move is very clear - he wants to
push ...e5-e4. That's the price of having a bishop on d3, as with the bishop
elsewhere, the simple d2-d3 would have stopped that plan for good.} 11. Nxd5 {
Unfortunately, we have to strengthen Black's center with this exchange.} cxd5
12. b4 {This cool move does the job. Now the knight is attacked and Black is
forced to retreat, as taking the pawn isn't possible.} Nc6 (12... Nc4 13. Bxc4
{Again, if we manage to get rid of some of Black's central pawns, we should be
extremely happy - this is the case here, too.} dxc4 14. Bb2 e4 {The e5-pawn is
now hanging. Black has two options - giving it up, or advancing it. Neither
will provide enough compensation/play for the missing material, though.} 15.
Nd4 {I feel this is the more human move.} O-O 16. Qe2 {White easily stabilizes
the position and starts targetting the weakness on c4. Now, ...Be6 isn't
possible, ...Ba6 would blunder the fork (Ne6 attacks the queen and a rook and
wins), while ...Qc7 allows for Nb5, where we trade Black's bishop and still
win the c4-pawn! Either way, White's nearly winning.}) 13. Bb5 {This pin is
extremely helpful, as it forces Black to make some clumsy move.} Bb7 {This is
what Jan is recommending. While it might seem less natural than 13...Bd7 to
some, as it doesn't unpin the knight, this move makes sense as it immediately
places the bishop on the long diagonal. Here, we reach a very important
crossroads. 14.c4! is the objectively more challenging move which creates a
huge mess where both sides are risking a lot, while 14.Bb2 reaches a very safe
position where we win a few pawns and force Black to fight to get them back,
which leads to simplifications and piece (even though I still like White a
tiny bit better at the end!). The position is truly critical, so I wanted to
give you two possibilities and let you decide for yourselves, what you like
better. And, just a friendly reminder - don't drown in these lines as 10...f5
is already a novelty - guys, even the World Champion Carlsen didn't find it
over the board, what's the chance your opponents will?} 14. Bb2 {The e5-pawn
attacked and the long diagonal is challenged. But, as Jan points out correctly,
Black can ignore this for the time being and sacrifice another pawn. As we say
in Russian, if the shed is on fire, let the house be on fire as well! Or in
other words, Black is already beyond the point when he's counting the pawns.
Other moves are much worse and lead to a nearly losing position for Black, but
in order to avoid making this too lengthy, I'd let you work the rest out.} O-O
15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxe5 {Now, White pockets another pawn.} Re8 {The only move,
but a natural one - the desire to take advantage of the pin is very
instinctive.} 17. f4 {Now, we are ready to castle and start converting our
extra stuff - even giving up the b4-pawn isn't a problem. The advantage of
being several pawns up is that you can always try to consolidate by returning
one of them!} Qb6 {Black's got to stop us from castling or he'll be thrown out
of business soon. Jan cuts his analysis short here, saying Black is enjoying
sufficient compensation. Objectively he is right, but I believe it's
definitely worth digging deeper!} 18. a3 {Everything is safe on the e-file, so
we simply protect the pawn. Now, the idea is Qf3, possibly followed by Qf2 to
resolve the problems over the diagonal. Qf3-e3 would also do the job.} a5 {
Black needs to be active, or else we consolidate the position and compensation
vanishes.} 19. Qf3 {We sacrifice one pawn, but get to stabilize the position a
lot.} axb4 20. axb4 Bxe5 {It's the right time to take on e5 as White cannot
take with the bishop, as that would leave his bishop pinned and his a1-rook
unprotected.} 21. fxe5 Qxb4 22. Rxa8 Rxa8 23. Qc3 {The game is still going,
but White is continuing his fight for the advantage.} Qe4+ 24. Kd1 Qxg2 25. Re1
{Objectively, after a few more precise defensive moves, Black should make a
draw, but it's clear that with this powerful battery over the long diagonal
and the threat of e5-e6 coming down the pipeline, White is the one pressing
for the advantage. It's just important to understand that:  1: objectively, 4.
Ng5! should be a forced draw if we are speaking of the 25-30-move-long precise
sequences;  2: we did pose tons of problems to the opponent;  3: if they find
dozens of perfect moves, it's a draw - congratulations, you just drew the God
of chess!;  4: we've been off the official theory for the last 15 moves - no
one in the world will find all those moves. So, I am happy with the amount of
challenge Black is facing.}) 11. Be2 {As stated earlier, White's idea behind
Nc3 was to take the e4-square under control and prepare this move. Now, we
just want to play d2-d3 and control the e4-square even better.} f5 {In his
course, Andrey is suggesting this typical move which grabs a lot of space.} (
11... Nf4 {Magnus played this, but the course of the game clearly proved him
wrong.} 12. O-O Bg4 13. d3 {White wants to take Bxf4, thus putting to an end
all of Black's hopes for counterplay.} Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 f5 15. h3 Bh5 {In fact,
this position was reached in two games. Besides Carlsen's one, it was seen in
another battle of two 2500-rated players. Black's position looks okay, but
it's not... after Van Foreest's excellent decision.} 16. g4 {White resolves
that pin in a slightly unexpected fashion! The point is that we also gain
control over the e4-square.} fxg4 17. Ng5 {Now fxg4 is coming.} Qd7 18. Nce4 {
Black still cannot do anything as his pawn is pinned and the h5-bishop is
unprotected.} Be7 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Qxg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 {After the slightly
complicated heated battle that we just saw, White obtained a healthy extra
pawn and a nearly winning position. Unfortunately - at least from our
perspective as we fancy this line with White - he didn't manage to develop his
success and convert the advantage, as the World Champion showed some extremely
tenacious defense, as well as a bit of luck and the game, was eventually drawn.
Yet, this is something we call a huge opening success, as White just kept his
healthy extra pawn! 1/2 (45) Van Foreest,J (2644) - Carlsen, M (2872) Wijk aan
Zee 2020}) 12. d3 {We just keep developing.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qc7 {Here Andrey
Terekhov cuts his analysis short, suggesting Black has typical compensation
and the standard plan of ...e5-e4, ...c6-c5, ...Bb7 and ...Rae8, mobilizing
all his forces. He also correctly points out White needs to be careful as
castling might run into ...e5-e4 when the h2-pawn would hang. I do agree with
all of these words and plans, but I think we need to extend the analysis, as
White is still a pawn up and while Black does have compensation, it's not
'breaking through the roof'. In my opinion, compensation in this position is a
rather defensive one, as Black has more space and it's not easy to convert
this extra pawn. But, it's not a situation we need to shy away from, as we can
keep improving our position step by step!} 14. g3 {We improve our control over
the h2-b8 diagonal, setting up an obstacle in front of Black's Q+B battery.} c5
{Black might also start with ...Bb7, but he'd need this move anyway in order
to grab more space and get a better control over the d4-square, in order to
open up the long diagonal for his b7-bishop and to be able to return the
a5-knight back to normal life via c6.} 15. O-O Bb7 16. Rb1 {Here's an open
file, so we grab it. Now, we might consider ideas with d3-d4, but our main
goal is to play Nd2 or Ng5 followed by Bf3, trading that mighty bishop,
simplifying the game, and thus coming one (huge!) step closer to the endgame
where we will be a healthy pawn up.} Rae8 {Here, I would like us to look at
two plans.} 17. Nd2 {I like this solid plan best. Now, if Black waits, Bf3!
will trade the bishops and make his compensation for the missing pawn very
questionable.} c4 {This amazing blockading move is the only way for Black to
get counterplay. I would like to remind you it's already been AGES since we
have left the official theory and landed on a completely unexplored ground. So,
while I am trying to show you Black's amazing resources, I wouldn't bet a mere
penny on your opponents finding all this. Yet, it's good to be thoroughly
prepared - I expect 2650+ GMs to benefit from this course!} (17... Kh8 18. Bf3
{This is just to show you what our idea is we plan on playing this way after
any Black's move, only 17...c4! can trouble us a bit .} Bxf3 19. Qxf3 e4 {
Now, we are about to go Qd5 and Nf3, for example. At this point, I already
don't see any compensation for Black. The only thing he can essay is} 20. Qe2 {
but after} exd3 {White is just threatening to take that e4-pawn, while after}
21. Qxd3 f4 22. Ne4 {White is just winning as ideas like Ba3 and Rd1 are
coming and Black has no counterplay. Right now his bishop is hanging, and it's
not possible to move it as Bxf4 would pick another free pawn. Besides that,
White is already a pawn up! So, things look terrible here for Black.}) 18. Re1
{White could play Bf3 immediately, too, but it's nice to improve the rook
first - it's going to be rather restraining Black's activity over the e-file
and stopping all the possible ...e5-e4 related ideas. Our next moves will be
Bf3, likely followed by Bxb7 and Qf3, or possibly, after the bishop trade,
we'll play d3-d4 in order to force ...e5-e4, which will close the position a
lot and enable us to ensure a firm blockade, stabilizing the situation and
preparing to start converting our pawn. One important line here is} Kh8 {
Black should be rather playing some waiting game like this. Again, don't feel
stressed that the arising positions are complicated - we are talking some
2700-level preparation here!} 19. Bf3 Ba6 20. Nf1 {The bishop is going to g2,
while the knight will come to e3 and d5! I don't believe Black can claim full
compensation here - indeed, it's not easy to break through and convert the
pawn, but his compensation is more of a defensive/constraining character - we
and only we are the ones playing for a win here. By the way, once again, this
d3-d4 idea could prove reasonable in the future. Possibly, once we go Bg2 and
Ne3, we might even go d3-d4! to force ...e5-e4, which would block the center
and deprive Black of any dynamic ideas. There isn't enough for a pawn here.})
4. b4 {In this chapter, we'll speak about all the sidelines Black has in the
Evans. Or, to use different wording, about everything Black can do against our
dear gambit except for 4.b4 Bxb4 5.c3 Ba5 and 5.c3 Be7, the two main moves. It
was definitely possible to discuss everything in one chapter, but I don't want
to overwhelm you with the information. In fact, I've covered those sidelines
in more detail than one would require in the practical settings, but as usual,
the goal of the course is to provide you with all the solutions you might need,
so that you never wonder what you should do versus this or that variation.}
Bxb4 {This is definitely the main move. In this chapter, however, we won't
discuss Black's main defenses on next move. Instead, we will be focusing on
the less principled possibilities.} 5. c3 {Now, it's time to analyze the two
main defenses - 5...Ba5! and 5...Be7! Black can definitely equalize in both,
but the positions remain interesting and fun to play and as far as I am aware,
there is no mathematically forced perpetual check or dead-drawn endgame or
something, so you won't need to fear opponent's amazing preparation that can
just kill the game. If they are prepared, they equalize, but we get to play
exciting and ambitious chess, nevertheless.} Ba5 {This is the most popular
move by far. The goal of this move is not to allow for d4 when White can meet .
..exd4 with cxd4, as the c3-pawn is pinned. Additionally, unlike in the
situations with the bishop on c5, Black's bishop isn't getting hit with a
tempo.} (5... Be7 {This is the second move popularity-wise and my choice for
Black in my full 1.e4 e5 Black repertoire 'Unleash the Bull'. Of course, I
analyzed the Evans gambit a lot as I was preparing that course. And, obviously,
the evaluation is absolutely correct - Black is perfectly fine. But, after the
publication, I had to dig into this deeper as I was teaching Evans to a few
private students of mine - not because this is some very best weapon against 1.
e4 e5 or anything, but because I think it's a fantastic tool to develop your
feel for the initiative. At the same time, it's worth mentioning that - as
weird as it sounds! - some important things have happened in chess during the
last year, namely Lc0, the neural engine, appeared and many evaluations have
changed, as a result. So, while we won't be able to claim any advantage in
this line if Black did his homework well, we'll be sure to surprise Black with
a handful of new interesting dangerous ideas.} 6. d4 Na5 {The most practical
reply and the one I give in my Black repertoire.} 7. Bd3 {The most precise
move, as it protects the e4-pawn and the bishop would possibly enjoy a bunch
of activity after the eventual e4-e5.} d6 {The most solid defense. Instead of
grabbing everything he was offered, Black returns his extra pawn.} (7... exd4 {
As usual, I don't approve of Black's greed in the Evans gambit.} 8. cxd4 {
By the way, 8.0-0 is also interesting if you feel like sacrificing even more.}
d5 9. exd5 {While this move involves creating an isolated pawn on d4, I like
it because it opens up the position for our well-developed pieces.} Qxd5 10.
Nc3 Bb4 11. Qc2 Nf6 {At this point, I think that Nigel had a better option
than the very logical 12.Ba3.} 12. O-O {This is my suggestion, as it attacks
the Black queen because we unpin the knight on c3. Now if the Black queen
retreats, after Re1+ the king will be in jeopardy. So, Black has to part with
his bishop.} Bxc3 13. Qxc3 O-O 14. Re1 {White puts the rook on the open file,
preventing or making ...Re8 more difficult and taking the e4-square under
control. Now, Re5! is a serious threat, winning the a5-knight.} Nc6 15. Ba3 Rd8
16. Bc4 Qd7 {Time to apply pressure on f7. Black's queen has a hard time
finding a good spot as ...Qd7 obstructs the c8-bishop's development while ...
Qh5 and ...Qa5 drive the queen too far from the main course of action - the
f7-square. Either way, White is already much better. For example, after} 17.
Ng5 Nd5 18. Qf3 {The d5-knight is under pressure, as White wants to take
everything on d5 and win with Re8 mate - the back rank is too weak. Black
cannot move the knight as then he'd lose the pawn on f7 and the game. So, he
is forced to enter the following line, which is clearly bad.} h6 19. Bxd5 hxg5
20. Re7 {Pointe finale! Now, Black needs to give up his queen.} Qxd5 21. Re8+
Rxe8 22. Qxd5 {We are not winning here, but White is definitely much better.
Importantly, the Black pieces still aren't developed and the g5-pawn is weak.
We might also want to consider playing Bb2, moving the queen, and pushing
d4-d5!, activating the bishop over the long diagonal. All in all, this is a
game for two results - a win or a draw, White is better for the rest of the
game.}) 8. dxe5 dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nf6 {White got his pawn back, while Black got to
develop his kingside pieces without running into any threats or problems. Both
parties should be rather content.} 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 {This is the right move
for White, as it prepares f2-f4 and Nd2, while protecting the bishop - see the
line 11.Nd2 to understand why it's important to protect the d3-bishop one more
time. Here, we need to analyze the moves 11...c7-c5, which is the main line,
played by Karjakin and Lazaro Bruzon, amongst others. Kramnik went ...Nd7 here,
trying to trade the knights, which is a very logical continuation. Black has a
handful of other moves, such as ...c7-c6, and while we will analyze this move,
we won't cover 10 other continuations as I believe White's plan and way of
development is rather similar in all the cases.} c5 {Black tries to grab space
on the queenside, ensuring himself of a nice spot on c7 for his queen, as
otherwise the move Rd1! could be tough to meet. But, I don't actually think
this is a good move for Black, as we get to build our kingside initiative
without any worries!} (11... c6 12. Nd2 {The second most popular move, but I
think it's a pure coincidence, as it's clearly bad - Black is just wasting
time.} Qc7 13. f4 {This was Black's idea, but then 11...c5 should have been
preferred, at least taking more space and possibly intending ...c5-c4.} b6 14.
Nb3 {I like this new idea a lot because if we force Black to take, after axb3
we will resolve our only issue - the somewhat weak queenside pawns will again
become excellent. On the other hand, a move like ...Nb7 looks really ugly, so
Black is already in deep strategic trouble here - the engine is even claiming
White is almost winning, which is a bit of an exaggeration. But, truth be told,
it's really bad for Black, as we dominate the entire board.}) 12. Nd2 Qc7 13.
f4 {I think that this move, as played by the notable theoretician Huschenbeth,
among others, is a clear improvement over Nc4, as was played in
Kryvoruchko-Karjakin. Why so and what's the idea? Well, White has more space
and pawn weaknesses, which means he needs to play actively to utilize his
dynamic advantages as well as not to end up trading a lot of pieces/
transposing in some inferior endgame where he'll struggle a lot with his
weaknesses. That's exactly what we do! At this point, many moves are possible,
but most GMs that got here chose 13...b6. The position is very new and
unexplored, though, as only 7 games have reached it.} Be6 {This is another
possible plan, which I, however, don't believe in.} 14. Ndf3 {Now, White's
threat is c3-c4!, grabbing tons of space and preparing Bb2!} c4 {This is
pretty forced, or else c3-c4 would have been too strong.} 15. Be2 Bc5+ 16. Nd4
{I definitely believe White is better here as his space advantage is enormous.
Later, we play Be3, Rae1, Bf3, Kh1, and initiate tons of active play on the
kingside. Please pay close attention to how misplaced the a5-knight is!}) (5...
Bc5 {This is something people used to do back in the day as Black, trying to
control the d4-square and a lot of lovely miniatures have been created from
now on. Nowadays, it's known this isn't the best move available to the
opponent as after d2-d4! White gains the center while also winning a tempo on
the Black bishop. Importantly, you get the same position after 4...Nxb4 5.c3
Nc6 6.d4.} 6. d4 {We immediately take the center, of course.} exd4 {This has
been the most popular move by a huge margin.} 7. O-O {This is the main move
for a good reason. Now, there are a few extremely important tricks that I'd
like to teach you.} d6 {The main theoretical move.} (7... Nge7 8. cxd4 {
Okay, Black can afford this move, if we are being frank. He'll just be worse
after it, but at least, it's not an immediate loss as after 7...d3 or 7...Nf6.}
Bb6 9. Ng5 d5 {Black has to find this pawn sacrifice to stay in the game.} 10.
exd5 Nxd5 {Just as in the famous Fried Liver variation that we see after 3.Bc4
Nf6 4.Ng5 d5 5.exd5 Nxd5?, taking on d5 is terrible here as well. White wins
in multiple ways, the most beautiful one being} 11. Nxf7 Kxf7 {This is also
extremely typical.} 12. Qh5+ Ke6 13. Re1+ {Curtains. The Black king is in
jeopardy and that knight is lost anyway.}) (7... dxc3 {This is also too greedy.
Normally, you cannot afford to open the position up so much when the king is
in the center and the position is already fairly open, while your pieces are
so undeveloped!} 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 {Just as after 7...d3, you see this very
typical idea when we force the Black king on f7 to fork it and the c5-bishop.}
9. Qd5+ Ke8 10. Qxc5 d6 11. Qxc3 Nf6 {While the material is even, the position
is not, as the Black king is terrible. Now, all we need to do is open up the
game.} 12. Re1 {We are preparing e4-e5!} Be6 13. Na3 {First, we bring the
remaining pieces in the game. The knight might look ugly here, but it'll come
to c4 or b5 to help us attack Black. The good news about having it here as
opposed to the d2-square is that the c1-bishop doesn't feel forgotten.} Qd7 {
Let's suppose Black makes some move now.} 14. Nb5 a6 15. Nbd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 {
Nxe6 and e4-e5, or just e4-e5 are unstoppable, White is totally winning. Say,
if} Bf7 {then we can either play e4-e5 right away, or start with Bg5 or Ba3,
claiming that the threat is stronger than the execution.} 17. Bg5 {It's gonna
be totally over within the 5 next moves.}) 8. cxd4 Bb6 {At this point, I
suggest that we simply develop as opposed to trying to kill Black instantly.}
9. Nc3 Na5 {Black won't stay in the game for a long time unless he finds this
move.} (9... Nf6 {This is an excellent way for Black to lose quickly as we
have a lovely dynamic resource here. Again, the strategic considerations step
back into the shadow here, all that matters is that uncastled king on e8. Come
on!} 10. e5 dxe5 11. Ba3 {We have not only opened the e-file, but also we've
stopped Black from castling. For example, after} Bxd4 12. Qb3 Qd7 13. Rfe1 {
Black is completely tied up, he cannot develop or untangle and as Rad1 is
about to follow, the material losses are inevitable.}) 10. Bd3 Ne7 {Now that
the bishop isn't on the a2-g8 diagonal, Black can develop the knight here
without fearing Ng5-Qh5 too much.} 11. h3 {I like this calm positional move
which prevents ...Bg4. In fact, we don't necessarily have to checkmate Black
just because we've sacrificed a pawn. We can also try to create some serious
positional pressure as we have the beautiful center and more space. The
c8-bishop will find it difficult to land on a good spot, while the a5-knight
doesn't paint Black's position in the bright colours, either.} O-O 12. Rb1 {
This rare move, which was seen in 4 games only, has been suggested by the new
God of chess - Lc0. The idea is to possibly bring the rook over via b5 all the
way to the kingside, or to even come to b4 if we play Bd3-c2 and the Black
knight ever wants to visit c4! Another dangerous idea we are about to annoy
Black with is Bg5. So, he should, in my opinion, stop that.} h6 13. Re1 {
Okay, we are improving another piece.} Nac6 14. Bc2 {Here we see another
benefit of the rook on b1, as ...Nb4 isn't possible. Black will really find it
difficult to develop and create any counterplay, while our play is very easy.
Qd3 and e4-e5 is on cards, while ideas like Bc1-e3 or Nc2-e2-g3 don't look too
bad, either! White's compensation for the pawn is rather overwhelming, in my
opinion.}) 6. d4 {Now, Black has two solid options - 6...exd4 and 6...d6. The
former is suggested by Lysyj and Ovetchkin in their excellent book on 1.e4 e5
that deals with everything but Ruy Lopez. Bologan recommends the weird 6...
b5!? which we will also consider, even though you aren't likely to meet that
move, which has been played only in 44 games as opposed to several thousand
games in the two main lines.} exd4 {A very principled move. Black takes,
claiming that the a5-bishop is doing a fantastic job of stopping us from
grabbing that center. He believes the direct play with Qb3 won't yield much
and that he would be able to stabilize the situation without much trouble. Is
that the case? Objectively Black is totally fine, but he would need to play
extremely carefully. No easy life guaranteed or secured.} (6... b5 7. Bxb5 {
This rare move isn't too bad. Neither it is too challenging, either.} Nxd4 8.
Nxd4 {This was the point behind the pawn sacrifice, as now the bishop isn't on
the a2-g8 diagonal and White cannot hope to sacrifice stuff on f7 - see the 6..
.Nxd4? line for more detail.} exd4 9. O-O {I definitely think this move is
more interesting than 9.Qxd4 both objectively and practically, as White is
clearly planning to take on d4 with a pawn in order to obtain a fairly
impressive center while also inviting Black on a dangerous journey of greed,
as we let the c3-pawn hang. It's also important that this move wasn't covered
by Bologan at all, which gives us a fair hope that the Black players won't be
too acquainted with the line. By the way, we are again entering some rather
fresh ground as only 11 games have reached this position!} c6 10. Bc4 Ne7 11.
cxd4 O-O {At this point, we reach an equal position, because White's center is
about to be dismantled with ...d7-d5. Still, I have a feeling Black will need
to sweat a bit for equality as we have such possibilities as} 12. e5 {This is
another interesting idea, intending to get a structure like this.} d5 13. exd6
Qxd6 14. Ba3 Bb4 15. Bxb4 Qxb4 16. Nd2 {White's bishop is slightly more active
and the c6-pawn is arguably a little weaker. Also, I can definitely imagine a
scenario where Black goes ...Nd5 at some point and White takes and then
installs his knight on c5, reaching a position where he has the better minor
pieces. While objectively this is equal, it's neither a dead draw nor a
position where it's extremely easy to play as Black, so I am quite happy about
the opening outcome.}) (6... d6 7. Qb3 {This is definitely a good move and the
one preferred by Ding, Caruana, Anand and many others.} Qd7 {The f7-pawn is
the major target in Black's camp, attacking it right now is very logical.} 8.
O-O {The reason why the queen is well-placed exactly on d7 is because the
a4-e8 diagonal is covered and d4-d5 followed by Qa4+ doesn't win that
a5-bishop anymore. This is one of the two Black's major defensive ideas.} Bb6 {
Now, we again reach a position where while Black can equalize, he needs to be
extremely careful.} 9. Nbd2 {Black needs to know this non-trivial move or else
he lands in a lot of trouble.} Na5 {Black grabs our powerful bishop.} 10. Qc2
Nxc4 11. Nxc4 {Now, however, the e5-pawn turns out to be under lots of
pressure.} Qc6 {In my opinion, this is pretty much the only move that saves
Black from massive trouble. Pay attention, guys - Ding Liren and many other
strong players didn't find it!} (11... exd4 {This is what Ding did against
Mamedyarov, but Black's position becomes really bad very quickly.} 12. cxd4 Ne7
{White's center is extremely impressive, so is the fact Black hasn't developed
and castled yet. We will be able to capitalize on this!} 13. a4 c6 {a4-a5 is
too serious a threat.} 14. Ba3 Bc7 {Mamedyarov keeps creating threats with
every move.} 15. e5 dxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17. Rfd1 Qe8 18. Nd6 {White's advantage
was nearly decisive, but Black managed to save half a point with the
combination of stubborn defense and luck. Please take a look at the rest of
the game in the chapter on model games. 1/2 (39) Mamedyarov,S (2747) - Ding,L 
(2766) Huaian 2016}) 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 {White gets his pawn
back and opens up the position, which is extremely favorable as we are ahead
in development. This is an equal position, objectively, but I definitely like
White better here practically and the results prove my opinion as White scored
4/6, having won two games, drawn 4 and lost none. We will cut the trainable
variation here but will analyze this position and what to do next in more
detail in the chapter on model games. 1-0 (31) Lomasov,S (2549) - Lysyj,I 
(2630) Yaroslavl 2018}) 7. Qb3 {I believe this is a much better move than the
more popular castling, as we are applying immediate pressure on that f7-pawn
as well as not allowing Black to develop with ...Nge7 and 0-0.} Qe7 8. O-O Bb6
{The best defense, as Black immediately avoids all the hassle with the
potentially insecure bishop and protects the d4-pawn. At this point, White has
a plethora of options. Again, objectively this definitely is equal, but I
don't think that handling this is necessarily easy and pleasant for Black,
especially as we have this excellent novelty on move 16.} (8... Nf6 {Not a
great move, but it's not a terrible one, either. The only high-level game
where both players were 2400+ that reached this position was Stopa -
Bartholomew, where Black had a had time getting out of the opening.} 9. cxd4
Nxe4 {Black has to take, or else he's still suffering, but for no compensation
at all.} 10. Ba3 Nd6 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Rae1 {White is just mobilizing all of his
forces. We are two pawns down, but it doesn't matter, because this is the
wrong count! The right count starts when you look at the a8-rook, the
c8-bishop, the a5-bishop. How about the d6-knight? We are several pieces up,
that's what I call it.} Qd8 13. Bxd6 cxd6 14. Bxf7+ {Thanks to some nice
tactic, we win a pawn back.} Kh8 15. Bd5 {I think it's a good position to stop
at as White is totally dominating the board while being just one pawn down.
Even that extra d-pawn is doubled, so it makes no difference! Just as the best
traditions of gambits teach us, we have managed to paralyze and blockade
Black's entire queenside. Things look just terrible for the second player.}) 9.
cxd4 {The main move for White and the one I like best. But, in case if you are
looking to expand your repertoire, do look at 9.Nbd2, it's a very decent
continuation as well.} Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nc3 {Now the threat is Nd5.} Nf6
12. Ba3 {The main line, I do like this move.} d6 13. Rad1 Bxc3 14. Qxc3 {
Now e4-e5 is a threat. The simple Re1 is also quite annoying.} Qe5 15. Qc1 {
Again, I agree with Lysyj that this is the best move for White, as he avoids
the queen trade and prepares f2-f4 as well as Bb2 and Rfe1.} O-O 16. Rfe1 {
Here is my suggested novelty, which is very exciting for White. Lysyj doesn't
analyze it at all in his excellent move, which is understandable given this
book is rather old and my faithful friend Lc0 didn't exist back then. It's not
even clear what move Black should make as f2-f4 and e4-e5 is coming!} Re8 {
The right solution as Black escapes the pin down the a3-f8 diagonal.} 17. Bb2
Qh5 {The right defense, objectively. To be honest, I have no faith at all that
any Black player would be able to reach this position OTB unless they are a
well-prepared titled player, or maybe even rather a GM. Still, even here White
retains very nice compensation. Say,} 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Rd3 {This rook lift
looks really good. What should Black do as all the sorts of threats are coming
up? Man, this is very dangerous. I know the computer will hold a draw and that
I cannot argue with the God of chess which claims 0.00, but that's not the
point of my work. The point is to help you win, and with such preparation, you
will!!} *

