{[%evp 0,15,28,21,45,21,28,28,35,25,93,62,159,155,141,142,135,139]} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {Now, we are going to analyze Black's sidelines on move 3. Some
of them, such as 3...Be7 and 3...g6, actually make a lot of sense, even though
those clearly aren't the best moves available out there. On the other hand,
some moves, such as 3...d6, 3...h6, and so on, clearly don't deserve too much
attention, but I did want to cover them anyway because my private students of
the club level face them a lot when opponents either don't know theory or want
to avoid the theoretical battle. Logically, it's fair enough to expect that if
you are a club player, you'll encounter them a bunch, too. If you are a
tournament player or a titled player and feel that studying those moves isn't
worth it, feel free to either skip this chapter or just use this for
occasional checks when you do face these moves online. The good news is that
White is able to keep the advantage in all those lines without knowing too
much or without making the play sharp and unpredictable. The bad news is...
wait, why did I say that? Well, usually after the words 'the good news' they
follow with 'but' or 'here's the problem, though'. Not this time - this time
we just enjoy the easy advantage. Remember the rule of thumb: in most cases,
passive moves in this position are punished by the active d2-d4! which yields
White the space advantage, as we will see in numerous variations.} Be7 {
I am going to mark this move as a fairly interesting one, because while it's
clearly inferior to the main guys 3...Bc5 and 3...Nf6, it does have some
interesting ideas behind it. For one, if White were to play 4.d3 here, Black
could go 4...Nf6!, getting back to the 4...Nf6 Italians while avoiding the Two
Knights with 4.Ng5. Pretty clever, isn't it? Even Magnus tried it in a rapid
game in 2018, and it was occasionally essayed by Jobava, Laznicka, Bacrot, and
others. I can definitely relate to the ideas and reasons why strong players
might want to try such continuation: it avoids the sharp lines like 4.Ng5 or 4.
d4 where White is likely to just make a draw if he wishes to and did his
homework well, as well as the 3...Bc5 4.c3/d4 stuff, where White can also try
to simplify the game and make a draw. Obviously, that's not what we're gonna
be doing in this course - we are playing for a win - but stronger players
might try this against you to just get a game without compromising their
position too much. Of course, such luxury comes at a price, though.} (3... d6 {
This is another rather passive move. However, as we will see, it's not a very
easy one to refute! The fact that it was played by Ivanchuk in the past and by
Paravyan and Gledura recently, should give you an idea that it's a fairly
decent continuation, in fact. At this point, I also like the dynamic
continuation.} 4. d4 {In the Open Games, White often wants to meet ...d7-d6
with d2-d4. This is good for several reasons, the most important being the
fact that we ensure ourselves of some rather significant space advantage.
Besides that, once the Black pawns steps on d6, Black cannot jump out to c5
with his bishop anymore, which makes our knight on d4 feel a lot more
comfortable.} (4. O-O {Is another good move, and objectively, this might be
even stronger. I think that 4.d4 is very straightforward and well-aligned with
what we tend to do versus other Black choices on move 3, and the best defense
for Black after 3...d6 4.d4 is quite unknown, so I decided to go with it
anyway. But, 4.0-0 is something you might to investigate independly, as this
is less forcing and also leads to a clear advantage.}) 4... exd4 {Leads to the
same kind of positions as ones analyzed after 3...h6.} (4... Bg4 {Many
students of mine get naturally scared of this pin, which is understandable.
But, in fact, White is nearly winning here.} 5. h3 {A very important move that
truly punishes Black's play, as the d4-pawn isn't hanging at all.} Bxf3 (5...
Bh5 6. d5 Nb8 (6... Nd4 7. g4 {Now, in order not to lose the pawn, Black needs
to take on f3, and after} Nxf3+ 8. Qxf3 Bg6 9. Bb5+ {He loses the right to
castle, ending up in a lost position. It is also important to mention the
bishop on g6, which is a very common problem Black faces if he allows the
h2-h3 and the g2-g4 push in the Italian/Ruy positions. In fact, our kingside
isn't weak at all as we have multiple pieces there, as Black has no way to
ever attack us, and because that pawn on g4 ensures us of a huge space
advantage. Instead, the g6-bishop is dead. Period. It's just not getting out!})
7. g4 Bg6 {Black has to retreat in this way, which is rather passive. Now,
White is able to obtain large advantage thanks to his extra space rather
effortlessly.} 8. Nc3 {Same idea - the bishop is extremely misplaced and
passive on g6, White is much better.}) 6. Qxf3 {The mate is threatened which
means d4 is untouchable, while after} Nf6 7. d5 Nb8 {By the way, after 7...Na5
8.Bd3 White would be threatening b4! trapping the knight.} 8. Nc3 {White's
advantage is large, as he owns all the space and the bishop pair. His
development is also clearly superior. To be honest, I feel I am getting tired
of describing White's advantages, so let's cut this here! It is possible to
either continue in a normal calm positional way or consider going for the
slaughter with moves like g2-g4, g4-g5, h2-h4, and so on! Your choice.}) (4...
Nf6 {As I was preparing the material for this course, I bumped into some
fairly unexpected discovery, which lied in acknowleding that the move 4...Nf6!
