d8 and this terrible Black pawn structure White would be clearly better.}) 7.
Nxe5 {This position was reached 47 times, mostly in the games of U-1800-level
players. Black would mostly take the pawn here, which results in some very
nice pressure for White. But, there's a better move!} Bd6 {This suggested
improvement of mine was seen only in 7 games, mostly between unrated players.
But, in fact, Black is almost okay here!} (7... Nxe4 8. O-O Bc5 {This is how
most games went, but now Black suddenly finds himself on the edge of survival.}
9. Nd3 Be7 {Had the bishop gone elsewhere, Re1 would have created too
problematic a pin.} 10. Re1 Nd6 11. Bb3 {Now Black cannot castle, while after}
Be6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Nd5 {White is attacking the e7-bishop and the c7-pawn and
is simply nearly winning after the forced} Bxd5 14. Bxd5 Bf6 15. Bf4 {The
White pieces are all incredibly active and the d8-knight cannot ever join the
game as the b7-pawn would hang. This is just lost.}) 8. Nf3 Nxe4 9. O-O {
White is going to keep some initiative thanks to the ugly position of the
knight on d8 and the slightly exposed knight on e4. For example, after White
is going to keep some initiative thanks to the ugly position of the knight on
d8 and the slightly exposed one of the knight on e4. For example, after} O-O (
9... Be6 10. Re1 {We are making use of the fact that the king is still on e8.}
Bxc4 11. Rxe4+ Be6 12. Nc3 {Now Nb5 is a positional threat, taking the bishop
