d4 isn't a part of the repertoire given here, I did think it'd make tons of
sense to mention this possible transposition as many of you are already
playing 4.d4.}) 10. Re1 Nc5 11. Nc3 {The knight is coming to b5, forcing} a6 {
but then after} 12. Nd4 {We still keep the obvious pressure as Black cannot
develop his pieces to c6 and e6. Be3, Rad1, Nd5 are all about to follow. The
position is symmetrical, but not equal at all - it's an uphill struggle for
Black.})) (3... Nd4 {This is a very bad move objectively, but it needs to be
analyzed carefully as many White players immediately walk in a trap and lose!}
4. Nxd4 {Just as castling, this is a very good move. I like the fact that it
spoils the Black structure immediately. By the way, this position is actually
a 3...Nd4 Ruy Lopez ('Bird variation') where white is a tempo up. Since white
is already better in the Bird, here it's even worse for black.} (4. Nxe5 {
It's very tempting to grab that pawn, isn't it. But, after} Qg5 {The double
attack on e5 and g2 puts White in trouble. Now White can still bail out, but
in order to prevent you from ever wanting to go here, I'll give the most
