and principled way to continue.} (5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. O-O Ne7 8. Nc3 {
This is, undoubtedly, slight better and quite pleasant for White as well, but
it's not putting the Black idea under any immediate pressure. Which is not bad
at all, actually, if you're just looking for the slightly more pleasant game!})
5... d3 {Black typically never dares to capture one more pawn.} (5... dxc3 {
This is a step in some very wrong direction.} 6. Qb3 {The f7-square is a huge
issue now.} Nh6 7. O-O {We could have taken on h6 and on f7 immediately, but
we keep that option for the next move. Now, the game can develop in a few ways,
but the most logical one seems to be} Bg7 8. Bxh6 Bxh6 9. Bxf7+ Kf8 10. Nxc3 {
White restored the material balance and has a clear advantage thanks to the
huge lead in development as well as the fact that the Black king is rather
exposed. The ensuing play is no rocket science: we will play Rad1, possibly
e4-e5! to lock the Black queenside in, and so on. Back in the day they'd just
call this entirely lost. Nowadays, the engines show true miracles when it
comes to saving bad positions, so I won't be that harsh - I'd just say it's no
fun for Black.}) 6. Bg5 {It is important to make this move before Black played
...Bg7, because now ...Nge7 is impossible on account of Bf6!} Be7 (6... f6 7.
Be3 {White will still pick up the d3-pawn and the weakness of the a2-g8
