Curtains!}) 7. Bf4 {We have forced the Black bishop to the wrong diagonal and
now just retreat.} Nf6 8. Bxd3 O-O 9. O-O {Why do I like this position better
than the one after 5.Nxd4? The structure is slightly different, and in this
structure, White is often able to build the bind by playing c2-c4, grabbing
the d5-square as well as a plethora of other squares under some firm control.
Moreover, we can often deprive Black of what he was looking for - the
potentially unbalanced fun position - by pushing e4-e5 and liquidating in a
slightly more pleasant risk-free endgame where it's a fight for two results -
either White wins, or Black draws.} d6 10. h3 {Stopping all the possible ...
Bg4-related ideas sounds smart.} Re8 11. c4 {White will follow with Nc3, Qd2,
