he's not MUCH worse, this looks very unpleasant in the practical settings, as
Black has no counterplay while we keep gradually improving our position. Life
made easy!}) (3... h6 {This move clearly isn't best. It does serve the purpose
of taking the g5-square under control, though.} 4. d4 {This is very typical.
When allowed, we grab that center and challenge that e5-pawn.} exd4 (4... d6 {
Now it gets really bad.} 5. dxe5 Nxe5 (5... dxe5 6. Qxd8+ {Now the knight
recapture drops the e5-pawn, while the king recapture loses the one on f7.
Either way, White is winning.}) 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Bxf7+ {A typical tactic.
Instead, 7.Qxd8 is also good, but this wins a tempo, too.} Ke7 {Of course, the
bishop was untouchable as Black would have lost the queen.} 8. Qxd8+ {White is
a pawn up and the Black king is likely to be in jeopardy. There is no need to
analyze this any further.}) 5. Nxd4 {At this point, many moves are possible,
but we won't go too deep. I would like to mention a few things, though: 1 If
we compare this with the Scotch Game, which arises after 1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.
d4 exd4 4.Nxd4, White is kind of a tempo up, as he has the additional move Bc4,
while Black has played ...h7-h6. I think the difference is clearly in our
favor. White now simply has more space and Black also needs to watch out for
some typical dynamic problems, for example} Nxd4 (5... d6 {Maybe that is the
most solid move, as it stops the e4-e5 ideas. But Black won't be able to
