extra space discussed in many other places in the chapter.} (5... Nf6 6. Nxc6
bxc6 7. e5 {White would get the very typical initiative, Black's position is
rather bad here.})) 5. dxe5 (5. d5 {If you don't like the simplifications that
arise in the main line 5.dxe5, consider giving this a try. But, we are not
going to discuss this deeply as the arising positions don't look like the
Italian at all!}) 5... dxe5 (5... Nxe5 {You wouldn't believe this, but this
losing move was even played by many 2400+ level players! Now Black is
dead-lost.} 6. Nxe5 dxe5 7. Qh5 {A very typical double attack on the e5 and
the f7-pawns. Black not only loses a pawn, but also, he ought to weaken his
position.} g6 8. Qxe5 Nf6 9. Bh6 {White is a pawn up and his position is
totally overwhelming. I guess we are not discussing this any further. 1-0 (30)
Nihal,S (2610) - Benidze,D (2469) Konya 2019}) 6. Qxd8+ {Now, Black seemingly
has several ways of recapturing, but once you look more attentively, it
becomes obvious only one recapture is possible.} Bxd8 (6... Kxd8 7. Bxf7 {
Again, a free pawn.}) (6... Nxd8 7. Nxe5 {This is a free pawn.}) 7. Nc3 {
Now, let us discuss the arising position. What are White's goals and how can
he be better? For one, it's a very symmetrical position, isn't it. In such
situations, it is not possible to count on the advantage thanks to the extra
space or the better structure, as the word 'symmetrical' in the description of
the pawn structure strongly suggests. So, the main factor involved is the
activity and development, as well as the possibility to start creating threats.
Let's understand White's advantages and goals:  1 He is better developed.  2
He is easily able to castle long - this is very important as it will enable
him to join the game quickly with his a1-rook.  3 He is able to control both
key diagonals.  Now, this part might require further explanation. I believe
that in many symmetrical structures, such as the French Exchange, or this
structure, where the d-pawns get exchanged, there are two key diagonals. In
this case, it's a2-g8 and g1-a7. The reason is that the bishops are placed
best exactly there as they are able to control several important squares. So,
White already controls a2-g8, as Black shouldn't be too willing to go ...Be6
as that will compromise his pawn structure. On the other hand, while we don't
control g1-a7 yet, we inevitably will, as we are about to go Be3, stopping ...
Bc5.4 It is likely that due to the superior activity of our pieces, we will be
able to create dynamic threats, which will result either in structural changes
that are supposed to be favorable for us or in material gains. For example, we
can play Nd5, keeping the Black bishop stuck on d8. That will force Black to
either tolerate the very strong knight, or trade it, which will either enable
us to get the bishop pair if Black takes with the bishop, or, possibly, take
exd5 and put more pressure on the e5-pawn. Another very important thing is
that Black cannot castle long here, or, at least, this won't be easy at all.
Now, the issue is that castling short is dangerous strategically as it will
drive the king too far away from the center while staying in the center is
dangerous because even though this is a queenless middlegame, there are a lot
of pieces and the king might run into some checks/pins/attack. Finally, let's
start discussing the Black moves. I believe it's not as much about the moves,
as it is about plans, so let's focus on Black's very main continuation ...Nf6,
while briefly mentioning minor tries.} Nf6 (7... f6 {I am not a fan of this
move which was played by Hebden and Galego, both 2500+ players. The idea is to
protect the e5-pawn and prepare the move ...Na5! Now, because Black just
weakened the a2-g8 diagonal, it makes sense to keep the bishop there, so I
like the very logical continuation} 8. a3 {Very important! The bishop is now
ready to retreat to a2 in the event of ...Na5.} Nge7 9. Be3 Ng6 10. O-O-O Nf8 {
Black is forced to spend a lot of time in order to prepare ...Be6, obstructing
the a2-g8 diagonal.} 11. Nd2 {This is a very nice move. The ideas include
protecting the c4-bishop as well as possibly preparing f2-f4! Why is f2-f4
potentially strong if it might spoil our structure? Well, we are much better
developed, so we need to open the position up!} a6 12. f4 {This is consistent,
but I find it a little rushed.} (12. Nb3 {Is an even better move, preparing
Nc5 and Nd5 and opening up the d-file.} Be6 13. Nd5 Ne7 14. Nc5 {Black's
position is terrible.}) 12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Ng6 14. Bg3 {White did keep some
initiative, but enabled Black to solidify his position and get a firm controll
of the e5-square. I think we should continue the unrushed play with that
Nd2-b3-c5 idea. 1-0 (44) Gokerkan,C (2452) - Haznedaroglu,K (2461) Kemer 2019})
8. Be3 {We continue the logical development. Now, Black has a few choices -
not even move-wise, but regarding the character of the arising position. Say, .
..Be6 will give him the doubled pawns, while castling will drive his king away
from the center. Some other moves, instead, such as ...Be7, keep the tension
for now. So, we should discuss all those scenarios.} Be6 {This is,
surprisingly, a novelty, but I believe that's one of the best decisions
available to Black out there. While the arising position will be quite
unpleasant for him, it is rather tenable, objectively. Which, of course,
should not discourage us from going for that position as we'll be the one
having all the fun!} (8... O-O {This is the most popular move and the one I
call a nearly losing mistake! Be careful and attentive as this is your chance
to punish those guys.} 9. Bc5 Re8 10. Ng5 {This is it. Black has to go ...Be6
and get only a knight for that bishop as well as a handful of weaknesses.} Be6
11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bb5 {Another excellent move, which was found in most games.
The idea is to take on c6, and this cannot be stopped.} Be7 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14.
Bxe7 Rxe7 15. O-O-O {This is it. The position here is not just somewhat better,
it is completely resignable for Black. Why so? He has too many pawn weaknesses.
Way too many. For example, the plan of Rd2/d3 followed by doubling rooks on
the d-file, playing f2-f3, and then re-routing our knight via a4 to c5, or via
d1 and e3 to c4 should suffice, as one of the Black pawns will inevitably fall.
Just for your record, White scored 12/12 from here.}) (8... Be7 {With a move
like this, Black tries to not only activate the bishop, but also prepare the
maneuvre ...Bd6 and ...Ke7 followed by ...Be6. We should be by all means
discouraging and stopping this plan, because if Black manages to play that,
his position would become very solid and nearly equal.} 9. Nd5 {This is a very
important idea, as we take advantage of the hanging pawn on c7. Now, to play ..
.Bd8 is kind of silly, so all the Black players preferred ...Bd6 here.} Bd6 10.
Nxf6+ {Now, however, we get the benefit of spoiling the opponent's structure.}
gxf6 11. Nh4 {Another neat move - we increase our control over the f5-square,
possibly planning to land there with the knight. That would be extremely
efficient especially if the light-squared bishops were absent. But, oftentimes
even with the bishops that would be very strong, as it could force Black to
part with his bishop pair or tolerate that monstrous knight.} Rg8 {1/2 (77)
Van der Wiel,J (2465) - Nikolic,P (2330) Valetta 1980} 12. g3 {I like this
idea better as it immediately renders the g8-rook useless. Instead, after 12.
h3, as was played in the game, we still need to play something like g2-g4,
which might give Black counterplay on the account of the weakened dark squares
on f4 and g5 as well as the possible ...h7-h5 break.} Be6 13. Bb5 {I want to
take that c6-knight! Let me show you why this is an interesting plan.
Objectively, we are already going too deep in the jungles of a relatively
unimportant position, but as you might know from my previous courses, I
typically extend my ambitions beyond the desire to just teach you the opening
all the way to the middlegame/endgame instruction. Sorry, the coach inside me
cannot help himself - this is just really important for your growth!} O-O-O 14.
Bxc6 bxc6 15. b3 {White's idea now is to just play Ke2 and take the d-file,
and possibly, he wants to play c2-c4, killing that e6-bishop completely! All
the Black pawns might fall prey to our minor pieces once the rooks are swapped
- for example, those a and h-pawns can't be protected by any other pawns! And
the Black bishops are rather useless, too. Importantly, often we can play Nf5
as if Black trades, the endgame with the dark-squared bishops will just be
dead-lost for him!}) 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Ke2 {My favorite move, instead of
castling. The reason is that several pieces already got traded, so there's no
point in driving the king all the way back to c1. It'll be equally safe and
potentially move useful on e2.} Be7 11. Ng5 {Another key maneuvre. The knight
wasn't doing anything on f3, so we re-route it. Where is it going? Let's see!}
Nd8 12. f3 h6 13. Nh3 Nc6 14. Rhd1 {The knight is coming to f2 in order to be
able to come to d3. On the order hand, our other knight can travel to c4 after
moves like a2-a4! to prevent ...b7-b5, followed by Nb1-d2-c4 and c2-c3. The
pressure on the e5 and the e6-pawns is very unpleasant and the removal of the
rooks might only hurt Black as our king will easily make its way to the center.
I am definitely not claiming White is winning here, but I do claim that
Black's life would be very difficult, with his defensive task being dull and
thankless. I would evaluate this position as something between White's small
and serious advantage, like half a pawn.} *

