{[%evp 0,17,21,34,28,28,21,5,15,-14,2,16,16,41,17,-4,3,55,46,36]} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 {In this chapter, we'll speak about all the sidelines
Black has in the Evans. Or, to use different wording, about everything Black
can do against our dear gambit except for 4.b4 Bxb4 5.c3 Ba5 and 5.c3 Be7, the
two main moves. It was definitely possible to discuss everything in one
chapter, but I don't want to overwhelm you with the information. In fact, I've
covered those sidelines in more detail than one would require in practical
settings, but as usual, the goal of the course is to provide you with all the
solutions you might need, so that you never wonder what you should do versus
this or that variation.} Bb6 {Actually, I was surprised to see this move
played a few times in a row (!) by no less than Carlsen in his online match
versus Grischuk. Why would that happen? Carlsen should definitely know how to
deal with the Evans Gambit, shouldn't he? My reasoning was that either he
wasn't feeling like going for the main lines, which would mean it's quite
interesting an opening for White if the World Champion is somewhat afraid of
it, or that he thought 4...Bb6 was a very decent continuation, too. Anyway, we
need to check this move! To be honest, though, I am not sure about its
objective merits. Black definitely is not getting killed or anything, but
White has chances to fight for some advantage without risking much - what's
not to like?} (4... Be7 {Surprisingly, it's not that easy to refute this move!
And by refuting, I don't even mean beating Black by force, but even getting a
clear-cut advantage. I believe White's best move that secures an edge might be
5.a3, where he reaches the improved version of the slow Italian positions, but
it kinda doesn't fit with our gambit-style play, so we will look at the more
unique-flavored} 5. b5 Na5 6. Bd3 {This is a really strange position, isn't
it! And, as you might know, based on my previous works, this is something very
typical of my repertoires as we have a novelty right here on move 6. Why do we
go here and not on e2? The idea is to keep the e4-pawn protected, because
after 6.Be2 d5! is very strong.} (6. Be2 d5 {That's why I cannot recommend
this move. Now either after 7.Nxe5 dxe4, or after 7.d3 I don't think White is
better.}) (6. Nxe5 {This is mostly being played, but after} Nxc4 7. Nxc4 d5 8.
exd5 Qxd5 {Black attacks the g2 and the b5-pawns and I cannot see why we
should be happy to go here.}) 6... d6 {Black has to protect the e5-pawn.} 7.
O-O Nf6 8. Re1 {We prepare the retreat square on f1 for the bishop and protect
the e4-pawn one more time.} O-O 9. h3 {Stopping ...Bg4 sounds like a good idea.
Now, let's stop for a second and try to understand what we are playing for
here. The main liability of our opponent is his a5-knight, which is really
misplaced. It's not possible to explain what it's doing on a5. Nor it is easy
to understand how the knight will return back to the game, as ...c7-c6 can
always be met with a2-a4. We won't study this position too deeply, but I can
give a sample line, such as} c6 10. a4 Be6 11. Bf1 Re8 12. d3 {White will
follow up with Nbd2, Bb2, possibly with c2-c4 at some point. The only problem
with this position that I have - not myself, but thinking of you, the students
of this repertoire - is that it's not a very typical Evans-type position. But
the good news is that we will keep the obvious advantage thanks to the fact
Black is nearly a piece down, his knight is absolutely terrible. There's no
forced win or anything, just a very pleasant position where we can increase
edge without any rush.}) (4... d5 {This might look extremely unexpected, but
in fact, this move was tried by several 2300 and 2400± rated players! Black
is seeking to counterattack the center and to lure our bishop on d5, so that ..
.Nxb4 comes with a tempo on the bishop if White takes with the piece, or if
White takes with the pawn, then after ...Nxb4 the d5-pawn is under some
serious pressure.} 5. exd5 {I believe this is the right way to take, as we
open up the e-file.} Nxb4 6. O-O {Development almost always comes first in the
open games, and this position is no exception.} Nxd5 7. Nxe5 Ngf6 {Now that
the e5-pawn has been eliminated, White gets the advantage very easily.} 8. d4
Be7 9. Bb3 O-O 10. c4 {White just got the free center. He will follow up with
Nc3 and then Qd3 and Bc2 in order to start applying pressure over the b1-h7
diagonal. Later, he'll continue with the normal developing moves, such as Bg5,
Rad1, Rfe1, and so on. Black's position is clearly very unpleasant as we have
the center - and as a result, some serious spatial advantage, too.}) (4... Nxb4
{This move is definitely possible, but it has no independent value, as after}
5. c3 Nc6 {This is something people used to do back in the day as Black,
trying to control the d4-square and a lot of lovely miniatures have been
created from now on. Nowadays, it's known this isn't the best move available
to the opponent as after d2-d4! White gains the center while also winning a
