{[%evp 0,25,21,28,21,21,21,16,6,-15,-30,-29,15,-34,-39,-42,-49,-53,-60,-64,-63,
-61,-49,-49,-29,-64,-70,-86]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 {
Now, it's time to analyze the two main defenses - 5...Ba5! and 5...Be7! Black
can definitely equalize in both, but the positions remain interesting and fun
to play and as far as I am aware, there is no mathematically forced perpetual
check or dead-drawn endgame or something, so you won't need to fear opponent's
amazing preparation that can just kill the game. If they are prepared, they
equalize, but we get to play exciting and ambitious chess, nevertheless.} Ba5 {
This is the most popular move by far. The goal of this move is not to allow d4
when White can meet ...exd4 with cxd4, as the c3-pawn is pinned. Additionally,
unlike in the situations with the bishop on c5, Black's bishop isn't getting
hit with tempo.} (5... Be7 {This is the second move popularity-wise and my
choice for Black in my full 1.e4 e5 Black repertoire 'Unleash the Bull'. Of
course, I analyzed the Evans gambit a lot as I was preparing that course. And,
obviously, the evaluation is absolutely correct - Black is perfectly fine. But,
after the publication, I had to dig into this deeper as I was teaching Evans
to a few private students of mine - not because this is some very best weapon
against 1.e4 e5 or anything, but because I think it's a fantastic tool to
develop your feel for the initiative. At the same time, it's worth mentioning
that - as weird as it sounds! - some important things have happened in chess
during the last year, namely Lc0, the neural engine, appeared and many
evaluations have changed, as a result. So, while we won't be able to claim any
advantage in this line if Black did his homework well, we'll be sure to
surprise Black with a handful of new interesting dangerous ideas.} 6. d4 (6.
Qb3 {Objectively, this is a questionable move but it was tried even by
Morozevich so I should briefly cover it. White wants to attack the f7-pawn as
quickly as possible.} Nh6 7. d4 {Now White threatens to take the h6-knight and
the f7-pawn.} Na5 {Black immediately grabs our bishop pair.} 8. Qb5 Nxc4 9.
Bxh6 gxh6 10. Qxc4 {This position is even a bit better for Black, but he needs
to find the precise move here} d6 {To my surprise, this was only played in
about 20 out of the more than 100 games that reached this position!} 11. Nbd2
Rg8 {It is also possible for Black to castle, but I find that position a bit
suspicious.} 12. O-O Bh3 13. Ne1 {For now, the position of the knight looks
ugly, but White will untangle with Kh1 or Qd3 and follow up with f2-f4. At
this point, we are on completely unexplored territory. The engine says it's -0.
25 at a very high depth, which, of course, cannot be called a theoretical
success for White. However, this is a complicated position so who the hell
cares what the engine says if you know it better than your opponent does and
enjoy playing unbalanced positions? As I said, Qd3 and f2-f4 are coming, and
it's not too easy for Black to understand what to do with his king. So,
practically speaking, I do think it's worth going here as White at least
sometimes - maybe often if you're 2000 or lower, or you can have it as a
surprise/rapid/blitz-weapon if you are a titled player like myself.}) 6... Na5
{The most practical reply and the one I give in my Black repertoire.} (6... d6
7. Qb3 {This is a serious mistake as now f7 cannot be protected. And the best
Black can do is go 7...Na5 and transpose in the lines with 6...exd4 7.Qb3 Na5,
having lost that important ...c7-c6! idea which I suggest as an improvement
for Black.}) (6... exd4 {Taking this pawn is very dangerous.} 7. Qb3 {Taking
this pawn is very dangerous.} Na5 (7... d5 {This pawn sacrifice does not solve
Black's issues.} 8. Bxd5 {This pawn sacrifice does not resolve Black's issues.}
Na5 (8... Be6 9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. Qxb7 {The material is equal, but White's
initiative is decisive.}) 9. Bxf7+ {This is more sound, but not too fun,
either.} Kf8 10. Qa4 Kxf7 {The bishop on f7 will be lost inevitably, but we
get that knight on a5 in return.} 11. Qxa5 {Again, we have a huge advantage
thanks to Black's woeful king. And we are not even down any material! All we
need to do is castle and bring the remainder of the pieces in. At the same
time, it's worth considering immediate aggression with moves like Ne5+,
Qa4-c4+ and so on.}) 8. Bxf7+ {This variation has the right to exist, but
White ends up better off, both practically and objectively.} Kf8 9. Qa4 Kxf7
10. Qxa5 d6 {That's what people - even such GMs as Sandipan and Degraeve
mostly do as Black, but his position is really bad here. Black is getting
ready to develop his bishop to e6 or g4.} (10... c6 {Although this is Black's
best move, it has only been played 6 times.} 11. Qf5+ Nf6 12. e5 d6 {Here we
have a choice between 13.e6 and 13.Qf4, both of which should yield us a
slightly better position.} 13. e6+ {To take isn't possible as Ng5+ forks the
Black king and bishop, which means Black has to retreat, but then this pawn on
e6 gains a lot of potential! Black still has some work to do in order to get
his pieces well-organized and coordinated.}) 11. Qd5+ {Again, an improvement
over the main move cxd4, this check has been seen in one game only. The point
is that after taking Black can annoy our queen with ...c7-c6, begging for a
trade and stopping the checks. So, we check first.} Kf8 12. cxd4 Nf6 13. Qb3
Nxe4 14. O-O {White's initiative is terrific because we control the key a2-g8
diagonal which means Black cannot organize his kingside pieces in a proper
