this is a tremendously important improvement for White, but he ends up
equalizing thanks to this move. For example, after} O-O 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. c4 {
White has an extra central pawn and he deprived the opponent of the bishop
pair. But, if Black knows what to do, he will get easy equality. To be more
precise, he just needs to play ...c7-c6! to restrict White's center. After
that, the simple moves ...Be6 and ...Rad8 will clearly be good enough. I am
trying to be as objective as possible here: as Black, I don't fear this
position as it's easy equality. As White, I might consider going for it in an
occasional rapid game as I don't think Black has enough challenges to be
troubled in a classical game. All in all, it's just a move, not better or
worse than others. But, of course, if this was my main suggestion or the best
option I had for White, I wouldn't have created this repertoire at all.}) 7...
d6 {The most solid defense. Instead of grabbing everything he was offered,
Black returns his extra pawn.} (7... exd4 {As usual in the Evans Gambit, I
don't approve of Black's greed, attempts to grab the pawns or open the
position up.} 8. cxd4 {As usual, I don't approve of Black's greed in the Evans
gambit. By the way, 8.0-0 is also interesting if you feel like sacrificing
even more.} d5 {By the way, 8.0-0 is also interesting if you feel like
sacrificing even more.} 9. exd5 {While this move involves creating an isolated
