queen back and reaches and equal endgame. Funny, isn't it?} 13. Bxd7+ Kxd7 14.
cxd4 {Actually, I would imagine Black would still need to be careful here
because of the White's impressive center, but okay, objectively Black is fine.}
) 9... exd4 10. O-O (10. Qa4+ {Again, this looks tempting, but after} Kd8 {
it turns out that taking the bishop is too dangerous, we should refrain from
allowing Black to force our king in the open space.} 11. Qxa5 Qxe4+) 10... Bb6
11. Bb2 dxc3 12. Nxc3 Nf6 {As a result, we get a position where White is a
pawn down, but his development is excellent. I would definitely pick White,
especially because he has another beautiful resource that improves his
position greatly.} 13. Na4 {We also pick up the bishop pair.} O-O 14. Nxb6 axb6
15. Rae1 {The bishop pair and the powerful center together with the excellent
positions of all the pieces provide us with more than sufficient compensation
for the sacrificed pawn - in a practical game White is massively for choice.
Objectively, his advantage might be just slight, but I can imagine that ideas
like Re3-g3!, f2-f4 and e4-e5, Qg3, etc can put an immense amount of pressure
on Black really fast.}) 8. O-O Bb6 {Black needs to know this non-trivial move
or else he lands in a lot of trouble. Now, we again reach a position where
while Black can equalize, he needs to be extremely careful.} (8... Nf6 9. dxe5
{Black loses a pawn as taking back results in tons of trouble after} Nxe4 (9...
dxe5 10. Rd1 Qe7 11. Ba3 {Suddenly the queen ends up trapped.}) 10. Re1 Nc5 11.
exd6+ {White clearly gets a very powerful initiative as Black loses the
castling rights, unless he wants to get into even more trouble after} Ne6 12.
Ng5) 9. Nbd2 {Not the most popular move, but a rather popular one as of late,
as Safarli used it in a must-win situation against Nihal Sarin at the World
Cup in 2019, while Mamedyarov, Short and many other strong players also gave
it a try over the last few years. Black needs to know this non-trivial move or
else he lands in a lot of trouble.} Na5 {Black grabs our powerful bishop.} 10.
Qc2 Nxc4 11. Nxc4 {Now, however, the e5-pawn turns out to be under lots of
pressure.} Qc6 {In my opinion, this is pretty much the only move that saves
Black from massive trouble. Pay attention, guys - Ding Liren and many other
strong players didn't find it!} (11... exd4 {This is what Ding did against
Mamedyarov, but Black's position becomes really bad very quickly.} 12. cxd4 Ne7
{White's center is extremely impressive, so is the fact Black hasn't developed
and castled yet. We will be able to capitalize on this!} 13. a4 c6 {a4-a5 is
too serious a threat.} 14. Ba3 Bc7 {Mamedyarov keeps creating threats with
every move.} 15. e5 dxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17. Rfd1 Qe8 18. Nd6 {White's advantage
was nearly decisive, but Black managed to save half a point with the
combination of stubborn defense and luck. Please take a look at the rest of
the game in the chapter on model games. 1/2 (39) Mamedyarov,S (2747) - Ding,L 
(2766) Huaian 2016}) 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 {White gets his pawn
back and opens up the position, which is extremely favorable as we are ahead
in development. This is an equal position, objectively, but I definitely like
White better here practically and the results prove my opinion as White scored
4/6, having won two games, drawn 4 and lost none. We will cut the trainable
variation here, but will analyze this position and what to do next in more
detail in the chapter on model games. 1-0 (31) Lomasov,S (2549) - Lysyj,I 
(2630) Yaroslavl 2018}) 7. Qb3 {I believe this is a much better move than the
more popular castling, as we are applying immediate pressure on that f7-pawn
as well as not allowing Black to develop with ...Nge7 and 0-0.} Qe7 (7... Qf6 {
This is another possibility, but it's somewhat less reliable and natural. Here,
we simply castle.} 8. O-O {Now, we won't go in too much detail, but we will
definitely look at a few sample lines.} Bb6 {The most popular move which takes
care of the d4-pawn.} (8... Nge7 {To develop is also possible, but White gets
the pawn back.} 9. cxd4 O-O (9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. Bxf7+ {This is a
disaster for Black.}) 10. Bg5 Qd6 {This is the right move that has never been
played, but it's clear that Black cannot be fine with such ugly pieces. A tear
starts falling down my cheek when I look at those queenside pieces and the
queen in front of the d7-pawn.} (10... Qg6 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Qa3 {Oops - a
double attack! White wins something as} Nc6 {fails to the obvious} 13. d5 {
and the a5-bishop will be lost.}) 11. Na3 {The most precise move - the knight
is coming on b5 or on c2 and e3.} a6 12. Nc2 {White's advantage is large and
stable here due to his powerful center and the much better pieces.}) 9. e5 {
This cool move breaks the coordination between the queen and the d4-pawn.} Qg6
(9... Nxe5 10. Re1 d6 11. cxd4 {And White wins a piece because of the pin.})
10. cxd4 {Now, Black is facing an important choice - whether to grab the pawn
with ...Nxd4 or the bishop pair with ...Na5.} Na5 (10... Nxd4 {I find this
capture to be too greedy and uprepared.} 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12. Nc3 {Now, Ba3 is up
and coming.} Ne7 13. Ba3 {Again, Black cannot castle!} b6 {This is a rather
difficult idea to find - Black ignores his kingside and wants to go ...Bb7 and
counterattack. At this point, moves like Rad1 are very decent, but I like the
breathtaking} 14. Nb5 Bxa1 15. Rxa1 Bb7 16. Nxc7+ Kd8 17. f3 {Come on, who
would think Black can survive with the king on d8? The engine still thinks
it's okay for Black, but I won't bet a dime on anyone being ready to defend as
Black here, this looks outrageously dangerous!}) 11. Qa4 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Ne7 13.
Ba3 {While equality isn't too far away, I feel Black's position is still
rather tricky as he cannot castle yet and our pieces are a lot more active.
Let's stop here, as it's already not about theory at all - next, you just use
your dynamic understanding! (My course on that is about to follow).
Self-advertising aside, just enjoy the position where all of your pieces are
already on great spots and prepare to join the game with your b1-knight and
the rooks.}) 8. O-O Bb6 {The best defense, as Black immediately avoids all the
hassle with the potentially insecure bishop and protects the d4-pawn. At this
point, White has a plethora of options. Again, objectively this definitely is
equal, but I don't think that handling this is necessarily easy and pleasant
for Black, especially as we have this excellent novelty on move 16.} (8... d6
9. e5 {As usual, we want to open up the files and diagonals as our lead in
development is really strong. Black's position is already extremely dangerous,
for example} Nxe5 (9... dxe5 10. cxd4 {This important novelty (almost a
novelty, there was only 1 game here!!) changes the evaluation of the line, as
previously 10.Ba3 was played, but Black does have ways to survive there. Now,
we just want to take on e5 and claim a powerful initiative without any
sacrifices. I don't really see an appealing move for Black here. The engine
believes Black is nearly lost and gives 10... exd4 as the best move, but I
won't go into this as opening the files and lines and ranks like this clearly
requires being a computer. And it's still terrible! Feel free to check out
yourself how to finish Black off here.}) 10. Nxe5 Qxe5 11. Bxf7+ {This is
clearly extremely dangerous as well as objectively bad.}) (8... Nf6 {Not a
great move, but it's not a terrible one, either. The only high-level game
where both players were 2400+ that reached this position was Stopa -
Bartholomew, where Black had a hard time getting out of the opening.} 9. cxd4 (
9. Ba3 {Is another interesting opportunity you can investigate.}) 9... Nxe4 {
Black has to take, or else he's still suffering, but for no compensation at
all.} 10. Ba3 Nd6 (10... d6 11. d5 {Again, Qa4+ is going to be a problem as
the a5-bishop is about to lose its only defender.} Ne5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Bb2 {
The next move will be Qa4+ and White inevitably wins a piece.}) 11. Nc3 O-O 12.
Rae1 {White is just mobilizing all of his forces. We are two pawns down, but
it doesn't matter, because this is the wrong count! The right count starts
when you look at the a8-rook, the c8-bishop, the a5-bishop. How about the
d6-knight? We are several pieces up, that's what I call it.} Qd8 (12... Qf6 {
This just runs into even more time-winning threatening moves.} 13. Nd5 Qg6 14.
Bd3 Qh5 15. Re5 {Sorry, I know I'm being somewhat unpractical, but I couldn't
