while after} Nxe5 16. dxe5 {White is winning literally everything.}) 13. Bxd6
cxd6 14. Bxf7+ {Thanks to this nice tactic, we win a pawn back. Thanks to some
nice tactic, we win a pawn back.} Kh8 (14... Rxf7 15. Ng5 {And Black loses
because after} Qf8 16. Nxf7 {He cannot take back.} Qxf7 17. Re8# {A nice
finish!}) 15. Bd5 {I think it's a good position to stop at as White is totally
dominating the board while being just one pawn down. Even that extra d-pawn is
doubled, so it makes no difference! Just as the best traditions of gambits
teach us, we have managed to paralyze and blockade Black's entire queenside.
Things look just terrible for the second player.}) 9. cxd4 {The main move for
White and the one I like best. But, in case you are looking to expand your
repertoire, do look at 9.Nbd2, it's a very decent continuation as well.} Nxd4
10. Nxd4 Bxd4 11. Nc3 {Now the threat is Nd5.} Nf6 (11... d6 12. Rd1 {First,
we win a tempo.} Be5 13. Nd5 Qd8 14. Rb1 {Black won't be able to develop as
f2-f4 is a huge threat which cannot be stopped.}) 12. Ba3 {The main line, I do
like this move.} (12. Bg5 {This is another very tempting opportunity that
Lysyj describes in his book for Black as an 'aggressive and undeservingly rare
move, as it's very difficult for Black to extinguish White's activity'. Again,
feel free to investigate a little deeper yourself. For example, after} O-O 13.
Nd5 Qd6 14. Rad1 {White clearly gets a ton of initiative, even though the
engine keeps insisting it's a 0.00 type of position. Let your opponents prove
that equality!}) (12. Nb5 {Another fun move, which I won't analyze, but I do
want you to be aware of its existence.}) 12... d6 13. Rad1 (13. Bxf7+ {It's
possible to regain one pawn in such a way, but as Lysyj correctly points out,
it's not good for White.} Qxf7 14. Qa4+ Bd7 15. Qxd4 O-O {Black finished his
development, has no weaknesses, and is a pawn up.}) 13... Bxc3 14. Qxc3 {
Now e4-e5 is a threat. The simple Re1 is also quite annoying.} Qe5 (14... O-O
15. Rfe1 {Now e4-e5 can barely be stopped, so Black's only move is} Ng4 {
but then White gets a terrific initiative with} 16. f4 {Qg3 is about to create
new threats, White's dark-squared bishop is already exercising a lot of
pressure and can always come to b2 to annoy Black even more. This position is
extremely dangerous for him.}) 15. Qc1 {Again, I agree with Lysyj that this is
the best move for White, as he avoids the queen trade and prepares f2-f4 as
well as Bb2 and Rfe1.} O-O 16. Rfe1 {Here is my suggested novelty, which is
very exciting for White. Lysyj doesn't analyze it at all in his excellent move,
which is understandable given this book is rather old and my faithful friend
Lc0 didn't exist back then. It's not even clear what move Black should make as
f2-f4 and e4-e5 is coming!} (16. Bb2 {The actual main line that has been
featured in multiple correspondence games. Feel free to investigate it
yourself, as I don't think we need 10 interesting options analyzed in the
repertoire. A few that I already gave should more than suffice!}) 16... Re8 {
The right solution as Black escapes the pin down the a3-f8 diagonal.} 17. Bb2
Qh5 {The right defense, objectively. To be honest, I have no faith at all that
any Black player would be able to reach this position OTB unless they are a
well-prepared titled player, or maybe even rather a GM. Still, even here White
retains very nice compensation. Say,} (17... Qe7 18. Re3 {I believe White is
