{[%evp 0,11,21,21,21,21,21,14,14,0,365,35,37,54]} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4
Nf6 4. Ng5 {Welcome to the second part of this repertoire - the romantic Two
Knights with 4.Ng5! This is definitely an extremely interesting line, which I
chose for several reasons. First of all, I firmly believe it's a very
ambitious attempt where White has good chances for the opening advantage.
Obviously, 1.e4 e5! is a rock-solid defense which I love from the Black side,
too. But, while Black should clearly be able to equalize in all the lines
after 1.e4 e5, and often in many ways, this move is something that would force
him to know as much as possible. This suggestion of mine clearly fits well
with what I am recommending against 3...Bc5. Also, a very important
consideration I had in mind while making this repertoire is that since this is
a Chessable course - exactly a Chessable course, and not some random DVD or
something - we need to make the maximum use of MoveTrainer technology. In the
sharp line, this tool will serve us best! This chapter is devoted to all the
sidelines Black can try and throw at us, starting from 4...Bc5 and 4...d5 5.
exd5 Nxd5 to 5...b5, 5...Nd4, etc. The main position of the 4.Ng5 line, which
arises after 4...d5 5.exd5 Na5 6.Bb5+ c6 7.dxc6 bxc6 will be covered in the
following chapters. Since this chapter is devoted to Black's sidelines, it is
obvious that we will be able to keep an advantage - often, even get a winning
position after the opening! - but some lines are rather tricky and require a
rather careful handling, so be attentive! Let's dive in.} d5 (4... Nxe4 {
Okay, this is clearly terrible. But, surprisingly, a few players over 2300
have tried this move once or twice. Let's see how we refute it.} 5. Bxf7+ {
It's very important to take exactly in this manner, as the explanations given
after 5. Nxf7? and 5.Nxe4? show.} (5. Nxe4 d5 {Again, this is not good for
White. As terrible as Black's 4th move is, we still need to be careful and
aware of opponent's ideas.}) (5. Nxf7 Qh4 {Is exactly what Black wants - now
he is even better!}) 5... Ke7 6. d4 {We open the position up as much as we can.
When the opponent's king has lost the castling rights and is stuck in the
center, this is the right thing to do, as Morphy and Anderssen taught us with
their brilliant games.} h6 (6... Nxd4 {As usual, greed is no good, especially
when your king is on e7.} 7. Bd5 Nf6 8. Nf7 {White is winning tons of material
and the game.} Qe8 9. Nxh8 Nxd5 10. c3 {The last important point - even though
our knight is stuck in the corner, it doesn't bother us, as we win one of the
Black horses as well!}) 7. Nxe4 Kxf7 8. d5 {Now the knight will get kicked out
and Black loses.} Nd4 (8... Ne7 9. d6 {This is clearly terrible as well as now
our knight lands on d6 and the Black king's life is in jeopardy.}) 9. c3 Nf5
10. Qf3 {g2-g4 is coming, White is winning that knight.}) (4... Bc5 {This
defense, the so-called Traxler counterattack, does contain a few traps, but
nowadays it's pretty much common knowledge that Black is nearly lost after
this move.} 5. Bxf7+ {The cleanest solution. I won't go into too much detail,
but 5.Nxf7 is believed to be a forced draw or nearly so.} Ke7 (5... Kf8 6. Bb3
{Black's idea is to bring the queen to g6 via e8 and use the f-file for his
rook. We'll see those ideas after 5...Ke7, but 5...Kf8 is just a worse version
of that line for Black as the king is in the rook's way.}) 6. Bc4 {This is a
rather rare move, which was seen in 84 games only out of more than 1600 games
that featured this position. I believe it's White's best move as the bishop is
likely to be able to help us defend by returning to e2! This idea has been
enjoying quite some popularity in correspondence chess, which is a sign of
very high quality.} Rf8 7. O-O {Now, Black has two attempts that make sense.
He should either play ...Qe8, trying to bring it to g6 and get some initiative
going, or play 7...h6 in order to deflect our knight from the e4-pawn and win
that pawn. The latter is what people mostly did, but I think the former choice
is Black's best try.} Qe8 (7... h6 8. Nf3 Nxe4 {Black did get his pawn back,
but just for an instant. The position opened up a lot, which is extremely
dangerous for the opponent as his king is on e7!} 9. Bd5 {A double attack on
c6 and e4, the point being to take on c6 and then win the e5-pawn. It's worth
mentioning 9. d4!? is also very interesting, but I find the solution in the
text the cleanest one.} Nf6 (9... Nxf2 {In the only game that reached this
position, Black chose to give up two pieces for the rook in order to force the
White king on f2 and to avoid losing the e5-pawn. I cannot really judge this
decision, because, as my first coach used to say, 'In a bad position all the
moves are bad.' No matter whether Black took this pawn or retreated, he'd find
himself on the verge of losing.} 10. Rxf2 Bxf2+ 11. Kxf2 d6 12. d3 {White is
simply nearly winning, because while the material is level from the purely
arithmetical viewpoint (we have two pieces for the rook and a pawn), the minor
pieces are a lot better in such positions, as the rooks lack open files and
cannot prove too useful. For example, in this position, Black's rook does have
a semi-open f-file, but it's barely possible to explain how it can create any
threats there. Our goal should be to hide the king on g1 to get rid of the pin
and follow with the logical developing moves, such as Be3, Nbd2/Nc3, Qe2, Re1/
f1, and so on. We can also consider taking on c6 at some point in order to
deprive Black of the last drops of counterplay. White is already almost
winning.}) 10. Bxc6 dxc6 11. Nxe5 {Now Ng6+ is a threat.} Re8 12. c3 {The last
precise move - we prepare d2-d4 followed by the rapid development of our
queenside.} Kf8 13. d4 Bd6 14. Bf4 {White is a healthy pawn up and the Black
king still isn't entirely safe. I believe, at this point it's obvious that
Black's hopes to have fun with the move 4...Bc5 have been put to an end.}) 8.
Nc3 Qg6 {Black isn't really threatening anything, but he does have a bit of
activity now. Black isn't really threatening with anything, but he does have a
bit of activity now.} 9. Be2 {I like this idea as we get ourselves ready for
all the possible ...Bg4 ideas in the future, which would have otherwise been
annoying after Black would play ...d7-d6. Besides controlling the g4-square
better, we also reinforce our control over the h5-square. Now, I see two
principled choices for Black - regaining the pawn with 9...h6 or continuing
the development with 9...d6. Analyzing this position deeply might sound like
overkill as it's already brand-new with no games in it, but I would still like
to offer you a few lines to make sure you are prepared well enough for
anything you might encounter.} d6 (9... h6 10. Nf3 Nxe4 11. Nxe5 {Several
other solutions are also good, but this is the most brutal refutation of
Black's idea.} Nxe5 12. Nd5+ Kd8 (12... Kd6 {The Black monarch's desire to
take a guided tour to the middle of the board will backfire badly.} 13. d4 Kxd5
14. dxc5+ Ke6 15. f4 Nc6 {Or else Black wouldn't even keep that piece that he
had grabbed so greedily on d5. Or ese Black wouldn't even keep that piece that
he had grabbed so greedily on d5.} 16. f5+ {A fork!} Rxf5 17. Rxf5 {17.Bg4
also wins, but this is way stronger.} Kxf5 (17... Qxf5 18. Bg4 {We win a queen
because of the pin.}) 18. Bh5 Qh7 19. Qd5+ Ne5 20. Be3 {21.Rf1 with a mate is
unstoppable. This, perhaps, was too long a line - much longer a line than was
required - but it is nice to understand how badly Black can get punished for
this greed.}) 13. d4 {We fork the opponent's minor pieces and get the
sacrificed piece back. Now Black is forced to do something like} Nxf2 {the
alternatives are even worse for him.} 14. Rxf2 Rxf2 15. Kxf2 Qf7+ 16. Nf4 Bb6
17. Kg1 {Even though the material is currently equal, White is nearly winning
as he'll easily develop and the Black king on d8 will prove extremely
vulnerable and misplaced.}) 10. d3 Nd4 {Now we just need to trade down a few
pieces and convert our extra pawn in the endgame.} 11. Na4 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 Bg4
13. Qe1 {We will trade the bishop on c5 and will just continue with f2-f3,
keeping the extra pawn for no compensation. We could have stopped here if it
wasn't for one important line.} h6 {Suddenly our knight is trapped. This also
leads to a lost position, but is Black's best chance.} 14. Nxc5 dxc5 15. Qe3
hxg5 16. Qxc5+ Kf7 17. Qxe5 {We got three pawns for the knight and will
inevitably get four as both c7 and g5 are hanging. For example, after} Kg8 18.
Qxg5 Qxg5 19. Bxg5 {Black is totally lost as this pawn mass in the center will
just start rolling. It's scary and inevitable, Black cannot do anything about
it. f2-f3, d3-d4, c2-c4, Rad1, Rfe1, etc. Run, run, run. Get a bunch of queens
and make the opponent resign. Quite easy, isn't it?}) 5. exd5 {Now, 5...Na5 is
the very main line and the only sound move. But, we also need to refute a
handful of other possibilities, such as 5...Nxd5, 5...b5, and 5...Nd4.} Na5 {
Finally we get to the main line! We will discuss Black's very main
continuations in the following chapters, but now we'll already start analyzing
this move, or more precisely, Black's minor tries in it. What's the idea of
going to the edge with the knight? Well, as we saw, Black cannot afford to
take on d5 right away. So, he hopes to drive the White bishop somewhere back
and capture the pawn later. But, the issue is that is allows for a nasty check.
} (5... Nxd5 {This move is known to be bad for a long time. Actually, 6.Nxf7
has been known to be the refutation for hundreds of years and it even obtained
the meaty name 'The Fried Liver Attack'. But, I think another continuation is
even better and it requires less memorization. While 6.Nxf7 is by all means
very attractive and strong, it's even easier to kill Black with another move
while also cutting down on some work. Be very careful, because especially if
you're a club player, this is the mistake you'll face PLENTY!} 6. d4 {We are
immediately opening up the center. Another important thing is that we are
protecting the g5-knight, thus creating threats like Qf3, hitting the f7-pawn
and the d5-knight.} Nxd4 {I think this relatively rare (third most popular)
move is Black's only chance to survive.} (6... Be7 {Black's second popular
move, which also runs in a typical sacrifice.} 7. Nxf7 Kxf7 8. Qf3+ Ke6 {
Other moves aren't critical at all - this way Black, at least, protects his
knight on d5.} 9. Nc3 {We attack that knight one more time.} Ncb4 (9... Nxd4 {
This maybe is an objectively good move, because trying to hold on to the piece
puts Black in a very dangerous situation, but this clearly isn't critical.} 10.
Bxd5+ Kd6 11. Qd3 {Now the material is even, but Black's king is simply
terrible on d6. Following with Be3, Bb3/e4, Ne4, 0-0-0, and so on, we will win
rather easily.}) 10. O-O {Now we just finish the development. The plan is to
keep developing and opening the position, while the instant threat is a2-a3,
forcing the Black knight away and winning the d5-knight. Now we just finish
the development. Now the plan is to keep developing and opening the position,
while the instant threat is a2-a3, forcing the Black knight away and winning
the d5-knight.} c6 11. a3 {We force the knight away. Now, two options are
possible - either retreating back to a6, or courageously taking the c2-pawn.}
Nxc2 (11... Na6 {This is possible, but not too attractive, as Black is under
strong attack and he's not even grabbing more material. It's possible, but not
too attractive, as Black is under a very strong attack and he's not even
grabbing more material.} 12. Re1 {Now Rxe5 is a huge threat, which forces
Black to react.} Bf6 13. dxe5 {Taking isn't possible because of Bf4, so Black
needs to retreat.} Be7 (13... Bxe5 14. Bf4 {Black is pinned all over the place!
}) 14. Qg4+ Kf7 15. e6+ {Attacking again!} Kf8 16. Bxd5 cxd5 17. Qf3+ {We've
gotten rid of the defender of the e7-square (the d5-knight) and now threaten
checkmate on f7, which forces Black to defend and wins the Black queen.} Bf6
18. e7+ {The hunt on the Black king resulted in the decisive material gains,
now it's time for him to resign.}) 12. dxe5 {White couldn't care less about
the a1-rook as his goal is to open up the position and to win that d5-knight,
which would make us a huge step closer towards the main idea - mating the
Black king!} Nxa1 13. Rd1 Nc2 14. Nxd5 {Now the Black king is getting
slaughtered instantly, for example} cxd5 15. Bxd5+ Kxe5 16. Qf4# {Mate! This
is quite deserved when your king keeps walking around in the middle of the
board for many moves!}) (6... exd4 {This has been played in most games that
reached this position, but after} 7. O-O {White is significantly ahead in
development and Black is just lost.} Be7 {Black mostly tried to defend in this
way, which loses instantly.} (7... Be6 {Another defensive attempt, which is
also clearly insufficient.} 8. Re1 {The rook joins the attack, creating
threats like Nxe6 or even Nxf7.} Qd7 9. Nxf7 {A very beautiful tactical shot.
Now the point is that the queen cannot take because of Bxd5, while after} Kxf7
10. Qf3+ Kg8 11. Rxe6 {White wins his piece back with a completely winning
position, as} Qxe6 12. Bxd5 {wins the Black queen.}) 8. Nxf7 {Simple and
strong.} Kxf7 9. Qh5+ {We are forking the king and the d5-knight, gaining our
sacrificed piece back. Importantly, 10...Ke6 does not allow Black to hold on
to his extra piece as Re1+ finishes the hunt on the Black monarch instantly.}
g6 10. Bxd5+ {Of course, we aren't trading queens as the heat of the attack
keeps increasing.} Ke8 11. Qf3 {Now the deadly check on f7 is threatened,
forcing Black to react.} Rf8 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxc6+ Bd7 14. Qd5 {At the end
of the variation, we have cashed out by converting our initiative into a
