1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 {Finally we
get to discuss the mainline of Two Knights with 4.Ng5, where Black sacrifices
a pawn, hoping to get significant compensation as we are spending a few moves
to grab it.} 7. dxc6 bxc6 (7... Nxc6 {Of course, taking with the knight wasn't
the plan - now Black is just a pawn down as he didn't manage to achieve his
goal of forcing our bishop back while also winning a tempo.} 8. Bxc6+ {This is
the cleanest move, I think, as it totally suppresses Black's counterplay
related to the potential knight jumps.} bxc6 9. d3 {White will play Nf3, h2-h3,
Nc3 (or, possibly, Nbd2 if the Black bishop is on g4 in order not to
experience that unpleasant pin), we are just a pawn up. I'll just give one
sample line.} Bg4 10. Nf3 Bd6 11. h3 Bh5 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. O-O {We have almost
finished our development, now it's time to follow with Qe2, Ne4, Bd2-c3 or Bg5
with a healthy extra pawn.}) 8. Bd3 {This slightly ugly-looking move is my
recommendation in this position. But, it's not a fruit of my imagination - in
fact, this idea has been already enjoying a great reputation for years, and
while it's not the most popular move in the entire pool of games, it is
definitely the move top-players choose most frequently whenever they reach
this position. What is the point? Why does the bishop go to this weird square,
obstructing the d2-pawn and thus all the queenside pieces, instead of the more
natural square on e2? The reason lies in the position of our g5-knight. Black
can choose to kick it around and in many lines, we want to retreat to e4, so
we need our bishop to be protecting that square. Now, the main move and the
best move by Black, which has been given in their 1.e4 e5! repertoires by such
great analysts as Jan Gustafsson and Nikolaos Ntrilis, is 8...Nd5. That's the
move I've played with Black on many occasions, too, and I definitely think
that's his best choice. But, there are several other continuations available,
such as 8...h6, 8...Ng4 (Bologan's choice in his book) and 8...Bc5. Black has
other moves as well - 8...Be7, 8...Bg4, etc, but they clearly are inferior to
those three. Actually, I am able to assume that Black might be able to
equalize with perfect play in some of the lines given in this chapter, but I
definitely think it'll be way more difficult than after 8...Nd5.} Ng4 {
Bologan's suggestion and something that Grischuk played recently vs Vitiugov 
(July 2019, Grand Prix). Black immediately attacks our g5-knight. In this
chapter, this is definitely the best move available to Black.} (8... Bc5 {
This is also a relatively popular move and a rather logical one as Black is
getting ready to castle while also deploying his bishop to an active position.
Here, we also get a serious advantage, this time by relatively simple means.}
9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 {Having castled, we are now looking to either finish the
development with d3 or trade a pair of knights with Ne4.} h6 11. Nge4 Nxe4 12.
Bxe4 {About 15 games reached the position after 11...Nxe4, but most players
chose to take with the knight which is natural as it also attacks the Black
bishop - only 2 took with the bishop. Oftentimes, we tend to try remembering
forcing variations or just simply copy engine's moves. But, in my opinion,
it's is instrumental to look at this position conceptually. Conceptually,
Black's main advantage is the extra space on the kingside reached after the
subsequent ...f7-f5 and hopes to get a bunch of activity on that part of the
board. So, to my mind, it makes perfect sense to take with the bishop as we
are able to retreat with it to f3, thus keeping it on the kingside and
protecting our king! At the same time, the bishop recapture is a lot more
natural as it prepares d2-d3, which develops the queenside.} f5 13. Bf3 {
Now the goal is to simply play d2-d3. Later, we might want to challenge that
c5-bishop with Be3 or Na4. It is also important to mention that in many
situations, we might want to follow with d2-d3, Na4, and b2-b3!, intending to
develop the bishop to the long diagonal in order to target the e5-pawn and the
diagonal, overall. Also, please keep in mind the idea of g2-g3!, which is
often useful as it prevents all the kinds of possible problems related to ...
e5-e4 or anything else that could possibly hurt our f3-bishop. White is just a
healthy pawn up, we are on our way to the full point!}) (8... h6 {The second
most popular move which is rather popular at a club/ tournament level, yet it
is also being occasionally used by the likes of Caruana, Bacrot, Sokolov, and
many other notable GMs. So, we clearly need to check it seriously.} 9. Ne4 Nd5
{This is the idea behind Black's last move - he is preparing to play ...Nf4.
The whole point is that had he started with 8...Nd5, which is the main move
that we are about to discuss in the following chapters, White would be able to
retreat to f3 with his knight, while after 8...h6 9.Nf3?? e4! White would just
lose a piece.} (9... Nxe4 {does not make any sense as after} 10. Bxe4 {White
is just a pawn up. Of course, the game is still going on, but soon White will
stabilize the situation and convert his extra pawn. A natural sample line
could go:} Bc5 11. O-O O-O 12. d3 f5 13. Bf3 {We will continue with Nc3, Bd2,
or Be3, etc. One very important maneuver that can often serve you well in
these positions is g2-g3! followed by Bg2 in order to insure yourself against
all the possible ideas related to ...e5-e4. White is just a pawn up, there's
nothing Black can show in return for that missing pawn.}) 10. O-O {Now, we
need to discuss two moves - the main 10...Be7 and the sidelines 10...Nf4. It's
also important that we want to castle as quickly as possible; Levon Aronian
chose 10.Nbc3 against Caruana, which was fine, but less precise as after ...
Nf4! the g2-pawn was hanging.} Be7 {At this point, we need to make one very
important move. Black might want to push ...f7-f5 at some point sooner or
later in order to grab space in the center/on the kingside. So, we stop that
idea.} (10... g6 {This was played by Sokolov and Khismatullin in order to
develop the bishop to g7, but White has a very nice counter to it.} 11. Re1 {
We are developing the rook, intending to put pressure on the e5-pawn, while
also preparing to hide the bishop on f1.} f5 {Here White needs to improve on
the game Scherbakov-Khistmatullin which saw 12.Ng3.} 12. Nec3 {This move might
seem slightly ugly and unnatural as now the b1-knight clearly cannot get out,
but the point is that on g3 the knight would have been extremely restrained,
while now, even though it looks like our position isn't too harmonious at the
moment, we are able to go Bf1, d2-d3, and either Nb1-d2, or trade/move the
c3-knight and develop the other one on c3. For example, after} Bg7 13. Bf1 O-O
14. d3 Be6 15. Na4 {The knight started getting re-routed, it's coming to c5,
while the other one can now go to c3.} Nb7 16. c4 {White started active play
on the queenside while also kicking the Black pieces away from the center. The
fact that we're weakening the d3-pawn doesn't matter all that much.} Nb6 17.
Nbc3 Qc7 18. Qc2 Nd7 19. b4 {White was already much better, but eventually
Black managed to draw this correspondence game. Of course, it's not easy to
beat an engine, or even an engine and a human together, but here Black has
nothing to show for the missing pawn, I believe. 1/2 (43) Wilhelmi,D (2473) -
Telepnev,I (2494) ICCF email 2013}) (10... Nf4 {This move intends to double
our pawns after ...Nxd3, but unlike in the mainline, we don't have to and
won't allow for that.} 11. Be2 Be7 12. d3 {We are just developing, preparing
to get our queenside pieces out. At the same time, we might want to take on f4
in order to simplify the situation a bit. Remember, we are a pawn up in all
these lines, which means trades benefit us greatly unless we are trading
desperately while worsening our position. Any equal trade is good.} O-O 13.
Bxf4 exf4 14. Nbd2 {This is the right spot for the knight as it's coming to b3
in order to control the c5-square, block the b-file from all the attempts to
get counterplay related to ...Rb8 and prepare the trade of the a5-knight!
White is just a pawn up, really, I fail to see compensation.}) 11. Ng3 O-O {
Now Black is again ready to push ...f7-f5.} 12. Bf5 {Another key move - we
want to trade the bishops. Not only are we a pawn up, but also Black has
somewhat more space in such positions, so trading is twice as beneficial for
us. At this point, I think all the moves but one allow for the trade and
aren't interesting at all - we simply trade the bishops, play d2-d3, Nc3 or
Nd2, develop the queenside pieces (remember about the idea Nb1-d2-b3!) and
convert our extra pawn.} Ba6 {I can't say this is the best move objectively,
as maybe Black should already accept the fact he's a pawn down and his
position is bad. But, this is definitely the most principled continuation, as
Black avoids the undesirable trade and tries to create some threats. It also
led Black to success in a high-profile game between the late Igor Kurnosov -
what an insanely gifted player he was! - and Ernesto Inarkiev.} 13. d3 c5 {
At this point, White reacted quite well, but it would have been even better to
simply offer the knight trade. 0-1 (57) Kurnosov,I (2657) - Inarkiev,E (2680)
Khanty-Mansiysk 2013} 14. Nc3 {Black's problem is that he cannot really turn
down this offer, as} Nf6 {runs into} 15. Nce4 {White is being quite persistent.
We trade those guys and can either play for simplifications or go for the
kingside attack with such ideas as Qg4/h5, possibly intending some sacrifices
like Bxh6. The engine already claims White is just winning, I'd give the
slightly more modest evaluation as the position is still complicated, but it's
definitely a hugely favorable situation for us!}) 9. Ne4 f5 {That's the idea
behind Black's last move - he is just attacking our knight, hoping it would
retreat, which would enable him to get some very strong initiative with ...
e5-e4!} 10. Be2 (10. Ng3 {This is just terrible for White, as after} Bc5 11.
O-O Qh4 {Black is winning material by force - that's something you clearly
shouldn't do! Yet, I wanted to give this line to raise awareness among those
of you who are used to retreating whenever your pieces are attacked!}) 10... h5
(10... Nh6 {Of course, this wasn't Black's idea (or should not have been).} 11.
Ng3 {Now we can definitely afford to retreat, as now ...e5-e4 doesn't come
with a tempo and because Black no longer is able to generate threats on the
kingside.} Nf7 {This variation was twice essayed by the Russian GM Ponkratov,
who is known for playing very ambitious and fighting, yet often unsound chess.
The best way of proving the unsoundness of Black's setup is} 12. d4 {We offer
a pawn sacrifice in order to destroy the Black structure and to develop much
faster.} exd4 (12... Qxd4 {This leads to very similar consequences as the pawn
capture, leaving Black in a very unpleasant endgame. We've successfully
suppressed all of his counterplay!} 13. Qxd4 exd4 14. O-O Be7 15. Re1 O-O 16.
Bd3 {This endgame isn't just bad - it's simply lost. Please note that the
f5-pawn is currently hanging, Black is immediately losing material. Besides
that, we enjoy fantastic outposts on d3 and c4; the black knight on a5 doesn't
even fully count as a piece.}) 13. O-O Be7 14. c3 dxc3 15. Nxc3 O-O {Black
should trade queens and transpose to a terrible ending where all of his pawns
are weak/overextended and where the knight on a5 is misplaced, as otherwise,
White would choose to play with queens, which would lead to the even more
unpleasant consequences.} 16. Qc2 {We plan on continuing Bf4, Rad1, Rfe1, etc,
with the decisive initiative as Black's position has been terribly weakened by
moves like ...f7-f5 and because his pieces are extremely misplaced as well.})
11. h3 {Black is forced into a tunnel variation now.} fxe4 12. hxg4 Bc5 {
The right move, putting more pressure on f2, and the only move that has ever
been played. Now, the game is developing in a very forcing manner, but White
has two promising continuations.} 13. b4 {This is one of them and the one I am
recommending, as it's the cleanest solution, in my opinion. What's the point
behind this pawn sacrifice?} (13. Nc3 {That's another move which I would
suggest you check out yourself. The positions after} Qd4 14. O-O {are rather
crazy. Now Black typically castles, but Grischuk also introduced a weird
novelty 14...Rf8N last year, which is also something to look at. One line here,
which you would need to investigate if you want to play this way, is} O-O 15.
Qe1 hxg4 16. d3 exd3 17. Bxd3 Rxf2 18. Qxf2 Qxf2+ 19. Rxf2 g3 20. Ne4 gxf2+ 21.
Kf1 {Here Black typically plays 21...Bb6. I'll not give this move in the text
so that the line ends with our move. Jan calls this position 'just equal',
which is most likely correct evaluation-wise, but I won't call this position
dead-equal or stop analyzing here as it's a rather unbalanced situation with
plenty of interesting ideas for both sides. Definitely something fun to look
at! Another weird thing is that Bologan, who is recommending only 8...Ng4 is
claiming that 'Black is somewhat worse but should hold a draw'. This is
definitely good news for us as well, as it means a strong 2650+ GM doesn't see
a clear way to equalize after 3...Nf6 4.Ng5!}) 13... O-O (13... Bxb4 14. Nc3 {
The idea was to deflect the Black bishop away from the g1-a7 diagonal and now
he is unable to create threats over there with moves like ...Qd4. Next, White
either picks the e4-pawn or the h5-pawn with a nearly winning position. For
example, after} Qd4 15. gxh5 O-O {Black attacks the f2-pawn.} 16. O-O Bc5 17.
Qe1 {You might get an impression as if the situation was still unclear, but
White is massively better as he is a pawn up and Black's structure is terrible,
while his activity will be easily extinguished either with:  1.Rb1 in order to
unpin the rook; Nd1-e3!, blocking the g1-a7 diagonal and stopping all the
ideas over it for good; or  2.d2-d3!, intending to play Be3!}) 14. bxc5 Qd4 {
Is a transposition to 13...Qd4.} 15. O-O Qxa1 16. Nc3 {The queen on a1 is now
paralyzed, it has no moves.} e3 {Jan says that's the move that made him
interested in the whole thing with 8...Ng4.} 17. gxh5 exf2+ 18. Rxf2 Rxf2 19.
Kxf2 Be6 {At this point, Jan analyzes moves 20.Bf3, as was played between
Stellwagen and L'Ami (2 games in the database) and 20.Ba3 (420 games,
including the correspondence ones, of course), saying the latter should be a
draw. I also think it should be a draw if Black knows everything perfectly,
but White is still pressing in the arising position.} 20. Ba3 Qxd1 21. Bxd1
Rf8+ 22. Ke1 {For some reason, Jan analyzes only 22.Kg3, which I believe is
weaker. But, it's understandable he doesn't want to go into some tremendous
amount of detail as his main recommendation is 8...Nd5, while this line is
just something he mentions for fun. Something I don't understand, though, is
why Bologan analyzes only 22.Kg3, as it's his main (and only!) recommendation
versus 8.Bd3!, he should have investigated the position more deeply! What can
we say about this endgame? White has two pawns for the exchange and a bishop
pair as well. Black's pawn structure is rather damaged and ruined - all of his
pawns are weak! His knight on a5 is also out of business. In a similar
position (not this one) Jan suggests the plan of Na5-b7-d8-f7, which makes
perfect sense. Yet, this definitely isn't fast enough and White should be able
to obtain a clear advantage.} Nb7 23. d3 Nd8 24. Bc1 {Now it's a good time to
activate the bishop as it wasn't doing anything on a3.} Nf7 25. Bf3 {Now the
c6-pawn is a problem. We are already very deep in the line, so I won't analyze
several continuations available to Black, let me just give you a few more
moves.} Nh6 {Black is improving his knight's position.} 26. Bxc6 Rc8 27. Be4
Rxc5 28. Kd2 {White is clearly pressing in this endgame. His ideas include
a2-a4, Ba3, Nd5, possibly Bb2 if the rook leaves the 5th rank, as then the
e5-pawn might suffer. It's very important that the Black rook cannot find a
good use for itself as there aren't many open files, and the existing open
files don't offer any good entrance squares/targets for that rook.} *

