1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 {Finally, we reach the very main position of the whole 4.Ng5 complex,
which arises after this precise reply 8...Nd5! I would like to warn you in
advance that most of the arising positions are extremely messy and complicated
and involve a great deal of risk for both players - but as known, the higher
the risk, the higher the potential reward. And we are going to be very
well-prepared for taking that risk! Black is immediately attacking the
g5-knight while also bringing his knight to the lovely central square - soon
he will try to play ...Nf4. In my opinion, White has three very promising
ideas here. One is to go 9.h4 - a move that Ntirlis in his excellent book
calls critical. I also think it is very interesting, but it leads to some
absolutely insane complications. Another ambitious line is 9.Nf3 Bd6 10.0-0,
which is the very main continuation. It is definitely the richest line in this
position, which leads to some very interesting battles, where Black is
typically a pawn down, but White gets that cramped pawn structure and Black
enjoys serious compensation. As I mention in several places, one thing I
particularly enjoy about Chessable is the diversity of the students of the
courses. I know IMs and GMs have been studying my courses diligently; so have
amateurs and people who only play online. Of course, if you are a less
experienced player, my recommendation (just one line) is going to be more than
enough. If you are a more experienced player, though, you might be curious to
look around and to see what other ideas are available. Since I have no clue
who you, dear reader, are, and what your ambitions are, I thought I'd mention
those two options - either to enable you to save the time on the search, so
that you can start to investigate additional critical options on your own, or
so that you just enjoy hearing a bit more information about this variation and
the history of its development. Finally, I have decided to stick to the third
option, which is an extremely fresh idea, used by Van Foreest in this year's
Tata Steel against no less than Mr.Carlsen. This variation, although it leads
to equality - just as all others, ultimately! - was good enough to set the
World Champion on the verge of a loss. Hopefully, the preparation of the
players you'll be facing won't be much better than the one of the World
Champion! Now, let me mention a few theoretical sources for Black that we are
dealing with here.  1 Jan Gustafsson's Lifetime Repertoires 1. e4 e5! on
Chessable; I have managed to find a new idea that he hasn't covered in his
course. I do think his recommendation is the most forcing and critical test of
my suggestion for White, but we will be able to pose problems - and yeah, fair
enough, if Black is playing perfectly, it is going to be a draw.  2 Ntirlis's
'Playing 1. e4 e5' book, published by Quality Chess; Here's what happened:
Ntirlis did some high-quality extensive analysis of all the mainlines, but my
move appeared in the tournament play only very recently and is very rare, so
it's not discussed in his book at all! To be fair, he is discussing one line
that we can get via our move order as well, but it got some very superficial
coverage and the most critical idea for White wasn't mentioned. Good news for
us, as he's an excellent analyst and many people follow what he recommends in
his book, they won't be prepared to meet this repertoire!  3 Andrey Terekhov's
excellent course on two knights here on Chessable; Before I proceed to discuss
what's going on with that repertoire, I'd like to say a few words about its
author. I've known Andrey since 2013, when, interestingly enough, I - an
unrated player back then! - faced him in an OTB tournament in Kiev, as we were
both living in Ukraine back then. I've had an excellent tournament and got my
first FIDE rating of 2050 or so, but he beat me in a rather one-sided way,
showing I had a lot to learn. The reason why I am discussing him is that I
found him a very interesting person and a model presentation for the non-chess
world, what a chess player should look like. Having become an FM, he has
managed to pursue a highly successful career at Microsoft while also being an
all-round intelligent person with various interests as well as a rather
talented author. So, for me to see that he had published a Chessable course
wasn't just something interesting chess-wise, as I knew immediately the
quality of the content would be impeccable, but also, I just felt good about
hearing his name again and checking out his recent writing. Now that you might
be a little bored with my background and all these stories, let's return to
the chess part. Having said many good words about Andrey Terekhov, I now feel
obliged to challenge his theoretical conclusions in order not to sound biased!
Andrey mentions Gustafsson's suggestion in his course while also giving one of
his own - 10.Nc3 0-0 11.Be2 f5. This is also a rather good move and we will
deal with it in this chapter, too.} 9. Nf3 Bd6 (9... Nf4 {Before we dive in
the complications after the main move 9...Bd6, let's first look at this
sideline. Now it's very important to be careful, as 10.0-0 Bd6 transposes to
the mainline 9...Bd6 10.0-0, while we prefer the move order 10.Nc3!} 10. Bf1 {
In my opinion, this is clearly the best move which comes close to refuting the
somewhat sloppy 9...Nf4. Now Black doesn't get to take on d3 and we are about
to play either d2-d3 with the idea of Bxf4, or even d2-d4!, opening up the
center, as the e5-pawn is the only defender of that unstable knight.} Bd6 (
10... e4 {The idea to immediately attack White might sound tempting, and some
players found it such - for instance, a high-profile game Socko-Bartel, where
both opponents were around 2600, saw this move.} 11. d3 {Unfortunately, now
things quickly get terrible for Black.} exf3 (11... Nxg2+ 12. Bxg2 exf3 13.
Qxf3 {Again, this is just a free pawn. The bishop is very well-placed on g2 as
it will cover our king very conveniently in the event if we decide to castle
short. A few natural moves would be} Be7 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Bf4 {At this point,
White can choose to castle either way, he is nearly winning in both cases. If
he chooses to castle long, a very strong idea would be to go Bh3! to trade the
light-squared bishops and take advantage of the semi-open g-file to generate
an attack against the Black king. This is the most ambitious, and perhaps the
best approach. But, short castling is also very good objectively and it is
definitely a saner and a safer choice.}) 12. Bxf4 Qf6 {Bartel tried this nifty
trick, attacking both the bishop and the b2-pawn.} 13. Qxf3 Qxb2 {At this
point, White is doing great, but he needs to find a very important idea.} 14.
Qe2+ {Qe4 or Qe3 would have done the same job.} Be6 15. Qe5 {This was it -
White protects the a1-rook in this unusual way.} Bb4+ 16. Kd1 {Even though we
lost the castling rights, the Black queen is now trapped and has to trade ours,
which steers the game in a safe one-pawn-up endgame for White.} Qxe5 17. Bxe5
O-O 18. Be2 {We are about to play Bf3, improving our bishop. White's a healthy
pawn up and this is nearly winning for us, but I thought some ideas would
still be helpful. We can either play Nd2-b3 in order to trade that a5-knight,
or Bc3!? in order to force the trade of the Black bishop. As usual while a
pawn up, the more trades, the better for us.}) 11. d4 {The obvious threat is
dxe5 where White will not only attack the d6-bishop, but the f4-knight, too.}
exd4 (11... e4 {Black stops the idea of dxe5 while also attacking our knight.}
12. Ne5 {Now the f4-knight is hanging again.} Ne6 13. Nc3 {While this just
seems to be an innocent developing move, which attacks the e4-pawn, we also
have an idea of Nxc6! followed by d4-d5, forking both Black knights and
gaining the sacrificed piece back while also reaching the favorable
simplifications. As usual in those bad sidelines, White is already nearly
winning.}) 12. Qxd4 {Now the f4-knight is forced out.} Ne6 13. Qd1 O-O 14. Bd3
{This is just a free extra pawn, we will just castle and possibly play h2-h3
to stop any Bg4-related plans. Then follows Nc3, Be3, etc, where we just start
trading to approach the winning endgame thanks to our extra pawn.}) 10. Nc3 {
As I said in the introduction, this is a very rare move. At the moment of
writing, the main 10.0-0 was seen for more than 500 times, while this move was
chosen in 25 games only. But, it was played in such a high-level game as Van
Foreest-Carlsen, so its popularity will definitely increase a lot! What is the
difference, why do we start with 10.Nc3 as opposed to castling and playing Nc3
later? I would quote Andrey Terekhov's words from his course on Two Knights:
'The main idea behind this move is to take control of e4 square, and thus
prepare Be2, followed by d3. This might look slow but it is surprisingly
potent setup.' I find this explanation rather precise and concise - indeed,
Be2! is now our positional threat, sort of. Now, Black has three main moves
that we need to discuss - the main 10...0-0 which was seen in 15 games and is
suggested by Terekhov, the second most popular 10...Nf4 and Gustafsson's
novelty 10...f5!, which is the most precise way for Black to handle the
position, I think.} f5 {As usual, Jan Gustafsson lives up to his reputation of
a great analyst and suggests a very powerful novelty in his course - that was
the toughest nut for me to crack. Just as after 10...0-0 - Terekhov's
suggestion - I would be giving two alternatives here, which should suit both
those of you who are looking for some absolutely insane wild game as well as
those looking to check how well-prepared the opponents are and just let them
get half a point if they did their homework well. While objectively it's not
possible to prove White's advantage after this move, I am very satisfied with
our prospects practically as we are choosing between a forced draw and a
highly interesting complicated position which wasn't discussed in Jan's course,
which means even students of that course won't be expecting it at all. The
idea of Black's last move is very clear - he wants to push ...e5-e4. That's
the price of having a bishop on d3, as with the bishop elsewhere, the simple
d2-d3 would have stopped that plan for good.} (10... Nf4 {This is a very
interesting move, in fact! Jan and Andrey aren't even mentioning it, as 11.0-0
is very likely to transpose to the mainline. To the best of my understanding,
the reason why they are ignoring it is because after 10.0-0 they prefer 10...
0-0 instead of 10...Nf4, as that 10...Nf4 isn't considered most precise for
Black. It indeed is the most popular move according to the database, but it's
not what the top players have been doing as of late. But, many players are
unaware that 10.0-0 0-0! is currently the trend, so they are likely to make
this move - we need to be ready.} 11. O-O {The whole point of this move order
- this position also often arises via 10.0-0 Nf4 11.Nc3! - is that White used
to automatically insert the move Re1 in, but it would often prove useless as
that e5-pawn wasn't hanging, as a matter of fact! Now, our positional threat
is to go Be2 in order to stop the opponent from spoiling our structure. So,
Black needs to take.} (11. Bf1 {This is the 'lazy' solution you might want to
prefer in order to wait theoretical work after 11.0-0! The point is to protect
the g2-pawn and to kick that knight away with g2-g3!, followed by Be2 or even
Bg2, d2-d3 and normal development.} e4 {This is the only problem with that 11.
Bf1 move. Now we reach a rather interesting position, which is objectively
balanced.} (11... O-O {Now White's idea gets illustrated at its best.} 12. g3
Nd5 13. d3 Re8 14. Be2 {White manages to stabilize the situation in the center
and is about to castle. The only way for Black to stop this is} Nxc3 15. bxc3
Bh3 {but this runs into the following rather forcing idea.} 16. Ng5 Bg2 {
Other moves don't make sense as White gets to castle and improve his knight at
the same time - it's going to e4.} 17. Rg1 {The Black bishop doesn't have much
of a choice.} Bd5 18. c4 {The point of this weird maneuvre with Ng5 and Rg1
was that the bishop is now trapped!} h6 {The only continuation, as going ...
Be6 and just letting White trade is lame.} 19. cxd5 {White's king is now
totally safe as it will just walk to g2 via f1. We have the bishop pair and a
clearly better position. You might also want to go Rb1 and make use of the
open b-file!}) 12. Nd4 {Now, the threat is to go g2-g3 and kick the knight out,
which would be followed by Bg2 (!) and 0-0, where Black's pawn on e4 would be
weak and he wouldn't have any compensation for the already missing pawn.} (12.
Nxe4 {Don't you dare to take that pawn!} Qe7 13. d3 f5 {White is losing his
pinned knight.}) 12... Qe7 {The key move which creates a threat of ...Nd3+!}
13. Nde2 {White needs to try and trade that f4-knight.} Bg4 {This definitely
looks somewhat ugly for us as all of our pieces are pinned all over the place.}
14. h3 {The key maneuvre that lets us untangle.} Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nxf4 Bxf4
17. Bg2 O-O 18. Qe2 {White is about to castle, or he can follow up with d2-d3
or even b2-b3 and Bb2. This is a very interesting and complicated position,
where Black definitely has compensation, so the situation is rather balanced.
If you want to avoid much theory after 11.0-0, by all means go here, as it's
also quite debatable that your opponents will find this excellent idea of ...
e5-e4! followed by ...Qe7! But, I would objectively suggest that you study 11.
0-0! as that is a much better move from the objective standpoint.}) 11... Nxd3
12. cxd3 O-O {At this point, we have two interesting possibilities.} 13. b3 {
Aronian's move. The goal is to meet ... c6-c5, which is Black's typical idea
as he wants to grab space and improve his knight's position with ...Na5-c6,
with Ba3, putting pressure on the c5-pawn right away. Now, a few continuations
are possible here.} Re8 {This is Black's best bet, as he makes a useful move
and protects the e5-pawn extensively in advance while also not allowing for
Ba3.} (13... c5 {Ding made this move and got a rather bad position, which was
the reason why all this talk appeared that the line 10...Nf4 was rather not
too fun for Black.} 14. Ba3 {White often places the bishop on this position in
order to target the c5-pawn. But the fresh news about this game specifically
was the fact that he managed to attain all that without committing to a
useless move Re1.} Nc6 15. Ne4 Nb4 16. Bxb4 cxb4 {Now that the knight is
traded, many opportunities for dynamic counterplay also disappear from Black's
agenda.} 17. Re1 Bb8 18. Ng3 {18.Nc5! was even better, but this also works.}
Qxd3 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Rxe5 Be6 21. Re3 Qd4 22. Ne2 Qd6 23. d4 {White managed
to stabilize the position and keep the extra pawn. While Black did manage to
save his half a point, this has nothing to do with the opening - White's
opening was clearly a large success as he just got a healthy extra pawn
without allowing much of a counterplay. 1/2 (43) Aronian,L (2765) - Ding,L 
(2805) Saint Louis 2019}) 14. Re1 f6 {14...c5 was typically played, but this
looks very similar to the line discussed after 13...c5. This precise move,
instead, improves Black's position as it solidifies the e5-pawn while also
asking, if we got anything useful moves ourselves, as Ba3 stll isn't possible.}
15. h3 {A cool idea shown in one correspondence game. Just as Black, we are
playing this waiting game, preventing ...Bg4. Now, Black has a few options,
but our idea is to prepare d3-d4!} Be7 {A very precise move which attacks the
d3-pawn while also keeping the e-file open.} (15... Bf8 {Just to show you what
happens in the event of some random move, I'll give you this line.} 16. d4 exd4
17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Nxd4 {White got rid of his doubled pawn. Of course, he had
also opened the position up quite a bit, but it's debatable whether Black has
full compensation.} c5 19. Nf3 Bb7 20. Ba3 Nc6 21. Na4 {This is rather typical
- the c5-pawn is under a lot of pressure, while after} Nb4 22. Bxb4 cxb4 23.
Nb2 {White is about to re-route the knight to c4 and try to slowly but surely
convert his extra pawn. Of course, Black's bishops are rather strong, but
there's nothing to attack, so his compensation is only partial - and it's the
'stop the opponent from winning' kind of compensation, not the 'fun' one.}) 16.
d4 {White sacrifices a pawn in order to close the position down and create
some pawn weaknesses in Black's camp.} exd4 17. Na4 Ba6 18. d3 {I am quoting
the correspondence game, so there's no wonder both players' moves were close
to perfection. As a result, we obtain the position where Black enjoys the
bishop pair, but now the position got closed down and we have the semi-open
c-file, a target on it and a lovely outpost on c5 for our knight. The computer
shows 0.00 or a tiny edge for White. While I cannot argue with the evaluation,
I still like White practically as it is a lot easier for him to play: Black
has weaknesses on the c-file while we don't have any. This is the best
position that Black can get in this 10...Nf4 line, in my opinion. 1/2 (29)
Szczepanski,Z (2455) - Galliano,G (2419) ICCF email 2018}) (10... O-O {Andrey
recommends this natural move, and that's exactly what Magnus did versus Van
Foreest.} 11. Be2 {As stated earlier, White's idea behind Nc3 was to take the
e4-square under control and prepare this move. Now, we just want to play d2-d3
and control the e4-square even more.} f5 {In his course, Andrey is suggesting
this typical move which grabs a lot of space.} (11... Nf4 {Magnus played this,
but the course of the game clearly proved him wrong.} 12. O-O Bg4 (12... c5 {
This was seen in another top-level game Shankland-L'Ami. The
usually-well-prepared Erwin got a rather bad version of a typical position.}
13. d3 {The problem is that we are ready to play Bxf4 and kill all the
counterplay!} Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 Bb7 15. Ne4 {Not only do we obstruct the long
h1-a8 diagonal, but we also start attacking the c5-pawn.} Nc6 16. Be3 f5 17.
Nxc5 {White just won another pawn and went on to convert his extra material
into a full point. This was unexpectedly easy! : 1-0 (40) Shankland,S (2652) -
L'Ami,E (2613) Wijk aan Zee 2015}) 13. d3 {White wants to take Bxf4, thus
putting to an end all of Black's hopes for counterplay.} Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 f5 15.
h3 Bh5 {In fact, this position was reached in two games. Besides Carlsen's one,
it was seen in another battle of two 2500-rated players. Black's position
looks okay, but it's not... after Van Foreest's excellent decision.} 16. g4 {
White resolves that pin in a slightly unexpected fashion! The point is that we
also gain control over the e4-square.} fxg4 17. Ng5 {Now, hxg4 is coming. But,
at the same time, White is in no rush to take as that pawn is pinned.} Qd7 18.
Nce4 {Black still cannot do anything as his pawn is pinned and the h5-bishop
is unprotected.} Be7 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Qxg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 {After the slightly
complicated heated battle that we just saw, White obtained a healthy extra
pawn and a nearly winning position. Unfortunately - at least from our
perspective as we fancy this line with White - he didn't manage to develop his
success and convert the advantage, as the World Champion showed some extremely
tenacious defense as well as a bit of luck and the game was eventually drawn.
Yet, this is something we call a huge opening success, as White just kept his
healthy extra pawn! 1/2 (45) Van Foreest,J (2644) - Carlsen, M (2872) Wijk aan
Zee 2020}) 12. d3 {We just keep developing.} Nxc3 13. bxc3 Qc7 {Here Andrey
Terekhov cuts his analysis short, suggesting Black has typical compensation
and the standard plan of ...e5-e4, ...c6-c5, ...Bb7 and ...Rae8, mobilizing
all his forces. He also correctly points out White needs to be careful as
castling might run into ...e5-e4 when the h2-pawn would hang. I do agree with
all of these words and plans, but I think we need to extend the analysis, as
White is still a pawn up and while Black does have compensation, it's not
'breaking through the roof'. In my opinion, compensation in this position is a
rather defensive one, as Black has more space and it's not easy to convert
this extra pawn. But, it's not a situation we need to shy away from, as we can
keep improving our position step by step!} 14. g3 {We improve our control over
the h2-b8 diagonal, setting up an obstacle in front of Black's Q+B battery.} (
14. O-O {While it does run into ...e5-e4, this is still an interesting move.
