doesn't necessarily give Black a very easy life.} e4 15. dxe4 fxe4 16. Ng5 {
The e4-pawn is also hanging.} Bf5 17. Bg4 {Now we want to trade the bishops
and win that pawn.} Bxh2+ 18. Kh1 Be5 19. Bxf5 Rxf5 20. Qg4 Raf8 21. Nxe4 {
I definitely think Black has full compensation here, but White is a pawn up,
anyway, and it's an interesting position to play out.}) 14... c5 {Black might
also start with ...Bb7, but he'd need this move anyway in order to grab more
space and get a better control over the d4-square, in order to open up the
long diagonal for his b7-bishop and to be able to return the a5-knight back to
normal life via c6.} 15. O-O Bb7 16. Rb1 {Here's an open file, so we grab it.
Now, we might consider ideas with d3-d4, but our main goal is to play Nd2 or
Ng5 followed by Bf3, trading that mighty bishop, simplifying the game, and
thus coming one (huge!) step closer to the endgame where we will be a healthy
pawn up.} Rae8 {Here, I would like us to look at two plans.} 17. Nd2 {I like
this solid plan best. Now, if Black waits, Bf3! will trade the bishops and
make his compensation for the missing pawn very questionable.} (17. d4 {
It is interesting to see what happens if we attempt to break through in the
center right away.} e4 {Black by all means should be trying to keep this
strong pawn.} (17... exd4 {Of course, it's great for White to eliminate the
strong e5-pawn.} 18. cxd4 cxd4 19. Bb5 {Instead of taking the pawn, which is
also fine, we worsen the position of the Black rook.} Rd8 20. Bg5 {Another
nice move, suggested by the engine - White wants to play the position with the
material equality and initiative. We develop a piece and simplify the
