Bb5 {This pin is extremely helpful, as it forces Black to make some clumsy
move.} Bb7 {This is what Jan is recommending. While it might seem less natural
than 13...Bd7 to some, as it doesn't unpin the knight, this move makes sense
as it immediately places the bishop on the long diagonal. Here, we reach a
very important crossroads. 14.c4! is the objectively more challenging move
which creates a huge mess where both sides are risking a lot, while 14.Bb2
reaches a very safe position where we win a few pawns and force Black to fight
to get them back, which leads to simplifications and piece (even though I
still like White a tiny bit better at the end!). The position is truly
critical, so I wanted to give you two possibilities and let you decide for
yourselves, what you like better. And, just a friendly reminder - don't drown
in these lines as 10...f5 is already a novelty - guys, even the World Champion
Carlsen didn't find it over the board, what's the chance your opponents will?}
(13... Bd7 {To resolve the pin is a natural desire, but now Black's bishop is
rather passive.} 14. O-O {Now, a few possibilities exist.} e4 (14... O-O {
This natural move allows for the very powerful} 15. d4 {which totals the Black
center. Now, his position is falling apart, for example} Nxd4 (15... e4 {
the most stubborn defense.} 16. Ne5 {It looks like we are hanging the
b5-bishop, but it'll all foreseen in advance.} Nxe5 17. dxe5 Bxb5 (17... Bxe5
18. Qxd5+ {And White pockets the e5-bishop.}) 18. Qxd5+ {A slightly messy line
results in simplifications and an endgame with some extra pawn for White.} Kh8
19. Qxb5 {White is two pawns up for the time being, but Black can get one back.
} Rb8 20. Qd5 Bxb4 21. Qxd8 Rfxd8 22. Be3 {At the end of some very messy line
- guys, sorry, I really did my best to keep things as accessible as possible,
but these positions are just so complex! - White retains a healthy extra pawn
