diagonal. The position remains very complicated, but I believe White is
clearly for choice as Black's central pawns aren't dangerous anymore and we
don't suffer from lack of space - our pieces found some lovely spots for
themselves. Instead, the weak long diagonal and our extra pawn are major
factors at the moment.}) 14. c4 {An extremely potent idea, in my opinion,
which makes Black's task rather difficult and leads to some exciting fresh
position, which wasn't covered by Jan in his course. We are immediately
challenging the Black center, trying to destroy it. At the same time, we might
want to push c4-c5!, grabbing tons on space on the queenside. At this point,
it makes sense to check what happens if Black castles, allowing c4-c5 as well
as what's going on if he takes on c4.} (14. Bb2 {The e5-pawn attacked and the
long diagonal is challenged. But, as Jan points out correctly, Black can
ignore this for the time being and sacrifice another pawn. As we say in
Russian, if the shed is on fire, let the house be on fire as well! Or in other
words, Black is already beyond the point when he's counting the pawns. other
moves are much worse and lead to a nearly losing position for Black, but in
order to avoid making this too lengthy, I'd let you work the rest out.} O-O 15.
Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Nxe5 {Now, White pockets another pawn.} Re8 {The only move, but
a natural one - the desire to take advantage of the pin is very instinctive.}
17. f4 {Now, we are ready to castle and start converting our extra stuff -
even giving up the b4-pawn isn't a problem. The advantage of being several
pawns up is that you can always try to consolidate by returning one of them!}
Qb6 {Black's got to stop us from castling or he'll be thrown out of business
soon. Jan cuts his analysis short here, saying Black is enjoying sufficient
compensation. Objectively he is right, but I believe it's definitely worth
digging deeper!} 18. a3 {Everything is safe on the e-file, so we simply
protect the pawn. Now, the idea is Qf3, possibly followed by Qf2 to resolve
the problems over the diagonal. Qf3-e3 would also do the job.} a5 {Black needs
to be active, or else we consolidate the position and compensation vanishes.}
19. Qf3 {We sacrifice one pawn, but get to stabilize the position a lot.} axb4
20. axb4 Bxe5 {It's the right time to take on e5 as White cannot take with the
bishop, as that would leave his bishop pinned and his a1-rook unprotected.} (
20... Qxb4 {This also draws, but in a more complicated (rather thankless and
joyless) way.} 21. Rxa8 Bxa8 22. Bc3 Qa4 23. Qe3 {We stop ...d5-d4 and castle
next.} Qxc2 24. O-O {A position like this is very close to just being a draw,
but it's not yet, and if Black takes on e5, White's bishop is going to be a
deal stronger. Objectively the draw is attainable with something like 24...d4,
though.} d4 25. Qxd4 Qe4 {Black sacrificed a pawn, but activated the a8-bishop.
} 26. Qxe4 Bxe4 {Black will draw this rather easily. Still, if anything, we
are the ones playing with the half-useless extra pawn!}) 21. fxe5 Qxb4 22. Rxa8
Rxa8 23. Qc3 {The game is still going, but White is continuing his fight for
the advantage.} Qe4+ 24. Kd1 Qxg2 25. Re1 {Objectively, after a few more
precise defensive moves, Black should make a draw, but it's clear that with
this powerful battery over the long diagonal and the threat of e5-e6 coming
down the pipeline, White is the one pressing for the advantage. It's just
important to understand that:  1: objectively, 4.Ng5! should be a forced draw
if we are speaking of the 25-30-move-long precise sequences;  2: we did pose
tons of problems to the opponent;  3: if they find dozens of perfect moves,
it's a draw - congratulations, you just drew the God of chess!;  4: we've been
off the official theory for the last 15 moves - no one in the world will find
all those moves.  So, I am happy with the amount of challenge Black is facing.}
) 14... dxc4 (14... O-O 15. c5 {We take more space while also securing the
b4-pawn, kicking the Black bishop back and preparing ideas like Qb3 or Ba4-b3
to put pressure on the d5-pawn.} Bc7 (15... e4 {Counterattack is a good thing
overall, but not here.} 16. Bxc6 Bxc6 17. Nd4 {Both Black bishops are hanging,
the end is approaching.} Qf6 18. Nxc6 {We don't care about the rook as we'll
get two pieces for it - this is just terrible for the opponent.}) 16. O-O {
I would also like to mention that 16.Bb2 is also very interesting and leads to
some incredibly fascinating positions - feel free to study them on your own!
Now, many moves are possible, such as 16...a6, 16...Nxb4, etc. I don't think
it's possible to exhaust this position with variations, but I would try to go
rather deeply and give you a few more insights on what can happen.} a6 (16...
Nxb4 {Black does get the pawn back, but he exposes himself to all the kinds of
threats over the b-file and loses control over the center. 17.Rb1 is my
primary suggestion, but 17.d4 is also very interesting, trying to immediately
challenge Black in the center.} 17. Rb1 {Now, several moves exist, but it
seems that ...Nc6 is the most logical one.} Nc6 18. Ba4 {Now the b7-bishop is
attacked.} Qc8 19. d3 {We restrain Black's center and prepare to play Re1 to
put pressure on the e5-pawn and to later take Bxc6 and Nxe5. Black cannot ever
play ...e5-e4 here, so his position is rather bad.} e4 20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Qb3+ {
And the b7-bishop, as well as the game, is lost.}) 17. Ba4 {The bishop is
finding itself a new good spot - now it'll go on b3, or possibly even to c2 in
some cases.} Qf6 {Activating the queen and connecting the rooks seems very
logical.} 18. d3 {Again, we restrain the Black pawns' activity. Importantly, ..
.e5-e4 never works, even though it looks tempting in order to attack the
a1-rook.} Kh8 {Another brilliant subtle move from the engine which I don't
think anyone would find.} (18... e4 19. dxe4 dxe4 20. Ng5 {The attack is
coming up!} Qxa1 21. Qh5 {And Black is instantly getting mated. This is very
beautiful, in fact!} h6 22. Bb3+ Kh8 23. Qg6 {Now there's no way to stop Qh7
with mate.} hxg5 24. Qh5# {What a lovely mate!}) 19. Rb1 {We avoid all that
potential headache related to the ...e5-e4 ideas, which are aimed at attacking
our rook. Now, again, there are countless possibilities, but let me show you
one funky line.} e4 {Black immediately decides to break through in the center.}
20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Bb2 {We develop with a tempo, everything looks good, but...}
Qh6 {Now the knight cannot move because of mate.} 22. Qd7 {The c7-bishop is
hanging, though, and Black has only one sufficient defense.} Rac8 {I won't get
into too much detail about these jungles, but all the other moves would have
lost the game for Black quite instantly.} 23. Nh4 {White can move the knight
as the g7-pawn would hang with mate.} Nb8 24. Qe7 Nc6 25. Qd7 {And the game
ends up in some ridiculous repetition! Well, I hope you all understand the
goal of this line was to rather demonstrate how the game can continue in this
position as opposed to serving a guideline that should be followed blindly.
Even the move 10...f5 is already a novelty, so there is no way we can predict
how the game will continue. So, I gave you that line where we grab two pawns
and start defending, trying to return one or even both and make it to a
slightly better endgame. But, objectively, that line is an almost forced draw
if Black finds a bunch of rather forced moves. He might not! But, I thought,
this repertoire wouldn't be complete if I didn't offer you a fighting option
as well, which would enable you to get an absolute mess and try to prove you
are a better player in this wild position - hopefully, a bit of preparation
should ensure your massive odds! This has been some of the craziest stuff I've
analyzed as of late, and definitely the craziest stuff I'm presenting here on
Chessable!}) 15. Qe2 {The idea of letting one central pawn go should not be
appealing to Black. Now, we easily get the advantage. White wants to capture
the c4-pawn with the queen, attacking the c6-knight. This also prevents Black
from castling.} Qc7 (15... O-O 16. Qxc4+ Kh8 17. Bxc6 {And White wins a piece.
The position still remains interesting! But that's a different story - as I've
been claiming, we are not looking to be as comfortable as possible while
playing this line - instead, we want to pose as many problems to the opponent
as possible, and that's what we get.}) 16. Qxc4 {Black needs to defend the
e5-pawn and make the c6-knight more stable.} a6 {The threat is to give a check
on e6. At the same time, we stop the opponent from castling. At this point, I
already feel Black's position is rather bad, for example} 17. Bxc6+ Qxc6 18.
Qe6+ Be7 19. Qxc6+ Bxc6 20. Nxe5 {White keeps the extra pawn in the endgame 
(he is two pawns up at the moment, but Black will pick the g2-pawn now). Black
still has compensation due to his bishop pair, but this is, obviously, a
one-sided game where we can either win or draw.} *

