1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 {A word of caution: this chapter has NOTHING to do
with the remainder of the repertoire (except for the first chapter on Black's
sidelines on move 3). This is the first time I'm doing something of this sort,
and as far as I am aware, the first time it's happening on Chessable.
Basically, I knew many of you would be rather inexperienced players quite new
to chess, and while you might have interest in this repertoire (or some parts
of it), learning the whole thing might sound too scary and rather impossible.
So, I wanted to provide... no, not a backup weapon. Rather a
'Explain-the-Italian-in-10-minutes' sort of thing, which would enable the most
inexperienced players with an opportunity to just develop pieces nicely and
get a reasonable game. WARNING: this chapter might often contain exaggerations.
For example, if I were to teach chess to a complete beginner, I'd tell him
that 1.e4 g6?? is a huge mistake as Black is giving up the center. And yes, I
am aware that 1...g6 is called the Modern Defence and is considered a rather
risky, yet non-refuted interesting opening. Why would I say that? Do I like to
lie? No, that is because I firmly believe a beginner would benefit greatly
from comprehending and mastering firmly the concept of the importance of
fighting for the center. Later, I would tell him about the Pirc. Or maybe not
- it's a trashy opening, after all. Joking aside, I just wanted to explain
that what I will give here are some rather basic ideas which will make
beginners' and casual players' play easy and convenient, but is likely to NOT
appeal and NOT hold true in the games of the stronger players.} Bc5 (3... Nf6
4. d3 {Again, we protect our pawn on e4. Now, the most logical move is 4...Bc5,
and it's discussed via 3...Bc5 4.d3 Nf6, while the other way to continue is 4..
.Be7. We won't be discussing the plans with ...h7-h6 and ...g7-g5 which are
currently popular at the GM-level as this chapter is supposed to help players
new to Italian get started swiftly as opposed to being theoretical research.}
Be7 {The bishop is placed more passively here, but it is great for defensive
purposes as it stops all the Bg5-related pins and doesn't ever run into c2-c3
and b2-b4, or that Na4 plan.} 5. O-O {Castling is very important, the sooner -
the better.} O-O {Black can also start with 5...d6, it doesn't matter - he
will make that move earlier as it's crucial for him to be able to protect the
e5-pawn one more time and develop the c8-bishop and, eventually, the a8-rook.}
6. Re1 {This is a good move as it protects the e4-pawn additionally, while
also possibly attacking the e5-pawn, thus discouraging all the ideas related
to ...d7-d5. We also prepare the idea of Nd2-f1-g3.} d6 7. a4 {This is a good
move because it prevents ...Na5 which was now possible, as the d6-pawn is
protecting the pawn on e5. That would have been undesirable for us as it'd
trap and trade our light-squared bishop. Now, Black has several moves, but
we'll look just at a sample line.} Be6 {Here, we can do several things, but
for the sake of simplicity, I like the idea of playing} (7... Bg4 {This is a
common mistake, which leads to a bad position after} 8. h3 {Now, Black should
rather accept his mistake and play ...Be6, but then we just got the free h2-h3
in, which is good as now the g4-square is controlled better and the escape
square is created.} Bh5 9. c3 {White covered the d4-square from ...Nd4 and is
ready to play Nbd2-f1-g3. The problem for Black is that once that happens,
he'd need to either trade his bishop for our knight which will provide us with
the bishop pair and leave no rival of the c4-bishop, or he'd have to retreat
to g6, but his bishop would be just dead there. White is already significantly
better.}) 8. Nbd2 {We don't mind having Black take on c4 as that activates our
knight, while after} Qd7 {We have several more useful moves, such as} 9. h3
Rfe8 10. c3 Rad8 11. b4 {Now it is high time we start playing on the queenside.
The next move can be b4-b5, kicking the c6-knight away. White's position is
very comfortable now.}) 4. d3 {We will just develop our pieces calmly. This
move enables the development of our queenside bishop and, possibly, the knight
might go to d2.} Nf6 5. Nc3 {This is a very simple way of handling the
position, which works perfectly in the youth tournaments, etc. But, sometimes
it is also getting tried at the highest level - just look up in the database
and you'll see hundreds of 2750+ level games. The idea could be to either jump
with the knight to d5 after Bg5, trying to make use of that pin, or to go Na4
and get the bishop pair.} d6 {This is the main move, but I am not sure if I am
a huge fan of it, actually!} (5... O-O {Now Bg5 is a funny trap that sometimes
works, but we won't count on that.} 6. O-O {Again, Black will go ...h7-h6 or ..
.d7-d6, where we will continue either with the plan of Na4 to get his bishop
pair, or with Be3 to ask him to take, which improves our structure and our
control over the central squares and opens the f-file. At the club level and
online, such positions are easier to handle as White, unless Black knows what
he's doing.} (6. Bg5 {This move isn't too impressive when Black can play ...
h7-h6 and ...Be7, joining the defense with his bishop. But, it would win
immediately if Black were careless.} d6 7. Nd5 {White will take on f6 to
follow with Nh4, Qh5, Nf5, and so on. Black is already nearly lost! That's the
blunder which has already been seen for thousands of times at a club level and
will be seen for several more thousands of times!})) (5... h6 {Let's suppose
our opponents are careful and stop the Bg5-related ideas while also not
playing ...d7-d6 yet and not letting us get their bishop with Na4!} 6. h3 {
Even Karjakin and Nepo, among many others, have played this move! We are
taking the g4-square under control, while also letting Black say a word.} d6 {
Is very similar to the mainline with 6...0-0. Of course, we'll take Black's
bishop again!} (6... O-O 7. O-O d6 8. Na4 {Again, we want that bishop!} Bb6 9.
Nxb6 axb6 10. a3 {We end up in positions very similar to those where Black
doesn't go ...h7-h6. It's all the same, we will go Re1 to protect the e4-pawn
and will try to push d3-d4 to open the game up a bit and gain a slight
advantage thanks to the better minor piece.}) (6... a6 {I feel like this is
the most careful way of handling this line, as this stops White's main idea.
Now, we'll resort to our second idea (which you can also try instead of Na4!)}
7. O-O d6 8. Be3 {Another key idea. It is even more powerful now, with the
Black pawn on a6, but it's also reasonable with the pawn on a7. We want to
have Black take the bishop and open the f-file for us while also enabling us
to increase our control over the d4 and f4-squares. The reason why it's worse
for us with the Black pawn on a7 is because Black can ignore our offer with ...
Bb6!, offering us to take there, where he'd answer ...axb6!, taking towards
the center and opening up the a-file for his rook. Generally, we do like the
idea of taking on b6 with the knight, as even though we open the a-file for
the opponent, we get the bishop pair. This is not the case when it comes to us
taking there with the bishop, though, as it is an equal trade, but he gets a
semi-open file. Fortunately, though, here this is not a problem anymore as
Black's pawn is on a6, so he cannot take ...axb6 anymore.} Bxe3 9. fxe3 O-O 10.
Qe1 {We intend to continue Nh4, Qg3, Nf5, Rf2, Raf1, and so on. The position
is objectively equal, but White's play is easier. The higher the level of
players, the easier it is to handle this with Black, while the less
experienced players will quickly find themselves under lots of pressure once
we start following this plan. One important remark is that in the event of ...
Be6 you would want to play Bb3, keeping the structure as it is and not letting
him get the symmetrical structure which arises after Bxe6 fxe6 - we don't need
that, as that'd kill our kingside ideas.}) 7. Na4 Bb6 8. a3 {Karjakin's move
seems rather interesting, though there's nothing wrong with the idea of taking
on b6 immediately, either.}) 6. Na4 {We will grab the opponent's bishop.} Bb6
7. Nxb6 axb6 8. a3 {A very important move that stops ...Na5, when Black would
get our bishop as well.} h6 {Stopping all the possible Bg5-related pins also
sounds reasonable.} (8... Be6 {Black wants to deprive us of the bishop pair.}
9. Bxe6 fxe6 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 {We stop all the possible play related to ...
d6-d5. Later, we can try either c2-c3 and d3-d4, or d3-d4 immediately in order
to open the position up. Our eventual goal might be to open the game up and
trade down a bit and try to use our bishop, which would be slightly superior
to the Black knight. Game on!}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Re1 {We continue in the same
manner, possibly preparing d3-d4 and protecting the e4-pawn in advance.} Be6 {
This is very similar to 8...Be6.} (10... Re8 {Black can also just make some
move of this sort, putting pressure on the e4-pawn in advance.} 11. Bd2 {
We are slightly improving the position of our bishop, waiting for Black to
make a move. The main point is} Be6 12. Bxe6 Rxe6 13. c4 {And White grabs a
rather significant space advantage. This is equal, but a bit easier to play as
White who will try to go Bc3 and eventually push d3-d4, or possibly, will
continue h2-h3, Nh4, Rf1, and f2-f4.}) 11. Bxe6 fxe6 {Now either d3-d4, or the
calmer moves like c2-c3 or Be3 make sense, it's a normal playable position
where we will be trying to eventually push d3-d4.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Bc5"]
[Black "Morphy, E. vs. Ford A"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C52"]
[PlyCount "45"]

{I couldn't help but show you this absolutely gorgeous game. This is exactly
the type of chess I make my young aspiring students play! This is the type of
chess so many amateur and professional chess players enjoy, even though
nowadays at the top-level people cannot play this way anymore. Objectively,
this isn't the most sound game out there and White was dead-lost at some point,
but in my opinion, those old games just need to be watched and enjoyed.
Analyzing them all the way to scrutiny with modern engines is a pure chess
crime. DISCLAIMER: It wasn't played by Paul Morphy. Instead, it was his uncle
Ernest who won this game as White!} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4
5. c3 Ba5 6. O-O ({As you know, I suggest} 6. d4 {in the theoretical chapter.
But, this isn't what matters.}) 6... Nge7 {A typical mistake, as now the
f7-pawn is too weak.} (6... Nf6 $1 {Is the reason why we should start with 6.
d4, as now we are not fast enough - the e4-pawn is under pressure. Let's see
what happened, though!}) 7. Ng5 {Of course, Morphy (that's so typical of their
family!) doesn't miss out on a chance to attack.} d5 {The only defense, but it
doesn't lead to a fun situation.} (7... O-O $2 8. Qh5 {And the game would have
been over immediately as both f7 and h7 cannot be protected.}) 8. exd5 Nxd5 9.
Nxf7 {A very typical idea in these positions. The Black king is immediately
lured in the very center.} Kxf7 10. Qf3+ Ke6 {This is way over the top - the
king is in too much danger here.} (10... Qf6 $1 {Would have been the only
sound defense, and after 11.Bxd5+ 11.Qxd5+ Be6 Black manages to defend.} 11.
Bxd5+ Be6 12. Bxe6+ Kxe6 {It's a bit ugly to have the king on e6, but Black is
on time to hide it on f7 and should be almost alright. I'm saying almost
because, after all, White isn't any material down anymore, so he's just
enjoying some free initiative, which is always nice.}) 11. Ba3 {White wanted
to stop ...Rf8, I guess. But, this move proves a bit slow and loses the
momentum.} (11. Re1 $1 {This move with the intention of d2-d4, while also
bringing the rook in the game, would have been extremely powerful, instead.
The immediate d2-d4 would have done the job as well.}) 11... Bb6 12. Re1 Na5 {
Here comes this beauty. The next move is losing, but I am not going to discuss
it from the objective standpoint.} 13. Rxe5+ {Typically you give exclamation
marks to the excellent move, while this one isn't, according to the engine.
Still, it gets my exclamation marks for the brilliancy, for the fantasy, for
the imagination. This is why we love chess!! The Black king is lured all the
way to the center.} Kxe5 14. d4+ Ke6 15. g4 {White wants to play Qf5 with a
checkmate!} (15. Qe4+ Kf6 16. Bxd5 {Would have been more sound objectively,
but that wouldn't be in Morphy's style!}) 15... g6 {Now White's idea pays off!}
(15... c5 $1 {The brutal computer move stops the White bishop from controlling
the squares on the a3-f8 diagonal and wins. But okay, who cares? We are here
to enjoy the show!}) 16. Qe4+ Kf7 17. Bxd5+ Kg7 18. Be7 {We need to give the
check on e5, but then ...Qf6 would defend... So, White blocks that diagonal
and the path for the queen!} Re8 {Now it's over. A forced mate.} 19. Qe5+ Kh6
20. g5+ Kh5 21. Bf3+ Bg4 22. Qg3 Qd7 23. Qh3# {What a beauty! It's worth
playing chess for years to play just a game or two like that. And who cares
White if was lost according to the engine? Don't get me wrong - I am not
trying to teach you to go for the lost positions. But, I do want to
demonstrate that people crack under pressure, just as Black did in this game!
1-0 (23) Morphy, E-Ford, A New Orleans 1840.} 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Bc5"]
[Black "Lomasov, S. vs. Lysyj"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C52"]
[PlyCount "65"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. O-O
Bb6 9. Nbd2 Na5 10. Qc2 Nxc4 11. Nxc4 Qc6 12. Nxb6 axb6 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Nxe5
{In the theoretical section, we stop at this point. Here I conclude with words
'White gets his pawn back and opens up the position, which is extremely
favorable as we are ahead in development. This is an equal position,
objectively, but I definitely like White better here practically and the
results prove my opinion as White scored 4/6, having won two games, drawn 4
and lost none.' Let us now see how White managed to take advantage of his lead
in development in this game and what ideas are available to us!} Qa4 {Lysyj
defends well. While driving the Black queen away from the kingside seems
dangerous, that's the right move as it challenges the White queen and prevents
White from creating more threats.} (14... Qe6 {Black can defend in this manner
as well, but here I am rather suspicious about his position as White gets to
develop and start creating threats rather rapidly.} 15. Nd3 $5 $146 {It's also
interesting to try this odd-looking move, trying to bring the knight over to
d5 via f4 or b4.} (15. Nf3 Nf6 16. Bf4 O-O {Now White can either simplify the
position and make a draw, or keep playing.} 17. Rfe1 {And the game continues,
our next move can be Be5 or Nd4, followed by Bg3 and f2-f4. Black's problem is
that it's not easy to benefit from our weak queenside pawns, while White's
extra pawn on the kingside might prove rather useful if White manages to get
those pawns going quickly.} (17. Bxc7 {This is just a draw.} Qxe4 18. Qxe4 Nxe4
$11 {and the queenside pawns get traded.})) 15... Nf6 16. c4 $1 {The bishop
will find an excellent spot for itself on b2.} O-O 17. Re1 $40 {I definitely
think that White, who is about to continue with Bb2, Nf4-d5, f2-f3, etc, is
for choice. His position is both better objectively and a lot easier
practically.}) 15. Qd3 {Now, the queen is going to g3.} Nf6 16. Bg5 {White
immediately challenges the f6-knight, getting engaged in a rather forcing
sequence.} ({But, it's worth mentioning that} 16. Re1 {was possible and rather
good, too, keeping the tension.}) 16... Qxe4 {This is a very bold-looking
decision, but it's absolutely correct. Black does have to play this resolutely.
} (16... O-O $6 {Had Black just ignored our idea, his position would have
instantly gotten rather terrible after the simple} 17. Bxf6 gxf6 18. Nf3 $40 {
White's knight will go to d4 and later to f4, the queen is coming to e3-f4 or
e3-h6, the Black king is terribly weak.}) 17. Qb5+ {White switches the angle
of the attack.} c6 (17... Nd7 $4 18. Rae1 {The other rook's move would also do.
Now Black is losing instantly as the discovered check is going to be deadly 
(Nxd7+, Ng6+, whatever).}) 18. Qxb6 {Now the obvious threats include Re1 and
Bxf6, so Black needs to castle urgently.} O-O 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Rae1 {Both
sides have been playing extraordinarily precisely! I don't want to discourage
your excitement about this by saying it's likely that both players have
analyzed it very deeply, but that could be true, too. Position-wise, White's
willing to give up his queenside (the a2-pawn) as the Black king is rather
weak now and the idea of bringing the rook over to f3 or g3 via e3 is too
attractive. Objectively, it's still balanced. But, whom would you prefer in a
practical game?!} Qd5 21. Nf3 {Even though this obstructs the 3rd rank, the
knight had to retreat. But, in the future it can come to d4 or h4 and join the
attack via f5.} Rxa2 22. Re3 (22. Re7 $5 {Would have been a rather attractive
move as well, keeping an eye on the b7-pawn and intending to double up with
Rfe1, possibly preparing Re8. But this wouldn't have been very consistent with
White's previous play (and rather with what I was explaining earlier!), so
White continued in a more natural way.}) 22... Ra6 23. Qc7 {White goes wrong 
(not too wrong, just a somewhat imprecise move) - it would have been better to
retreat to b1 in order to be able to control the first rank and prepare Rd1.
But, it's barely possible to demand the impeccable accuracy in such a murky
position. The move in the text is also very logical as it prepares the queen
transfer to g3, or to f4-h6.} c5 {Black tries to join the game with his
a6-rook.} 24. Qg3+ Kh8 25. Rfe1 Re6 26. Qf4 {A few very logical moves have
been made. Black is still perfectly fine, but White wants to bring the queen
over to h6, which would threaten the f8-rook and the f6-pawn and create a
threat of Rxe6 followed by Qxf6.} Qd6 27. Qh6 Rxe3 {Black simplifies on time.
It's a mystery why White didn't take with the rook, but perhaps, he was just
very excited about the idea that soon won him the game.} 28. fxe3 Rg8 29. e4 {
The pawn starts marching to e5, taking advantage of the fact the d6-queen is
unprotected. Again, this is still a perfectly sound position for Black - in
fact, White even overpressed with this fxe3, and now Black should be able to
stop the attack with careful moves like ...Rg6 and even be somewhat better.}
Bg4 {Ignorance. Now White's counterplay actually starts existing.} 30. e5 Qa6 {
The only right move would have been ...Qd8, keeping an eye on the f6-pawn. ...
Qf8 also saves, but leads to an unpleasant position.} (30... Qd8 $1 $13) (30...
Qf8 31. Qxf6+ (31. Qxf8 Rxf8 32. exf6 {The engine says it's a dead draw, which
is true, but with the pawn on f6 and threats of the backrank mate, Black is
the one feeling uncomfortable here.}) 31... Qg7 $13 {White can either allow
for the trade on f6, which would give him the somewhat more pleasant endgame,
or choose to continue with the queens on the board - either way, Black is
still under a bit of pressure.}) 31. e6 {Boom. Now the f6-pawn cannot be
defended and Black resigned. Let me show to you, dear students, why he made
such a seemingly premature decision. 1-0 (31) Lomasov,S (2549) - Lysyj,I (2630)
Yaroslavl 2018} Bxe6 32. Qxf6+ Rg7 33. Rd1 {And there is no way Black can stop
Rd8 with mate. What can we say about this game? Was it a one-sided game?
Definitely not - Black was defending extremely well, and at some point, when
White over pushed, he even was somewhat better. But, does this mean the
position is unplayable for White or something? Of course, not! You won't be
facing 2600+ GMs who were Russian Champions and 2700+ players in the past,
your opponents will be going down under pressure a lot faster. As you can see,
even for such a fantastic player and theoretician as Lysyj, the position
didn't turn out easy to handle at all. And, White could always simplify early
on, he wasn't obliged to take these risks and give up the a2-pawn, even though
this definitely seems to be the right way to play chess gambit-wise. Hopefully,
such a game would give you a better understanding why these positions are
rather dangerous for Black from the practical perspective despite the engine's
optimism and equality.} 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Bc5"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, S. vs. Ding"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C52"]
[PlyCount "78"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5 6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. O-O
Bb6 9. Nbd2 Na5 10. Qc2 Nxc4 11. Nxc4 exd4 {We've discussed this variation in
the theoretical chapter and I called this move a serious mistake which
concedes the center and allows White to get an overwhelming position rather
easily.} 12. cxd4 Ne7 13. a4 {Creating a very obvious, yet very
hard-to-deal-with threat of a4-a5, trapping the bishop. This move also enables
White to prepare Ba3 followed by e4-e5, which would open the a3-f8 diagonal as
well as the e-file, potentially.} c6 14. Ba3 {Now this move comes with a tempo.
} Bc7 15. e5 {Mamedyarov isn't letting Black relax even for a single move.}
dxe5 16. dxe5 O-O 17. Rfd1 {Another piece joins the game while also winning a
tempo.} Qe8 18. Nd6 {At this point, I cut the theoretical coverage, having
claimed that 'White's advantage was nearly decisive, but Black managed to save
half a point with the combination of stubborn defense and luck.' Let us now
see how the game continued and how White could improve on his play.} Bxd6 19.
Bxd6 {A normal move that keeps Black under pressure. But, I believe, the pawn
recapture would have been the easier choice.} (19. exd6 $1 {Also looked very
natural and would have enabled White to win an exchange.} Ng6 20. d7 $1 {
That a3-bishop gets to say a word.} Bxd7 21. Bxf8 Nxf8 22. a5 $16 {This would
have been a terrible position for Black, despite the material equality (he has
two pawns for the missing exchange). His problem is that White's rooks enjoy
several open and semi-open files on the queenside and will be easily able to
put tons of pressure on those queenside pawns. Besides that, Black's pieces
are rather passive, so his position is on the verge of being lost. Perhaps
Mamedyarov thought this wasn't enough, having decided to rather enjoy his
initiative without cashing out and grabbing material.}) 19... b6 {Another
inaccuracy - Black totally had to play something like ...Be6 or ...Bg4. His
idea to develop the bishop on b7 is understandable, but now the queenside
pressure simply becomes unbearable.} 20. a5 Bf5 21. Qb2 Qd7 22. Qa3 {A good
move that preserves this large advantage, but at this point, White had a
killer solution.} (22. e6 $3 {Would have won instantly, the point being} Qxe6 (
22... Bxe6 {doesn't help either as after} 23. Ne5 $1 Qe8 {Black's position is
cramped, which, unsurprisingly, leads him to the decisive material losses.} 24.
axb6 axb6 25. Rxa8 Qxa8 26. Bxe7 $18 {White finally wins that knight and the
game.}) 23. Qa3 $1 {The knight is hanging and the d6-bishop is protected.} Rfe8
(23... c5 {doesn't help, either.} 24. axb6 axb6 25. Qxa8 $1 Rxa8 26. Rxa8+ Nc8
27. Bc7 {Now not only Rd8+, but also Rxc8! followed by Rd8+ is unstoppable.} h6
28. Rxc8+ $1 Qxc8 29. Rd8+ {And White simplifies the position, keeping an
extra piece in the endgame - he should win easily.}) 24. Re1 $18 {Now that the
d6-bishop isn't hanging anymore, White is able to move the rook away from d1
and win.}) 22... Rfd8 {Again this e5-e6 ! idea would have been really powerful.
} 23. axb6 {This lets Black off the hook.} axb6 24. Qxa8 Rxa8 25. Rxa8+ Nc8 26.
e6 Bxe6 27. Ne5 {White went for this forcing line, having thought he was
winning at the end, but Black is just on time to hold on.} Qb7 28. Rb8 Qa6 {
This looks ugly, but somehow Black black is able to not lose all the material.}
29. Nxc6 h6 30. Ne7+ Kh7 31. Nxc8 Bxc8 {Now that the pin over the 8th rank has
been dealt with, Black has nothing to worry about and soon the game was drawn.}
32. h3 Qe2 33. Rc1 Bxh3 {The nicest way to force the draw, as Black finds a
lovely double attack.} 34. gxh3 Qd2 {Now both pieces on c1 and g5 are hanging,
which forces White to allow for a perpetual.} 35. Ba3 Qg5+ 36. Kf1 Qb5+ 37. Kg2
Qg5+ 38. Kf1 Qb5+ 39. Kg2 Qg5+ {And the stubborn/tricky Ding Liren was able to
save half a point. Despite the fact White didn't break through and couldn't
convert such a promising position, I am extremely happy to present this game
to you, guys, as it's really illustrative and remarkable that even top-players,
such as Ding, often cannot handle these sharp situations, especially while
caught off guard and without having refreshed all the sharp variations before
the game. I think that's another beautiful illustration of why I find the
Evans such a practical interesting weapon! 1/2 (39) Mamedyarov,S (2747) - Ding,
L (2766) Huaian 2016} 1/2-1/2

