{[%evp 0,73,14,46,37,37,21,25,29,-20,-39,-35,-36,-70,23,-26,15,-36,30,-43,13,
-15,45,22,15,21,5,4,0,14,-27,-29,26,51,38,31,42,-29,22,17,20,51,43,6,33,34,25,
-26,-8,0,0,0,23,0,0,0,0,0,67,12,43,-59,-35,-42,35,-34,376,359,442,402,402,354,
410,402,398,424] In this game, we are going to look at a rather interesting
situation, where the Azeri GM Safarli was in a must-win situation at the World
Cup, during his match with the young Indian prodigy Nihal Sarin. What's very
unusual is that Nihal, unlike 99% of the talented youngsters, is known for his
fantastic positional understanding, as opposed to tactical sharpness. So,
Safarli decided to force the opponent into a rather non-standard position
where it won't be easy to make decisions based on common sense and general
positional understanding.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Ba5
6. d4 d6 7. Qb3 Qd7 8. O-O Bb6 9. Nbd2 Na5 {Up to here, we've been following
the theoretical chapter, so I am not explaining anything in order not to
repeat myself twice, and here comes a slightly different move.} 10. Qb1 {
I like this move less than 10.Qc2 that I am suggesting in the theoretical
chapter, but let's think, what are the ideas behind this somewhat ugly move,
which doesn't let White connect the rooks fast. For one, I see that White
might want to take on e5 and then play Bb5, forcing either ...Nc6 or ...c7-c6,
which would weaken the dark squares. The important part about this is that the
b5-square is now protected by the White queen. I cannot call myself a huge fan
of this move as I find it a bit unnatural, but let's see how the game unfolds.}
Ne7 {One of many possibilities. Black is ready to sacrifice a pawn (or rather
return the extra pawn) in order to castle quickly.} 11. dxe5 O-O (11... dxe5 $4
{would have not just been dangerous, but it would have lost immediately.} 12.
Nxe5 {And White captures the f7-pawn with a check on the next move, reaching
an absolutely winning position.}) 12. Bb5 {Eltaj wants to force ...c7-c6 in
order to deprive the Black knight of that square.} (12. exd6 {Was also
interesting and was tried in one game by Lomasov - remember the previous game
between Lomasov and Lysyj? Semen Lomasov is sort of a hero of the Evans, check
out his games!} cxd6 13. Bd3 Ng6 14. Nc4 (14. Nd4 {would have been more
interesting in order to keep more pieces, possibly prepare Nf5 or Nb5, or
possibly Nb3 to ask Black to trade that knight and hope to recapture axb3,
with a balanced interesting position.}) 14... Nxc4 15. Bxc4 Qc7 16. Qb3 Bg4 17.
Nd4 {I don't think White handled this extraordinarily well, as Black managed
to develop and generate pressure on our c3-pawn rather easily.} Rac8 18. Bd5
Qxc3 19. Qxc3 Rxc3 20. Nb5 Rc2 21. Bb3 {Finally, Black won a pawn, but White
managed to obtain quite a lot of activity in return, so Black chose to repeat
the moves here. Not necessarily a decision I would make, but a relatively
understandable one.} Rc6 22. Bd5 Rc2 23. Bb3 Rc6 24. Bd5 Rc2 {1/2 (24) Lomasov,
S (2490) - Petrosyan,M (2554) Tarvisio 2017}) 12... c6 (12... Nac6 $2 {would
have been terrible as it would have lost control over the c4-square. Now, after
} 13. exd6 $1 Qxd6 14. Nc4 $1 {White is quickly gaining strategic initiative,
as well as the dynamic one. For example, after} Qg6 15. Nxb6 axb6 16. Bf4 $40 {
we have the bishop pair and Black's pawn on c7 is a huge target - White is
clearly better.}) (12... Nec6 $1 {Would have been the right move, even though
it looks a bit weird. Black needs to preserve the seemingly bad-looking knight
on a5 in order to control the c4 square and he is doing just fine here. Later,
he might play ...Qg4 and develop the light-squared bishop with a normal
position.}) 13. Bd3 Rd8 14. Nc4 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 {Even though the position got
somewhat simplified, it's still not easy to explain how the Black queenside
pieces are supposed to get developed.} Ng6 (15... d5 $1 {Would have been the
cleaner defense, which would have enabled Black to resolve at least problems
over the d-file.} 16. exd5 cxd5 17. Bd3 Ng6 {At least, now it's clear that
Black just needs to go ...Qc7 or ...Qe7 and develop the c8-bishop somewhere to
e6 or g4, followed by ...Rac8, reaching... if not a great position - things
remain balanced - then, at least, a position where it's very clear what he
should be doing.}) 16. Rd1 {The pressure over the d-file is rather unpleasant,
too. At this point, I feel that Black's position is already very difficult to
handle.} Qg4 17. Rxd6 {I find this recapture rather hasty, as now White loses
all the potential over the d-file and his extra e-pawn isn't too useful.} (17.
Qb3 $1 {Would have been even more annoying. The problem is that Black cannot
defend the pawn in the most natural way.} Be6 $2 (17... Nh4 $1 {The engine
shows this lovely move which aims to get counterplay, and perhaps it does, but
things look rather favorable for White anyway.} 18. Bxf7+ Kh8 19. Nxh4 Qxh4 20.
Be3 {And we easily protect the f2-square, while Black's queenside is still a
large problem and concern.}) 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. h3 $1 {It's worth worsening the
position of the Black queen instead of hurrying to take that pawn on d6, as
now Black is losing the e6-pawn as well.} Qxe4 20. Qxe6+ Kh8 21. Ng5 $18 {
And White has the decisive attack, now both Nxe4 and Nf7+ cannot be stopped,
so it's a good position for Black to resign in.}) 17... Rf8 18. Qb3 Nf4 {
Now, Black managed to untangle and get activity - most importantly, his
queenside pieces are now able to get out. Later, it was a brutal fight where
White ended up coming out on top.} 19. Bxf4 Qxf4 20. Rd3 Bg4 21. e6 {White
simplifies the position and trades the g4-bishop just on time.} fxe6 22. Bxe6+
Kh8 23. Bxg4 Qxe4 {A very precise move for Black - the rook on d3 is hanging,
so he is on time to capture this pawn as well.} 24. Rd7 Qxg4 25. Ne5 Qf4 26.
Nf7+ Kg8 27. Nd6+ Kh8 {Here White could have taken the draw, but he had to win.
So, the game continued.} 28. Rf1 h6 29. Kh1 Rf6 30. Nc4 {Had Black found the
right answer, White would have just lost! But, things went differently and it
was the Azeri GM who managed to make it into the next round of the World Cup.}
Bxf2 {Black still keeps the advantage, but the game is complicated and Black
needs to win anew.} (30... Re8 $1 {The threat is ...Qxf2! followed by ...Re1
with mate, White can barely do anything about this.}) 31. Nd2 Qg4 {I am not
going to criticize and discuss in detail every single move, as this was a pure
carnage in a mutual time scramble.} 32. Rxb7 Rg6 {This was it - Black just
forgot about his bishop.} 33. Rxf2 {And White won without any additional
adventures.} Kh7 34. Nf3 Re8 35. Qb1 Re3 36. Rb4 Qe6 37. Rf1 {This wasn't
another one-sided win. Instead, again we got a pure massacre, where the
luckier player went on to win. In my opinion, it's better to play Qc2 instead
of Qb1 in the opening, as those positions are a lot cleaner and White's play
is a lot more obvious and straightforward, but I wanted to demonstrate this
game to you, nevertheless, as I find it rather thrilling and fun to analyze!
Plus, it's always good to know your opening can be handled in several ways.
1-0 (37) Safarli,E (2593) - Nihal,S (2610) Khanty-Mansiysk 2019} 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
