[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Bc5"]
[Black "Huschenbeth, N. vs. Karpatchev"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C51"]
[PlyCount "111"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Be7 6. d4 Na5 7. Bd3 d6 8. dxe5
dxe5 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qc2 c5 {Again, we'll start the discussion
only here as the rest has been covered in the theoretical section. In fact, we
analyze a few next moves in the theoretical chapter as well, but I would like
to once again reinforce the point that Black should try to immediately trade
the knight with ...Nd7, equalizing. But, the move ...c7-c5, while it's the
most popular move, is a mistake, in my opinion. Black won't get much by
pushing his c-pawn down the board and White gets the time to get active on the
kingside.} 12. Nd2 Qc7 13. f4 {Let me quote myself from the theoretical
chapter here: 'I think that this move, as played by the notable theoretician
Huschenbeth, among others, is a clear improvement over Nc4, as was played in
Kryvoruchko-Karjakin. Why so and what's the idea? Well, White has more space
and pawn weaknesses, which means he needs to play actively to utilize his
dynamic advantages as well as not to end up trading a lot of pieces/
transposing in some inferior endgame where he'll struggle a lot with his
weaknesses. That's exactly what we do!'} b6 (13... Be6 {Black can also develop
in this way, where White can choose between several promising continuations.}
14. Ndf3 {In the theoretical chapter, I recommend this move, which looks very
good to me. But, other continuations are also possible and interesting for
White! I just didn't want to give 2-3 additional options as trainable or
alternative variations.} (14. Ndc4 $5 $146 Nxc4 15. Bxc4 {You might wonder why
we played this, as we are supposed to want to keep more pieces on the board as
opposed to trading. That is try, but the point is that after} Bxc4 16. Nxc4 b5
17. Ne3 {We get to play e4-e5 on the next move, kick that knight away and jump
to d5 or f5 with our knight, gaining a lot of activity. If Black doesn't play .
..c5-c4 himself, we might want to play c3-c4! in order to later develop the
bishop to the long diagonal, to b2.}) (14. c4 {The idea of grabbing the long
diagonal immediately also seems fairly attractive.} Rad8 15. Nb3 $1 {We hope
Black would take on b3 and fix our structure. But if not, our knight is quite
well-placed on b3! Now, it's also not so easy for Black to come up with a move.
For example, after} Nd7 $1 16. Bb2 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Qd7 18. Rad1 $40 {It's rather
obvious that White is enjoying the initiative.})) 14. c4 {I like the idea, as
White ensures full control over the long diagonal.} Bb7 15. Ndf3 {Now White
goes wrong, though.} (15. Nb3 $1 {Would have been much stronger. Now Black
clearly doesn't want to let us take on a5 and spoil his structure. The capture
on b3 is an obvious concession, while after} Nc6 16. Nxc6 Qxc6 17. e5 $40 {
White's initiative is clearly becoming very powerful}) 15... Rad8 {The problem
is that Black might want to sacrifice an exchange with ...Rxd3, followed by ...
Nxe4, with some terrific compensation.} 16. Bb2 (16. Re1 $1 {Would have
stopped Black's idea.}) 16... Rxd3 {Black, instead, decides to follow with
that exchange sacrifice.} (16... Nh5 $1 {Black didn't realize he had this very
powerful resource. The idea might not be obvious even when you have this
position on the board right in front of you.} 17. g3 {The pawn was hanging, so
g2-g3 is very natural.} f6 $1 {Suddenly the knight is short on squares. Wait,
we can still play Ng4. It can't be that bad, can it?} 18. Ng4 {But here comes
the problem...} Nxf4 $3 19. gxf4 Qxf4 {Suddenly this g4-knight is barely
capable of moving, White is losing. To be frank, this is an absolutely inhuman
tactic, which I don't think most titled players would find unless it was given
to them as a tactical problem when they knew in advance there was something.
Anyway, it doesn't make White's last move in the text better, I had to show
you this!} 20. h3 h5 $1 21. Ngh2 Qe3+ $1 {And the d3-bishop will be lost.}) 17.
Qxd3 Nxe4 18. Rae1 f6 {Retreating with the knight wouldn't have been
attractive, so Black throws more wood into the fire. Now a rather forcing
sequence follows.} 19. Rxe4 Rd8 20. Qc2 Bxe4 21. Qxe4 fxe5 22. Nxe5 {As a
result, Black got his exchange back, while White managed to stabilize the
position. As a result, White is clearly somewhat better, because the a5-knight
is just terrible - this is something you can tell especially distinctively in
a simplified position like this one, as the fewer the pieces, the more
important it is that each piece does some job. Besides that, White's bishop is
very strong on the long diagonal. Additionally, the fact that White has an
extra pawn on the kingside (or that Black doesn't have the f-pawn) means Black
is likely to experience problems with his king at some point. Say, if White
pushed f4-f5-f6 at an appropriate moment.} Bf6 23. Bc3 Qb7 24. Qf5 {Of course,
White shouldn't be willing to trade the queens, as that would have immediately
resolved all of Black's problems. Now Qe6+ is a rather serious threat.} Qc8 25.
Qh5 {Instead of forcing the better endgame (see annotations below), White
chooses to keep the tension.} (25. Qxc8 $5 {Here the queen trade could make
sense. Not that it suddenly started making sense strategically, but now Black
doesn't get to recapture with his knight and after} Rxc8 26. Bxa5 $1 {White
gets to spoil the Black structure. I can understand, though, that White wasn't
willing to go here as he could have been afraid of some better, but
non-winnable rook endgame in the future. Say, after} bxa5 27. Rd1 g5 $1 28. Rd5
gxf4 29. Kf2 Bxe5 30. Rxe5 Rd8 {It's likely that soon we'll arrive at some
rook endgame 2 vs 1 or something.}) 25... Qb7 26. Re1 Rf8 {Man, I really feel
bad for that a5-knight. Why not play ...Nc6, improving it?!} 27. Bxa5 {Finally
this structure becomes terrible!} bxa5 28. Qf5 Bxe5 29. Qxe5 {Now White will
be better until the rest of the game - this type of advantage is very steady.
It's important that due to the queens' presence on the board, Black's
defensive task is a lot more difficult as his king is weaker. Let's see how
White keeps improving his position - this is happening slowly, but surely.} Qf7
30. Re4 Rc8 31. h3 h6 32. Kh2 a4 33. h4 Rc7 34. f5 {Now ideas like Qe6,
forcing the queen trade at a moment of White's choosing, as well as Rg4 or Rf4,
combined with f5-f6, make Black's life quite difficult.} Rc8 35. Rg4 Rc6 36.
Kh3 Rf6 37. Rf4 Rc6 38. g4 {White can easily afford a move like this, as
Black's pieces are extremely passive. I don't want to be discussing where
specifically Black went wrong, or where the final straw broke camel's back.
Let's just say such positions tend to be very unpleasant in practical games
and typically you lose them not in one move, but rather step by step.} Rc8 39.
Re4 Rd8 40. Kg3 (40. Qxc5 {This pawn was already edible, as checks don't lead
anywhere.} Rd3+ 41. Kg2 Rd2+ 42. Kg3 Rd3+ 43. Re3 $1 {The queen endgame will
be winning on account of the important line} Rxe3+ 44. Qxe3 Qxc4 $4 45. Qe6+ $1
{With the winning pawn endgame.}) 40... Rd3+ 41. Kf4 Qf6 42. g5 hxg5+ 43. hxg5
Qxe5+ 44. Rxe5 {And White went on to win this rook endgame.} Rd4+ 45. Re4 Rd2
46. a3 Kf7 (46... Rf2+ {could still give some chances, but this is already
very tough. The important defense Black had to find was} 47. Kg4 g6 $1 {
The point being that after} 48. f6 {White does get a protected passed pawn,
but the pawn on g5 is very weak, so the White king cannot go too far. That's
not very easy!}) 47. Re6 Rd4+ 48. Ke5 Rxc4 49. Ra6 Rc1 50. Rxa4 c4 51. Rxa7+
Kf8 52. g6 c3 53. Kd4 c2 54. Kc3 Ke8 55. f6 gxf6 56. g7 {And finally, after
this rather tense struggle, White went on to win. Truth be told, besides that
chance in the early middlegame, where this cool move 16...Nh5! was really
strong, Black didn't have any chances to play for a win and just had to stick
to the passive defense, and eventually, he did not manage to hold. I think
White's technique shown in this game was rather impressive! 1-0 (56)
Huschenbeth,N (2581) - Karpatchev,A (2513) Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2017}
1-0

