1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Nf4 10. Bf1 {As I explain in the theoretical coverage, while 10.
0-0, most likely, just transposes to the lines which we study after 9...Bd6
followed by ...Nf4, this move is even better. It's more principled and
attempts to simply refute Black's move order. And, I believe, it is the reason
why almost nobody starts with ...Nf4. Now Black doesn't get to take on d3 and
we are about to play either d2-d3 with the idea of Bxf4 or even d2-d4!,
opening up the center, as the e5-pawn is the only defender of that unstable
knight.} e4 {The most principled move. Which, however, doesn't quite work.} (
10... Bd6 11. d4 $1 {As we discuss in the theoretical chapter, Black's
position starts falling apart here.} e4 (11... exd4 12. Qxd4 {This is just a
healthy extra pawn.}) 12. Ne5 Ne6 13. Nc3 $16 {Again, just a healthy extra
pawn for us. Moreover, the e4-pawn is attacked.}) 11. d3 {The f4-knight is
hanging. Retreating means accepting failure as then we just win another pawn.}
exf3 (11... Ne6 $2 12. dxe4 $18 {Two pawns would be too much, White will win
easily. Unless he didn't work on endgame at all, which he should!}) 12. Bxf4
Qf6 {I mention this trick in the theoretical chapter and would like to remind
you again how to deal with it. Now both the bishop and the b2-pawn are hanging.
} 13. Qxf3 Qxb2 14. Qe2+ Be6 15. Be5 {This is imprecise as it allows for the
check on c1.} (15. Qe5 $1 {This is the most precise way to extinguish all the
possible counterplay, because after} Bb4+ 16. Kd1 $16 {Even though White loses
the right to castle, which seems undesirable, the Black queen is now getting
trapped and Black has to trade!}) 15... Qc1+ 16. Qd1 Qg5 {This again allows
White to stabilize the position.} (16... Bb4+ $1 {Would have yielded just
enough counterplay immediately.} 17. c3 (17. Bc3 $2 Qb2 $1 {is a rather nasty
surprise!}) 17... Qb2 $1 {And Black gets some interesting counterplay as Nd2
just hangs the c3-pawn, which is rather unappealing.} 18. Bxg7 Rg8 19. cxb4
Rxg7 $11 {The rook and the b4-pawn are both hanging, so Black will get a pawn
back. He would still be a pawn down, but his pieces are rather active and now
it's not easy to develop the f1-bishop because the g2-pawn is under some
serious pressure.}) 17. Bc3 (17. f4 $1 {Would have been a lot more active.} Qg6
18. Qf3 $1 {White's developing in a rather ambitious manner, while also,
possibly, keeping an eye on the c6-pawn and keeping in mind ideas like Bc3!?
to attack the knight and that pawn. But, ideas like c2-c3, d3-d4, Bd3, etc, or
Be2 and 0-0 are also very natural and attractive. It's worth mentioning,
though, that we need to be very careful about playing Be2 as ...Bd5! would
attack both the queen and the g2-pawn!}) 17... O-O-O {This is way over the top,
the Black king isn't safe there. Besides that, Black allows for the queen
trade, which is extremely desirable for White.} (17... Bc5 $1 {Black shouldn't
have refrained from this active move. Now, it's not so clear how White should
be developing his kingside, while} 18. Nd2 {runs into the lovely} Bxf2+ $1 19.
Kxf2 Qc5+ {and both the White king and the c3-bishop are hanging, Black wins a
pawn as a result of this combination.}) 18. Be2 {This sacrifice is interesting,
as White gets to activate his bishop quickly, but it wasn't needed at all.} (
18. Qd2 $1 {Would have been a very simple solution, attacking both the queen
and the a5-knight, forcing the queen trade and reaching a winning endgame with
an extra pawn.}) 18... Qxg2 19. Bf3 Qg5 20. Qd2 {Now, White is asking for the
same endgame as he could get after 18.Qd2, just without one pawn!} Qc5 {
A very cool reply.} 21. Qe3 (21. Bxa5 $2 Qe5+ $1 {And Black pockets the
a1-rook!}) 21... Qb6 22. Qxb6 axb6 23. Nd2 {White reached a slightly more
pleasant endgame. His pieces are more active, the a5-knight is bad, which is
typical. Besides that, if we ever go Nb3 and Black takes, we'll get the open
a-file and a lot of play there. I've decided to cut short the remainder of the
game as it was very long and messy, it would have taken dozens of pages to
annotate all those moves, and they don't have much to do with the positions
typical of the Two Knights with 4.Ng5.1/2 (59) Socko,B (2627) - Bartel,M (2598)
Warsaw 2019} 1/2-1/2

