1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Nc3 Nf4 11. O-O Nxd3 12. cxd3 {Now we get this very
unusual, ugly-looking structure, which needs to be discussed in detail. We
have already talked a lot about it in the theoretical chapter, so I will quote
some things I had said there and will explain a bit more. Now, it's likely
Black will play ...c6-c5 at some point in order to grab more space and get the
better control over the d4-square and to improve his knight by means of ...
Nc6-d4. At that point, once ...c6-c5 is played, a very typical plan would be
to go b2-b3, Ba3 and start attacking the c5-pawn by means of Rc1, Ne4/a4, etc.
On the other hand, if Black doesn't go ...c6-c5, his a5-knight is out of play
and d3-d4 could be a possible idea, getting rid of the weak doubled pawn.} O-O
13. b3 c5 (13... Re8 {Is another possibility, trying to keep the pawn on c6,
which is discussed in another game (1/2) (29) Szczepanski,Z 2455 - Galliano,G
2419 ICCF email 2018. It's important that we shouldn't be looking at this
position from the perspective 'okay, so if he goes there, I go here. He takes,
I take. Check, I retreat.' In other words, it's not a forcing position.
Instead, we need to understand several ideas well, such as when to attack the
c5-pawn, when to push d3-d4, when to return the extra pawn, and so on.}) 14.
Ba3 Nc6 15. Ne4 Nb4 16. Bxb4 {Now that the knight is traded, many
opportunities for dynamic counterplay also disappear from Black's agenda.} cxb4
17. Re1 Bb8 18. Ng3 (18. Nc5 {Was even more ambitious, followed by Rc1, and
possibly the pawn sacrifice with d3-d4, aimed at shutting Black's bishops down.
} a5 {Suppose Black tries to do something on the queenside and activate the
bishop via a7.} 19. Rc1 Qd5 20. d4 $1 {This typical idea is worth remembering.}
exd4 21. Re4 {Now the d4-pawn falls, either now, or after} d3 22. Re3 {White
gets to collect the pawn, and while Black's bishops are definitely good, it's
definitely not going to suffice to fully compensate for the missing pawn.})
18... Qxd3 19. Nxe5 Bxe5 20. Rxe5 Be6 21. Re3 Qd4 22. Ne2 Qd6 23. d4 {White
managed to stabilize the position and keep the extra pawn. While Black did
manage to save his half a point, this has nothing to do with the opening -
White's opening was clearly a large success as he just got a healthy extra
pawn without allowing much of a counterplay. Let's now see how White could try
to make the better use of his pawn.} a5 24. h4 {I am not sure about this
decision. Levon wanted to make an escape square while possibly keeping the
options of harassing Black on the queenside open, but I think he could have
continued in a calmer manner.} (24. Rc1 {Instead, getting another piece in the
game looked natural. Now, Black's best bet involves trading the queenside
pawns.} a4 25. g3 {I like this way of creating an escape square better. It
might seem a little odd to weaken the long diagonal, but Black's won't ever
get any attack and we want to play Nf4, improving our knight and preparing
d4-d5. That is why the pawn needs to be on g3.} axb3 26. axb3 Bg4 27. Qd3 {
White is about to play Nf4, possibly Qc2-Qc7, or Qb5 to attack the b4-pawn.
Obviously, there's no immediate win and this is closer to a draw rather than
to a win, but the game is going on and Black will be struggling for many more
moves.}) 24... Rfd8 25. Qd2 a4 26. Rd1 (26. Re1 {It could be also interesting
to place the rook on e1! It might look a bit odd, as it looks like we want to
protect the d4-pawn to move the knight. But in fact, we are likely to be able
to play Nf4 after g2-g3 even without the rook on d1, as the e6-bishop would
hang and there might be threats over the e-file!} axb3 27. axb3 h6 28. g3 {
Nf4 is on cards, White keeps pushing. Besides that, Qc2-e4 could be a nice way
of regrouping the pieces and activating the queen, possibly preparing Qe5.})
26... axb3 27. axb3 Ra5 28. Rg3 Rf5 {Here it already feels like Black is
rather active, so it's barely possible to make much progress.} 29. Ra1 Bd5 30.
Qe3 h6 31. Rg4 Rf6 32. Ng3 Qe6 33. Qxe6 Bxe6 34. Re4 Bxb3 35. d5 Rb6 36. Rb1
Bxd5 37. Rexb4 {Finally, simplifications followed and the draw was agreed soon.
} Rxb4 38. Rxb4 Be6 39. f3 Ra8 40. Kh1 Rd8 41. Kg1 Ra8 42. Kh1 Rd8 43. Kg1 {
It's worth keeping in mind the idea of the pawn sacrifice d3-d4!, which
intends to close the position down a bit, but also,it can be the first step
towards winning that pawn back with Re1-e4, Rc1-c4 or something like that.
Besides that, it's worth noting that this extra d-pawn had to start rolling at
some point, so the plan of g2-g3, allowing for Nf4, followed by d4-d5, would
have been rather strong! 1/2 (43) Aronian,L (2765) - Ding,L (2805) Saint Louis
2019} 1/2-1/2

[Event "?"]
