1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. O-O Nf4 11. Nc3 Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O 13. Ne4 c5 {In my
opinion, the entire plan where Black goes ...c6-c5 quickly, isn't very correct,
because now White has a clear target.} (13... Bc7 {I know playing in such a
manner might not look appealing, but I think that might be Black's best bet.})
14. b3 Nc6 15. Ba3 Nb4 {Same mistake as in Aronian-Ding. White is very happy
about trading this knight!} (15... Bg4 {Playing dynamically is what Black
should be looking for. Now, something like} 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd4 18. Qd1 {
looks like a better chance for him. Objectively, White is still clearly better,
though! But, converting a position after such sample line} Rc8 19. Rc1 Ne6 {
won't be as easy. We will likely play something like Qf3, Rc4, and Rfc1,
targetting this c5-pawn. I like the fact White is playing without any risk
whatsoever, but it's still not very easy to breakthrough. Which is
understandable - how could you expect a forced win out of the opening or
something? :-)}) 16. Bxb4 cxb4 17. Re1 {This move might seem a bit mysterious
as the e4-knight is obstructing the e-file at the moment, but White is clearly
increasing his pressure on the e5-pawn. This is exactly the type of position
we're aspiring to get as Black has no counterplay here, in spite of the bishop
pair.} Bb7 (17... f6 18. d4 $1 {Again, we see this important idea. White
sacrifices a pawn, but kills the bishops and obstructs the d-file. He is also
very likely to get it back soon with Rc1-c4 or something.} exd4 19. Rc1 $16 {
White knights clearly aren't inferior to the bishops anymore, while Black's
pawns are rather weak, and now on top of that his kingside is weakened by ...
f7-f6.}) 18. Nxd6 Qxd6 19. Nxe5 Rfe8 20. Nc4 {White is ready to return one of
his extra pawns immediately, but the other one will stay safe. Hopefully,
eventually it'll get converted!} Qg6 21. Rxe8+ Rxe8 22. Qf1 {The queen might
appear to be somewhat passive on f1, but it's doing the job of protecting the
g2 and the d3-pawns. Now, we are about to go f2-f3. Possibly, later the queen
can get activated via f2.} h5 23. f3 Kh7 24. a3 {I am not sure about this move
as the b4-pawn was rather weak. It wasn't worth trading it.} (24. Rc1 {Would
have been a lot more natural, preparing Qf2, d3-d4, possibly intending to move
the knight to e5/d6 and invade over the c-file on c7.}) 24... Rd8 25. axb4 Rxd3
26. Ne5 Qb6+ {A few forced moves have been played, now White made a serious
mistake.} 27. Kh1 (27. Qf2 $1 {Would have kept serious advantage as White
wouldn't have lost the pawns.} Rxb3 (27... Qxb4 $4 28. Nxd3 $18 {Oops, that
was a free rook!}) 28. Qxb6 axb6 29. Nxf7 $16 {And Black keeps struggling to
save half a point.}) 27... Rxb3 {Now Black manages to get all the missing
pawns back.} 28. h3 Qxb4 {At this point, unfortunately, it is already too late
for the regrets, White needs to just agree to a draw. Later, some moves were
made and the evaluation still shifted back and forth for a few times, but the
most reasonable course of the events would have led to the trade of the
a7-pawn and the d2-pawn, resulting in a drawn position 3 vs 3 on the same side.
But, we did get to see a few important concepts, identical to those we saw in
the battle between Levon and Ding.  1: Attack the c5-pawn quickly;  2: Trade
the a3-bishop for the b4-knight to diminish Black's counterplay;  3: Possibly,
sacrifice the pawn with d3-d4 to tame the bishops and to try to get this pawn
back with Rc1-c4 or Re1-e4 in the future.} 1/2-1/2

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Szczepanski, Z. vs. Galliano"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C58"]
[PlyCount "57"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Nc3 Nf4 11. O-O Nxd3 12. cxd3 O-O 13. b3 Re8 {As I
explain in the theoretical chapter, the best way for Black to handle the
arising position involves keeping the pawn on c6 to stop the ideas like Ba3,
Rc1, Ne4/a4, etc. Instead, he should be slowly improving his position. But,
now we have additional ideas, such as pushing d3-d4 at the right moment.} 14.
Re1 {Attacking the e5-pawn cannot hurt.} f6 {Black makes the e5-pawn look
rock-solid, but this does have a disadvantage of weakening the king a bit.
It's not to say Black's move is a mistake, it's just that oftentimes good
moves achieve a lot, but also concede something!} 15. h3 {White prevents the ..
.Bg4 ideas. Just in case.} Be7 {A very precise move which attacks the d3-pawn
while also keeping the e-file closed so that the rook on e8 doesn't ever hang.}
(15... Bf8 $6 {As I explain in the theoretical chapter, the problem of this
move is that Black doesn't obstruct the e-file with it, which backfires in the
following line.} 16. d4 $1 exd4 17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. Nxd4 {White got rid of his
doubled pawn. Of course, he had also opened the position up quite a bit, but
it's debatable whether Black has full compensation.} c5 19. Nf3 Bb7 20. Ba3 Nc6
21. Na4 $1 {This is rather typical - the c5-pawn is under a lot of pressure,
while after} Nb4 22. Bxb4 cxb4 23. Nb2 {White is about to reroute the knight
to c4 and try to slowly but surely convert his extra pawn. Of course, Black's
bishops are rather strong, but there's nothing to attack, so his compensation
is only partial - and it's the 'stop the opponent from winning' kind of
compensation, not the 'fun' one.}) 16. d4 {White sacrifices a pawn in order to
close the position down and create some pawn weaknesses in Black's camp.} exd4
17. Na4 Ba6 18. d3 {To quote myself from the theoretical chapter: 'I am
quoting the correspondence game, so there's no wonder both players' moves were
close to perfection. As a result, we obtain the position where Black enjoys
the bishop pair, but now the position got closed down and we have the
semi-open c-file, a target on it and a lovely outpost on c5 for our knight.
The computer shows 0.00 or a tiny edge for White. While I cannot argue with
the evaluation, I still like White practically as it is a lot easier for him
to play: Black has weaknesses on the c-file while we don't have any. This is
the best position that Black can get in this 10...Nf4 line, in my opinion.'
Let's see how White tried to apply some pressure from now on and challenge
Black. Of course, it's a correspondence game, so it's hard to hope to win this
slightly more pleasant position, but it would give us a solid idea of where
the pieces should be going.} Bb5 19. Bd2 Nb7 (19... Bxa4 $2 {Would have been a
huge positional mistake.} 20. bxa4 {Now all the remaining White pieces are
better than the Black ones. We, likely, even want to take on a5 to leave Black
with that terrible dark-squared bishop. The c6-pawn is weak, same goes for the
pawn on d4. The c-file is semi-open, the f6-pawn makes the a2-g8 diagonal
weaker, Black's position is just terrible here. For example, if he makes some
random move, he might already lose material.} Kh8 21. Re4 {The d4-pawn is
falling, as the attempt to keep it afloat loses even more.} c5 $4 22. Bxa5 Qxa5
23. Qe2 {The pin over the e-file will yield White an extra piece.} Qc7 24. Re1
$18 {And White is winning that bishop and the game.}) 20. b4 {Now, the queen
is ready to jump on b3, the knight can travel to c4 via b2, possibly then
a2-a4 could be a reasonable plan to tuck the bishop all the way back on a6.}
Qd7 21. Re4 c5 22. Nxc5 Bxc5 (22... Nxc5 {Would have held as well, but from
the position of weakness, as Black would be a pawn down.} 23. Rxd4 Qe6 24. bxc5
Bxc5 25. Re4 {Sure, the bishops are active, but White is a pawn up and he's
playing for two results.}) 23. bxc5 Rxe4 24. dxe4 Nxc5 {Now, after some
precise simplifying operation, the position finally peters out into something
equal and drawish.} 25. Rb1 Bc6 26. Rb4 Ne6 27. Qb3 Bxe4 28. Rxd4 Qc6 29. a4 {
Okay, White wasn't able to win, or even present Black with any serious
problems in this game. But guys, this was a correspondence game and Black made
so many careful precise decisions here! Nevertheless, he was the one who had
to play very precisely in order to reach save harbours. So, I am totally
pleased with the type of positions we get after the opening. 1/2 (29)
Szczepanski,Z (2455) - Galliano,G (2419) ICCF email 2018} 1/2-1/2

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model games in 3...Nf6"]
[Black "Van Foreest, J. vs. Carlsen"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[ECO "C58"]
[PlyCount "89"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Nf6 4. Ng5 d5 5. exd5 Na5 6. Bb5+ c6 7. dxc6 bxc6 8.
Bd3 Nd5 9. Nf3 Bd6 10. Nc3 {The key theoretical idea in this repertoire versus
3...Nf6. Again, we want to take the e4-square under firm control as quickly as
possible. Later, we plan on following with Be2 and d2-d3, stabilizing the
situation, taking the e4-square under control and preparing the development of
our queenside pieces.} O-O 11. Be2 Nf4 {As I explain in the theoretical
section, this is exactly what White is looking for, as now he easily gets to
castle and keep his extra pawn. The fact that Black obtains the bishop pair
and deprives us of the e2-bishop doesn't really matter.} 12. O-O Bg4 13. d3
Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 f5 {Now it might appear as though Black were doing fine, as he
had established this unpleasant pin of our knight and is about to continue the
development with moves like ...Qf6 or ...Qc7, ...Rae8, possibly he'll try to
push ...e5-e4. What should White even do? But, this perception is incorrect.
In fact, White is much better... if he finds the right idea!} 15. h3 Bh5 16. g4
{An excellent solution by Van Foreest, as now White breaks the pin while also
establishing the rock-solid control over the e4-square.} fxg4 17. Ng5 {The
g4-pawn is pinned, so White doesn't need to rush to capture it.} Qd7 18. Nce4
Be7 19. Ng3 Bg6 20. Qxg4 Qxg4 21. hxg4 {At this point, I cut the opening
analysis short in the theoretical chapter and concluded with the words 'After
the slightly complicated heated battle that we just saw, White obtained a
healthy extra pawn and a nearly winning position. Unfortunately - at least
from our perspective as we fancy this line with White - he didn't manage to
develop his success and convert the advantage, as the World Champion showed
some extremely tenacious defense as well as a bit of luck and the game was
eventually drawn. Yet, this is something we call a huge opening success, as
White just kept his healthy extra pawn!' Let us now see how White could have
improved on his to either convert the advantage, or to at least pose a lot
more problems to Black.} c5 {Magnus is grabbing space while also improving the
a5-knight, as now the plan is ...Nc6-d4.} 22. N5e4 Nc6 23. Be3 Nd4 24. Rac1 {
So far everything looks good, both sides are making very logical moves.} (24.
c4 {A slightly strange suggestion of the computer does make a lot of sense,
actually. White might want to take on d4 at some point, but when his pawn is
on c2, ...cxd4 will fix that pawn as a target. Instead, when the pawn is on c4,
Bxd4 cxd4 will create White a protected passed pawn on c4. The problem is that
we are weakening the d3-pawn, but it doesn't really matter, as we are about to
take on d4 and close the d-file. Black, of course, can try to stop this idea
with ...Rfd8, but the weakness of the pawn doesn't tell at all.} Rfd8 25. Rad1
{As they say, weakness is something that can be attacked. And if it can't be,
then it's not a weakness! White can prepare plans like Nc3, Nge4, Nd5!, for
example, he is nearly winning (which isn't surprising given he's a healthy
pawn up).}) 24... Rac8 25. Kg2 c4 26. Bxd4 exd4 27. f3 (27. b3 $5 {Is a very
cool idea, which is rather difficult for any human being, of course. The point
is that we want Black to define the situation regarding the c4-pawn: it would
be great if he either moved it to c3, closing the c-file and depriving himself
of possible counterplay over it, or if he took, which opens the c-file and
enables us to challenge Black over it with moves like Rc4. The very beautiful
point is that the very obvious and natural answer} Ba3 {is dealt with in a
very beautiful way.} 28. dxc4 $3 {White just couldn't care less about that
exchange!} Bxc1 29. Rxc1 {Following with f2-f3, we easily stabilize the
position of the e4-knight. Now White has two pawns for the exchange. There are
no open files, d4 is weak, White's queenside pawns are potentially very
dangerous - Black is nearly lost. But, of course, this is not an easy decision
to make/an easy idea to find over the board, especially while facing the World
Champion and having a risk-free endgame against him!}) 27... Rc6 28. b3 {
A move later, Van Foreest finds this idea. Or, as will be seen on the next one,
half of it, as he didn't sacrifice an exchange.} Ba3 29. Rce1 (29. dxc4 $1 {
Would have again given White this overwhelming position.}) 29... cxd3 30. cxd3
a5 {Now Black's counterplay seems sufficient, and it's already barely possible
to hope to utilize that extra pawn.} 31. Rf2 Bc1 32. Nd2 {White decides to
give up the pawn in order to rearrange his pieces in a better way. But now the
position quickly steers towards some simplifications. It's not the fault of
White's last move, Black was already fine or nearly so, objectively.} Bxd3 33.
Nc4 Bf4 34. Ne5 Rc3 35. Nxd3 Rxd3 36. Nf5 g6 37. Re4 Bg5 38. Ne7+ (38. Nxd4 {
Would have been another way to force a draw. Black doesn't want to be a pawn
up, so he'll go for the following forcing line} Be3 39. Ne6 Bxf2 40. Nxf8 Rd2
$1 $11 {Black picks the a2-pawn and draws.} (40... Kxf8 $2 41. Kxf2 Rd2+ 42.
Re2 $16 {Is an endgame where White is still a pawn up and going to torture his
opponent for another hundred moves.})) 38... Kh8 39. Nc6 Be3 40. Re2 Rd1 41.
Nxa5 Rg1+ 42. Kh2 Rc1 {Now the idea is ...d4-d3, sacrificing the bishop, but
queening the pawn. Or Black can even play ...Bf4 first, followed by ...d4-d3,
so White removes the king away from that check.} 43. Kg2 {Apparently, Magnus
didn't want to play the endgame with an exchange for two pawns, so he took the
repetition.} Rg1+ (43... d3 44. R2xe3 d2 45. Rd4 d1=Q 46. Rxd1 Rxd1 $11 {
White definitely isn't risking to lose this! Even though, of course, Black
isn't, either.}) 44. Kh2 Rc1 45. Kg2 {A glorious fight! The opening idea shown
in this game (or shown in some others, but truly shown at a high level in this
one !) is brilliant, so it's high time we took advantage of it until it
becomes more popular! 1/2 (45) Van Foreest,J (2644) - Carlsen,M (2872) Wijk
aan Zee 2020} 1/2-1/2

